{"title_page": "John Neil Munro", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2011}}\n'''John Neil Munro''', Scottish journalist and biographer.\n\n==Background==\nJohn Neil Munro was born in [[Campbeltown]], [[Argyll and Bute]], and grew up in [[Stornoway]], [[Isle of Lewis]].\nHe studied Modern and Economic History at the [[University of Glasgow]] and then postgraduate journalism in [[Cardiff]].\n\n==Writing==\nIn the 1990s Munro worked as a journalist for various UK newspapers, including ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Glasgow Herald]]''.\n\n===Works===\n*''The Sensational Alex Harvey'' (Firefly Publishing, 2002), a biography of Glasgow rock star [[Alex Harvey (musician)|Alex Harvey]]\n*''Some People Are Crazy - The John Martyn Story'' ([[Birlinn (publisher)|Berlinn]], 2007. {{ISBN|1846970369}}; 2011, {{ISBN|9781846971655}}), biography of [[John Martyn]] with a foreword by Scots crime writer [[Ian Rankin]]<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/life-style/real-lives/how-herald-s-loss-was-music-s-gain-1.1065062 How Herald\u2019s loss was music\u2019s gain], [[Herald Scotland]], 1 November 2010</ref>\n*''When George Came to Edinburgh'' (Berlinn, 2010), [[George Best]]'s time at [[Hibernian F.C.]]\n*''Lust for Life! Irvine Welsh and the Trainspotting Phenomenon'' ([[Birlinn (publisher)|Polygon]], 2013, {{ISBN|9781846972423}}), [[Irvine Welsh]] and the impact of his first novel, ''[[Trainspotting (novel)|Trainspotting]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birlinn.co.uk/Lust-for-Life-The-Trainspotting-Phenomenon.html|title=Lust for Life! Irvine Welsh and the Trainspotting Phenomenon|publisher=Birlinn Ltd|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottishreviewofbooks.org/2013/09/talent-spotting/|title=Talent Spotting \u2013 Scottish Review of Books|website=www.scottishreviewofbooks.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munro, John Neil}}\n[[Category:Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:People from Campbeltown]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{Scotland-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2011}}\n'''John Neil Munro''', Scottish journalist and biographer.\n\n==Background==\nJohn Neil Munro was born in [[Campbeltown]], [[Argyll and Bute]], and grew up in [[Stornoway]], [[Isle of Lewis]].\nHe studied Modern and Economic History at the [[University of Glasgow]] and then postgraduate journalism in [[Cardiff]].\n\n==Writing==\nIn the 1990s Munro worked as a journalist for various UK newspapers, including ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Glasgow Herald]]''.\n\n===Works===\n*''The Sensational Alex Harvey'' (Firefly Publishing, 2002), a biography of Glasgow rock star [[Alex Harvey (musician)|Alex Harvey]]\n*''Some People Are Crazy - The John Martyn Story'' ([[Birlinn (publisher)|Berlinn]], 2007. {{ISBN|1846970369}}; 2011, {{ISBN|9781846971655}}), biography of [[John Martyn]] with a foreword by Scots crime writer [[Ian Rankin]]<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/life-style/real-lives/how-herald-s-loss-was-music-s-gain-1.1065062 How Herald\u2019s loss was music\u2019s gain], [[Herald Scotland]], 1 November 2010</ref>\n*''When George Came to Edinburgh'' (Berlinn, 2010), [[George Best]]'s time at [[Hibernian F.C.]]\n*''Lust for Life! Irvine Welsh and the Trainspotting Phenomenon'' ([[Birlinn (publisher)|Polygon]], 2013, {{ISBN|9781846972423}}), [[Irvine Welsh]] and the impact of his first novel, ''[[Trainspotting (novel)|Trainspotting]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birlinn.co.uk/Lust-for-Life-The-Trainspotting-Phenomenon.html|title=Lust for Life! Irvine Welsh and the Trainspotting Phenomenon|publisher=Birlinn Ltd|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref><ref>https://www.scottishreviewofbooks.org/2013/09/talent-spotting/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munro, John Neil}}\n[[Category:Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:People from Campbeltown]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{Scotland-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Martinevans123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Neil_Munro"}
{"title_page": "Internment", "text_new": "{{short description|Imprisonment or confinement of groups of people without trial}}\n{{hatnote|\"Concentration camp\" redirects here. For specific contexts see [[List of Gulag camps]] (1918-1991), [[Nazi concentration camps]] (World War II) and [[British concentration camps]] (Second Boer War). Not to be confused with [[Interment]] (burial).}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Boercamp1.jpg|thumb|[[Boer]] women and children in a [[British concentration camp]] in South Africa (1900\u20131902)]]\n{{Discrimination sidebar|state=collapsed}}\n'''Internment''' is the imprisonment of people, commonly in large groups, without [[criminal charge|charge]]s<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor=27879033|title=Human Rights Vol. 5, No. 3 \"INTERNMENT: {{sic|hide=n|nolink=y|reason=error in source|DENTENTION}} WITHOUT TRIAL IN NORTHERN IRELAND\"|journal=Human Rights|volume=5|issue=3|last=Lowry|first=David|publisher=ABA Publishing|year=1976|location=American Bar Association|pages=261\u2013331|quote=The essence of internment lies in incarceration without charge or trial.}}</ref> or [[indictment|intent to file charges]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y4c0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=without |title=Dance in Chains: Political Imprisonment in the Modern World |author-link=Padraic Kenney|last=Kenney |first=Padraic |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2017 |isbn= 9780199375745|location= |page=47 |quote=A formal arrest usually comes with a charge, but many regimes employed internment (that is, detention without intent to file charges)}}</ref> and thus no [[trial]]. The term is especially used for the confinement \"of enemy citizens in [[war]]time or of [[terrorism]] suspects\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/internment|title=the definition of internment|author=|date=|website=www.dictionary.com}}</ref> Thus, while it can simply mean [[imprisonment]], it tends to refer to preventive confinement rather than confinement ''after'' having been convicted of some crime. Use of these terms is subject to debate and political sensitivities.<ref name=euph>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/ombudsman/2012/02/10/146691773/euphemisms-concentration-camps-and-the-japanese-internment|title=Euphemisms, Concentration Camps And The Japanese Internment|author=|date=|website=npr.org}}</ref>\n\nInterned persons may be held in [[prison]]s or in facilities known as '''internment camps,''' also known as '''concentration camps'''. This involves internment generally, as distinct from the subset, the Nazi [[extermination camp]]s, commonly referred to as ''death camps.''\n\nInternment also refers to a [[neutral country]]'s practice of detaining [[belligerent]] [[armed forces]] and equipment on its territory  during times of war under the [[Hague Convention of 1907]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Second Hague Convention, 1907 |publisher=Yale.edu |url=http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/lawofwar/hague05.htm |accessdate=1 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009230811/http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/lawofwar/hague05.htm |archivedate=9 October 2012  }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] restricts the use of internment. Article 9 states that \"No one shall be subjected to [[Arbitrary arrest and detention|arbitrary arrest]], [[detention (imprisonment)|detention]] or [[exile]].\"<ref>[https://www.un.org/en/documents/udhr/index.shtml#a9 Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Article 9], United Nations</ref>\n\n== Defining internment and concentration camp ==\n[[File:Al-Magroon Concentration Camp.jpg|thumb|Ten thousand inmates were kept in [[El Agheila]], one of the [[Italian concentration camps in Libya]] during the [[Italian colonization of Libya]]]]\n[[File:Buchenwald Slave Laborers Liberation.jpg|thumb|Jewish slave laborers at the [[Buchenwald concentration camp]] near [[Weimar]] photographed after their liberation by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] on 16 April 1945. [[Elie Wiesel]] is seen second row from bottom, seventh figure from the left.]]\n\nThe ''[[American Heritage Dictionary]]'' defines the term ''concentration camp'' as: \"A camp where persons are confined, usually without hearings and typically under harsh conditions, often as a result of their membership in a group which the government has identified as dangerous or undesirable.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Concentration camp |publisher=American Heritage Dictionary |url=http://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=concentration+camp&submit.x=-664&submit.y=-210 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the first example of civilian internment may date as far back as the 1830s,<ref>James L. Dickerson (2010). ''Inside America's Concentration Camps: Two Centuries of Internment and Torture''. p. 29. Chicago Review Press {{ISBN|9781556528064}}</ref> the English term ''concentration camp'' was first used in order to refer to the ''reconcentrados'' (reconcentration camps) which were set up by the [[Spain under the Restoration|Spanish military]] in [[Cuba]] during the [[Ten Years' War]] (1868\u201378).<ref name=\"Columbia\">{{cite encyclopedia |date=2008 |title=Concentration Camp |encyclopedia=The Columbia Encyclopedia |edition=Sixth |publisher=Columbia University Press}}</ref> and similar camps were set up by the United States during the [[Philippine\u2013American War]] (1899\u20131902).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=Concentration Camps Existed Long Before Auschwitz |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/concentration-camps-existed-long-before-Auschwitz-180967049/ |work=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]] |date=2 November 2017}}</ref> The term ''concentration camp'' saw wider use as the [[British concentration camps|British set up camps]] during the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902) in South Africa for interning [[Boer|Boers]].<ref name=\"Columbia\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Documents re camps in Boer War |publisher=sul.stanford.edu |url=http://www-sul.stanford.edu/africa/boers.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609212833/http://www-sul.stanford.edu/africa/boers.html |archivedate=9 June 2007  }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, the arbitrary internment of civilians by the state reached its most extreme forms in the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[List of Gulag camps|Gulag system of concentration camps]] (1918-1991)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/anne-applebaum|title=Gulag: A History, by Anne Applebaum (Doubleday)|last=|first=|date=2004|website=The Pulitzer Prizes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> and the [[Nazi concentration camps]] (1933\u201345). The Soviet system was the first applied by a government on its own citizens.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Gulag consisted in over 30,000 camps for most of its existence (1918-1991) and detained some 18 million from 1929 until 1953,<ref name=\":1\" /> which is only a third of its 73 year lifespan. The Nazi concentration camp system was extensive, with as many as 15,000 camps<ref name=\"jewishvirtuallibrary1\">[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/cclist.html ''Concentration Camp Listing''] Sourced from Van Eck, Ludo ''Le livre des Camps.'' Belgium: Editions Kritak; and Gilbert, Martin ''Atlas of the Holocaust''. New York: William Morrow 1993 {{ISBN|0-688-12364-3}}. In this online site are the names of 149 camps and 814 subcamps, organized by country.</ref> and at least 715,000 simultaneous internees.<ref>{{cite book | last = Evans | first = Richard J.| title = The Third Reich in Power | year = 2005 | publisher = Penguin Group | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-14-303790-3}}</ref> The total number of casualties in these camps is difficult to determine, but the deliberate policy of [[extermination through labor]] in many of the camps was designed to ensure that the inmates would die of starvation, untreated disease and summary executions within set periods of time.<ref name=\"Marek Przybyszewski\">Marek Przybyszewski, [https://web.archive.org/web/20101022004220/http://www.historia.terramail.pl/opracowania/nowozytna/zamek_centrum_administracji.html IBH Opracowania \u2013 Dzia\u0142dowo jako centrum administracyjne ziemi sasi\u0144skiej (Dzia\u0142dowo as the centre of local administration)]. Internet Archive, 22 October 2010.</ref> Moreover, Nazi Germany established six [[extermination camp]]s, specifically designed to kill millions of people, primarily by [[Extermination camp#Gassing|gassing]].<ref name=\"Gellately2001\">{{cite book |author1=Robert Gellately |author2=Nathan Stoltzfus |title=Social Outsiders in Nazi Germany |year=2001 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-0-691-08684-2 |page=216 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1toqgWg8ROUC&q=forced+labor#v=snippet&q=forced%20labor&f=false }}</ref><ref>Anne Applebaum, [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2001/oct/18/a-history-of-horror/ A History of Horror], Review of \"Le Si\u00e8cle des camps\" by Jo\u00ebl Kotek and Pierre Rigoulot, [[The New York Review of Books]], 18 October 2001</ref>\n\nAs a result, the term \"concentration camp\" is sometimes conflated with the concept of an \"[[extermination camp]]\" and historians debate whether the term \"concentration camp\" or the term \"internment camp\" should be used to describe other examples of civilian internment.<ref name=euph/> \n\nThe former label continues to see expanded use for cases post-[[World_War_II |World War II]], for instance in relation to British camps in Kenya during the [[Mau Mau Uprising]] (1952\u20131960) for holding and torturing Kenyans,<ref>{{cite news |title=Museum of British Colonialism releases online 3D models of British concentration camps in Kenya |url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/museum-british-colonialism-releases-online-3d-models-british |work=Morning Star |date=27 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Mau Mau Rebellion |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/entertainment/books/1989/12/31/the-mau-mau-rebellion/186d8bdf-1d95-4b63-9147-c67f20d7eb0f/ |work=The Washington Post |date=31 December 1989}}</ref> and camps set up in [[Chile]] during the [[military dictatorship]] of [[Augusto Pinochet]] (1973\u20131990).<ref>{{cite news |title=Chilean coup: 40 years ago I watched Pinochet crush a democratic dream |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/07/chile-coup-pinochet-allende |work=The Guardian |date=7 September 2013}}</ref> Today, some media reports have claimed that as many as 3 million [[Uyghurs]] and members of other [[Islam in China|Muslim]] minority groups are being held in [[China]]'s [[Xinjiang re-education camps|re-education camps]] which are located in the [[Xinjiang]] region and which American news reports often label as ''concentration camps''.<ref>{{cite news |title=As the U.S. Targets China's 'Concentration Camps,' Xinjiang's Human Rights Crisis is Only Getting Worse |url=https://www.newsweek.com/xinjiang-uyghur-crisis-muslim-china-1398782 |work=Newsweek |date=22 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Uighurs and their supporters decry Chinese 'concentration camps,' 'genocide' after Xinjiang documents leaked |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/11/17/uighurs-their-supporters-decry-chinese-concentration-camps-genocide-after-xinjiang-documents-leaked/ |work=Washington Post |date=17 November 2019}}</ref> The camps were established under [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]]\u2019s [[Xi Jinping Core Administration|administration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/16/world/asia/china-xinjiang-documents.html|title='Absolutely No Mercy': Leaked Files Expose How China Organized Mass Detentions of Muslims|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=2019-11-16|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-11-16|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Stop Calling China's Xi Jinping 'President,' U.S. Panel Says|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/stop-calling-chinas-xi-jinping-president-u-s-panel-says-11573740000|date=14 November 2019|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Kate O\u2019Keeffe and Katy Stech Ferek}}</ref>\n\n==Examples==\n{{See also|List of concentration and internment camps}}\n*[[American Civil War prison camps|US Civil War]] (1861\u20131865)\n*[[British concentration camps|Boer War in South Africa]] (1900\u20131902)\n*[[Nazi concentration camps|German concentration camps before and during World War II]] (1933\u20131945)\n*Japanese internment of Europeans during [[World War II]] (\u22121945)\n*[[Internment of Japanese Americans|Japanese-American internment camps in World War II]] (1942\u20131946)\n*[[Japanese Canadian internment]] (1942\u20131949)\n*[[Cyprus internment camps]] (1946\u20131949)\n*Malayan [[New village]]<nowiki/>s as part of the [[Briggs' Plan]] during the [[Malayan Emergency]] (1950-1960)\n*[[Operation Demetrius]] in Northern Ireland (1971)\n*[[Omarska camp]] in Bosnia, 1992\n*[[Camp Bucca]] in Iraq (2003-2009)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalpolicy.org/images/pdfs/0422detention.pdf|title=Open Letter to Members of the Security Counsel Concerning Detentions in Iraq|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wnycstudios.org/podcasts/takeaway/segments/7674-largest-american-internment-camp-iraq-shuts-down|title=Largest American Internment Camp in Iraq Shuts Down {{!}} The Takeaway|website=WNYC Studios|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ritholtz.com/2014/12/how-u-s-torture-led-to-the-rise-of-isis/|title=How U.S. Torture Led to the Rise of ISIS|date=2014-12-23|website=The Big Picture|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n*[[Abu Ghraib prison]] in Iraq (1980-2014)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108388925325204831|title=Excerpts From Red Cross Report|date=2004-05-07|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-12-17|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/breaking-out-of-abu-ghraib|title=Breaking Out of Abu Ghraib|last=Anderson|first=Jon Lee|date=2013-07-26|access-date=2019-12-17|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=26496|title=Defense.gov News Article: Abuse Resulted From Leadership Failure, Taguba Tells Senators|website=archive.defense.gov|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n*[[Prisons in North Korea#Internment camps for political prisoners|North Korean prison camps]] (1948\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/north-korea-forced-labour-survivor-camp-15-hermit-kingdom-kim-jong-un-a7971926.html|title=Life inside a North Korea labour camp: 'We were forced to throw rocks at a man being hanged'|date=28 September 2017|work=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019141624/http://nkdb.org/bbs1/data/publication/Political_Prison_Camp_in_North_Korea_Today.pdf|title=Political Prison Camps in North Korea Today|last=|first=|date=2013-10-19|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*[[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] (2002\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/25/guantanamo-files-qahtani-salahi-torture|title=Guant\u00e1namo Bay files: Torture gets results, US military insists|last=Leigh|first=David|date=2011-04-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ama.com.au/sites/default/files/Prof_David_Isaacs_Speech.pdf|title=Professor David Isaacs Speech|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Slavery in Libya#Slavery in the post-Gaddafi era|Refugee detention centres]] in Libya (2011-present)<ref>{{Citation|title=EXCLUSIVE: Italian doctor laments Libya's 'concentration camps' for migrants|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aTgAdth2jmk&list=PLSyY1udCyYqCACdN9kIuTYlcsJhVqf2At&index=29|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infomigrants.net/en/post/13832/europe-s-apathy-toward-humanitarian-rescue-outrages-ngos|title=Europe's apathy toward humanitarian rescue outrages NGOs|date=2018-12-11|website=InfoMigrants|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2019/11/25/what-the-danish-lawrence-learned-in-libya/|title=What the 'Danish Lawrence' Learned in Libya (5th paragraph from the last one)|last=Wehrey|first=Frederic|date=2019-11-25|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/asithappens/as-it-happens-wednesday-edition-1.5198437/detained-migrants-killed-in-libya-airstrike-used-as-human-shields-doctors-without-borders-1.5198498|title=Detained migrants killed in Libya airstrike used as 'human shields'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediapart.fr/en/journal/international/021219/france-cancels-speedboats-delivery-libyan-coastguard|title=France cancels speedboats delivery to Libyan coastguard|last=Mediapart|first=La R\u00e9daction De|website=Mediapart|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*[[Xinjiang re-education camps|Uyghur re-education camps]] in China (2014\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=China is creating concentration camps in Xinjiang. Here's how we hold it accountable |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/china-is-creating-concentration-camps-in-xinjiang-heres-how-we-hold-it-accountable/2018/11/23/93dd8c34-e9d6-11e8-bbdb-72fdbf9d4fed_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=24 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi crown prince defends China's right to put Uighur Muslims in concentration camps |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/02/22/saudi-crown-prince-defends-chinas-right-put-uighur-muslims-concentration/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Anti-gay purges in Chechnya|Anti-gay detention camps]] in Chechnya (2017-present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/world/europe/at-least-100-gay-men-have-been-rounded-up-and-thrown-in-concentration-camps-in-chechnya/news-story/89553c2517a227ff20c57bef35cd78b3|title=The persecution of gay men in Chechnya has chilling similarities to the Third Reich|date=2017-04-19|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/01/15/russian-lgbt-network-reports-arrests-torture-and-deaths-part-chechnya-gay-purge-accusation|title=Is there a 'gay purge' in Chechnya? Rights group fears the worst|last=Stefanello|first=Viola|date=2019-01-15|website=euronews|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2017/04/11/chechnya-concentration-camp-homosexuals/|title=Report: Chechnya Opens 'Concentration Camp for Homosexuals'|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/E-8-2017-003094_EN.pdf|title=Question to the EU Commission by Matt Carthy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Trump administration migrant detentions]] as part of [[immigration detention in the United States|immigration detention]] in the United States (2018\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hignett |first1=Katherine |title=Academics rally behind Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez over concentration camp comments: 'She is completely historically accurate' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-concentration-camps-immigrants-detention-centers-southern-border-experts-1445483 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |date=June 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a27813648/concentration-camps-southern-border-migrant-detention-facilities-trump/|title=An Expert on Concentration Camps Says That's Exactly What the U.S. Is Running at the Border|last=Holmes|first=Jack|date=2019-06-13|website=Esquire|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Beorn |first1=Waitman Wade |title=Yes, you can call the border centers 'concentration camps,' but apply the history with care |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/posteverything/wp/2018/06/20/yes-you-can-call-the-border-detention-centers-concentration-camps-but-apply-the-history-with-care |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=August 30, 2019 |date=June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Michael Henry |title=Learning from the Germans: How We Might Atone for America's Evils |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/10/learning-from-the-germans-review-us-slavery |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |work=The Guardian |quote=Cages detaining refugees at the southern border are indeed 'concentration camps'.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Civilian internee]]\n*[[Extermination through labor]]\n*[[Extrajudicial detention]]\n*[[Gulag]]\n*[[House arrest]]\n*[[Labor camp]]\n*[[Kwalliso]] ([[North Korea]]'s [[Political prisoner|political]] [[penal labour]] [[Penal colony|colonies]])\n*[[Laogai]] (Chinese, \"reform through labor\")\n*[[Military Units to Aid Production]]\n*[[\"Polish death camp\" controversy]]\n*[[Prison overcrowding]]\n*[[Prisoner-of-war camp]]\n*[[Prisons in North Korea]]\n*[[Quasi-criminal]]\n*[[Re-education camp (Vietnam)]]\n*[[Re-education through labor]]\n*[[Remand (detention)]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Incarceration}}\n{{Segregation by type}}\n\n[[Category:Internments| ]]\n[[Category:Total institutions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Imprisonment or confinement of groups of people without trial}}\n{{hatnote|\"Concentration camp\" redirects here. For specific contexts see [[List of Gulag camps]] (1918-1991), [[Nazi concentration camps]] (World War II) and [[British concentration camps]] (Second Boer War). Not to be confused with [[Interment]] (burial).}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Boercamp1.jpg|thumb|[[Boer]] women and children in a [[British concentration camp]] in South Africa (1900\u20131902)]]\n{{Discrimination sidebar|state=collapsed}}\n'''Internment''' is the imprisonment of people, commonly in large groups, without [[criminal charge|charge]]s<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor=27879033|title=Human Rights Vol. 5, No. 3 \"INTERNMENT: {{sic|hide=n|nolink=y|reason=error in source|DENTENTION}} WITHOUT TRIAL IN NORTHERN IRELAND\"|journal=Human Rights|volume=5|issue=3|last=Lowry|first=David|publisher=ABA Publishing|year=1976|location=American Bar Association|pages=261\u2013331|quote=The essence of internment lies in incarceration without charge or trial.}}</ref> or [[indictment|intent to file charges]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y4c0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=without |title=Dance in Chains: Political Imprisonment in the Modern World |author-link=Padraic Kenney|last=Kenney |first=Padraic |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2017 |isbn= 9780199375745|location= |page=47 |quote=A formal arrest usually comes with a charge, but many regimes employed internment (that is, detention without intent to file charges)}}</ref> and thus no [[trial]]. The term is especially used for the confinement \"of enemy citizens in [[war]]time or of [[terrorism]] suspects\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/internment|title=the definition of internment|author=|date=|website=www.dictionary.com}}</ref> Thus, while it can simply mean [[imprisonment]], it tends to refer to preventive confinement rather than confinement ''after'' having been convicted of some crime. Use of these terms is subject to debate and political sensitivities.<ref name=euph>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/ombudsman/2012/02/10/146691773/euphemisms-concentration-camps-and-the-japanese-internment|title=Euphemisms, Concentration Camps And The Japanese Internment|author=|date=|website=npr.org}}</ref>\n\nInterned persons may be held in [[prison]]s or in facilities known as '''internment camps,''' also known as '''concentration camps'''. This involves internment generally, as distinct from the subset, the Nazi [[extermination camp]]s, commonly referred to as ''death camps.''\n\nInternment also refers to a [[neutral country]]'s practice of detaining [[belligerent]] [[armed forces]] and equipment on its territory  during times of war under the [[Hague Convention of 1907]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Second Hague Convention, 1907 |publisher=Yale.edu |url=http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/lawofwar/hague05.htm |accessdate=1 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009230811/http://www.yale.edu/lawweb/avalon/lawofwar/hague05.htm |archivedate=9 October 2012  }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] restricts the use of internment. Article 9 states that \"No one shall be subjected to [[Arbitrary arrest and detention|arbitrary arrest]], [[detention (imprisonment)|detention]] or [[exile]].\"<ref>[https://www.un.org/en/documents/udhr/index.shtml#a9 Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Article 9], United Nations</ref>\n\n== Defining internment and concentration camp ==\n[[File:Al-Magroon Concentration Camp.jpg|thumb|Ten thousand inmates were kept in [[El Agheila]], one of the [[Italian concentration camps in Libya]] during the [[Italian colonization of Libya]]]]\n[[File:Buchenwald Slave Laborers Liberation.jpg|thumb|Jewish slave laborers at the [[Buchenwald concentration camp]] near [[Weimar]] photographed after their liberation by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] on 16 April 1945. [[Elie Wiesel]] is seen second row from bottom, seventh figure from the left.]]\n\nThe ''[[American Heritage Dictionary]]'' defines the term ''concentration camp'' as: \"A camp where persons are confined, usually without hearings and typically under harsh conditions, often as a result of their membership in a group which the government has identified as dangerous or undesirable.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Concentration camp |publisher=American Heritage Dictionary |url=http://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=concentration+camp&submit.x=-664&submit.y=-210 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the first example of civilian internment may date as far back as the 1830s,<ref>James L. Dickerson (2010). ''Inside America's Concentration Camps: Two Centuries of Internment and Torture''. p. 29. Chicago Review Press {{ISBN|9781556528064}}</ref> the English term ''concentration camp'' was first used in order to refer to the ''reconcentrados'' (reconcentration camps) which were set up by the [[Spain under the Restoration|Spanish military]] in [[Cuba]] during the [[Ten Years' War]] (1868\u201378).<ref name=\"Columbia\">{{cite encyclopedia |date=2008 |title=Concentration Camp |encyclopedia=The Columbia Encyclopedia |edition=Sixth |publisher=Columbia University Press}}\n</ref> and similar camps were set up by the United States during the [[Philippine\u2013American War]] (1899\u20131902).<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=Concentration Camps Existed Long Before Auschwitz |url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/concentration-camps-existed-long-before-Auschwitz-180967049/ |work=[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]] |date=2 November 2017}}</ref> The term ''concentration camp'' saw wider use as the [[British concentration camps|British set up camps]] during the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902) in South Africa for interning [[Boer|Boers]].<ref name=\"Columbia\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Documents re camps in Boer War |publisher=sul.stanford.edu |url=http://www-sul.stanford.edu/africa/boers.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609212833/http://www-sul.stanford.edu/africa/boers.html |archivedate=9 June 2007  }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, the arbitrary internment of civilians by the state reached its most extreme forms in the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[List of Gulag camps|Gulag system of concentration camps]] (1918-1991)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/anne-applebaum|title=Gulag: A History, by Anne Applebaum (Doubleday)|last=|first=|date=2004|website=The Pulitzer Prizes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> and the [[Nazi concentration camps]] (1933\u201345). The Soviet system was the first applied by a government on its own citizens.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Gulag consisted in over 30,000 camps for most of its existence (1918-1991) and detained some 18 million from 1929 until 1953,<ref name=\":1\" /> which is only a third of its 73 year lifespan. The Nazi concentration camp system was extensive, with as many as 15,000 camps<ref name=\"jewishvirtuallibrary1\">[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/cclist.html ''Concentration Camp Listing''] Sourced from Van Eck, Ludo ''Le livre des Camps.'' Belgium: Editions Kritak; and Gilbert, Martin ''Atlas of the Holocaust''. New York: William Morrow 1993 {{ISBN|0-688-12364-3}}. In this online site are the names of 149 camps and 814 subcamps, organized by country.</ref> and at least 715,000 simultaneous internees.<ref>{{cite book | last = Evans | first = Richard J.| title = The Third Reich in Power | year = 2005 | publisher = Penguin Group | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-14-303790-3}}</ref> The total number of casualties in these camps is difficult to determine, but the deliberate policy of [[extermination through labor]] in many of the camps was designed to ensure that the inmates would die of starvation, untreated disease and summary executions within set periods of time.<ref name=\"Marek Przybyszewski\">Marek Przybyszewski, [https://web.archive.org/web/20101022004220/http://www.historia.terramail.pl/opracowania/nowozytna/zamek_centrum_administracji.html IBH Opracowania \u2013 Dzia\u0142dowo jako centrum administracyjne ziemi sasi\u0144skiej (Dzia\u0142dowo as the centre of local administration)]. Internet Archive, 22 October 2010.</ref> Moreover, Nazi Germany established six [[extermination camp]]s, specifically designed to kill millions of people, primarily by [[Extermination camp#Gassing|gassing]].<ref name=\"Gellately2001\">{{cite book |author1=Robert Gellately |author2=Nathan Stoltzfus |title=Social Outsiders in Nazi Germany |year=2001 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-0-691-08684-2 |page=216 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1toqgWg8ROUC&q=forced+labor#v=snippet&q=forced%20labor&f=false }}</ref><ref>Anne Applebaum, [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2001/oct/18/a-history-of-horror/ A History of Horror], Review of \"Le Si\u00e8cle des camps\" by Jo\u00ebl Kotek and Pierre Rigoulot, [[The New York Review of Books]], 18 October 2001</ref>\n\nAs a result, the term \"concentration camp\" is sometimes conflated with the concept of an \"[[extermination camp]]\" and historians debate whether the term \"concentration camp\" or the term \"internment camp\" should be used to describe other examples of civilian internment.<ref name=euph/> \n\nThe former label continues to see expanded use for cases post-[[World_War_II |World War II]], for instance in relation to British camps in Kenya during the [[Mau Mau Uprising]] (1952\u20131960) for holding and torturing Kenyans,<ref>{{cite news |title=Museum of British Colonialism releases online 3D models of British concentration camps in Kenya |url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/museum-british-colonialism-releases-online-3d-models-british |work=Morning Star |date=27 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Mau Mau Rebellion |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/entertainment/books/1989/12/31/the-mau-mau-rebellion/186d8bdf-1d95-4b63-9147-c67f20d7eb0f/ |work=The Washington Post |date=31 December 1989}}</ref> and camps set up in [[Chile]] during the [[military dictatorship]] of [[Augusto Pinochet]] (1973\u20131990).<ref>{{cite news |title=Chilean coup: 40 years ago I watched Pinochet crush a democratic dream |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/07/chile-coup-pinochet-allende |work=The Guardian |date=7 September 2013}}</ref> Today, some media reports have claimed that as many as 3 million [[Uyghurs]] and members of other [[Islam in China|Muslim]] minority groups are being held in [[China]]'s [[Xinjiang re-education camps|re-education camps]] which are located in the [[Xinjiang]] region and which American news reports often label as ''concentration camps''.<ref>{{cite news |title=As the U.S. Targets China's 'Concentration Camps,' Xinjiang's Human Rights Crisis is Only Getting Worse |url=https://www.newsweek.com/xinjiang-uyghur-crisis-muslim-china-1398782 |work=Newsweek |date=22 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Uighurs and their supporters decry Chinese 'concentration camps,' 'genocide' after Xinjiang documents leaked |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/11/17/uighurs-their-supporters-decry-chinese-concentration-camps-genocide-after-xinjiang-documents-leaked/ |work=Washington Post |date=17 November 2019}}</ref> The camps were established under [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]]\u2019s [[Xi Jinping Core Administration|administration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/16/world/asia/china-xinjiang-documents.html|title='Absolutely No Mercy': Leaked Files Expose How China Organized Mass Detentions of Muslims|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=2019-11-16|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-11-16|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Stop Calling China's Xi Jinping 'President,' U.S. Panel Says|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/stop-calling-chinas-xi-jinping-president-u-s-panel-says-11573740000|date=14 November 2019|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Kate O\u2019Keeffe and Katy Stech Ferek}}</ref>\n\n==Examples==\n{{See also|List of concentration and internment camps}}\n*[[American Civil War prison camps|US Civil War]] (1861\u20131865)\n*[[British concentration camps|Boer War in South Africa]] (1900\u20131902)\n*[[Nazi concentration camps|German concentration camps before and during World War II]] (1933\u20131945)\n*Japanese internment of Europeans during [[World War II]] (\u22121945)\n*[[Internment of Japanese Americans|Japanese-American internment camps in World War II]] (1942\u20131946)\n*[[Japanese Canadian internment]] (1942\u20131949)\n*[[Cyprus internment camps]] (1946\u20131949)\n*Malayan [[New village]]<nowiki/>s as part of the [[Briggs' Plan]] during the [[Malayan Emergency]] (1950-1960)\n*[[Operation Demetrius]] in Northern Ireland (1971)\n*[[Omarska camp]] in Bosnia, 1992\n*[[Camp Bucca]] in Iraq (2003-2009)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalpolicy.org/images/pdfs/0422detention.pdf|title=Open Letter to Members of the Security Counsel Concerning Detentions in Iraq|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wnycstudios.org/podcasts/takeaway/segments/7674-largest-american-internment-camp-iraq-shuts-down|title=Largest American Internment Camp in Iraq Shuts Down {{!}} The Takeaway|website=WNYC Studios|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ritholtz.com/2014/12/how-u-s-torture-led-to-the-rise-of-isis/|title=How U.S. Torture Led to the Rise of ISIS|date=2014-12-23|website=The Big Picture|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n*[[Abu Ghraib prison]] in Iraq (1980-2014)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108388925325204831|title=Excerpts From Red Cross Report|date=2004-05-07|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-12-17|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/breaking-out-of-abu-ghraib|title=Breaking Out of Abu Ghraib|last=Anderson|first=Jon Lee|date=2013-07-26|access-date=2019-12-17|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=26496|title=Defense.gov News Article: Abuse Resulted From Leadership Failure, Taguba Tells Senators|website=archive.defense.gov|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n*[[Prisons in North Korea#Internment camps for political prisoners|North Korean prison camps]] (1948\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/north-korea-forced-labour-survivor-camp-15-hermit-kingdom-kim-jong-un-a7971926.html|title=Life inside a North Korea labour camp: 'We were forced to throw rocks at a man being hanged'|date=28 September 2017|work=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019141624/http://nkdb.org/bbs1/data/publication/Political_Prison_Camp_in_North_Korea_Today.pdf|title=Political Prison Camps in North Korea Today|last=|first=|date=2013-10-19|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*[[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] (2002\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/25/guantanamo-files-qahtani-salahi-torture|title=Guant\u00e1namo Bay files: Torture gets results, US military insists|last=Leigh|first=David|date=2011-04-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ama.com.au/sites/default/files/Prof_David_Isaacs_Speech.pdf|title=Professor David Isaacs Speech|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Slavery in Libya#Slavery in the post-Gaddafi era|Refugee detention centres]] in Libya (2011-present)<ref>{{Citation|title=EXCLUSIVE: Italian doctor laments Libya's 'concentration camps' for migrants|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aTgAdth2jmk&list=PLSyY1udCyYqCACdN9kIuTYlcsJhVqf2At&index=29|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infomigrants.net/en/post/13832/europe-s-apathy-toward-humanitarian-rescue-outrages-ngos|title=Europe's apathy toward humanitarian rescue outrages NGOs|date=2018-12-11|website=InfoMigrants|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2019/11/25/what-the-danish-lawrence-learned-in-libya/|title=What the 'Danish Lawrence' Learned in Libya (5th paragraph from the last one)|last=Wehrey|first=Frederic|date=2019-11-25|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/asithappens/as-it-happens-wednesday-edition-1.5198437/detained-migrants-killed-in-libya-airstrike-used-as-human-shields-doctors-without-borders-1.5198498|title=Detained migrants killed in Libya airstrike used as 'human shields'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediapart.fr/en/journal/international/021219/france-cancels-speedboats-delivery-libyan-coastguard|title=France cancels speedboats delivery to Libyan coastguard|last=Mediapart|first=La R\u00e9daction De|website=Mediapart|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*[[Xinjiang re-education camps|Uyghur re-education camps]] in China (2014\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=China is creating concentration camps in Xinjiang. Here's how we hold it accountable |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/china-is-creating-concentration-camps-in-xinjiang-heres-how-we-hold-it-accountable/2018/11/23/93dd8c34-e9d6-11e8-bbdb-72fdbf9d4fed_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=24 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi crown prince defends China's right to put Uighur Muslims in concentration camps |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/02/22/saudi-crown-prince-defends-chinas-right-put-uighur-muslims-concentration/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Anti-gay purges in Chechnya|Anti-gay detention camps]] in Chechnya (2017-present)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/world/europe/at-least-100-gay-men-have-been-rounded-up-and-thrown-in-concentration-camps-in-chechnya/news-story/89553c2517a227ff20c57bef35cd78b3|title=The persecution of gay men in Chechnya has chilling similarities to the Third Reich|date=2017-04-19|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/01/15/russian-lgbt-network-reports-arrests-torture-and-deaths-part-chechnya-gay-purge-accusation|title=Is there a 'gay purge' in Chechnya? Rights group fears the worst|last=Stefanello|first=Viola|date=2019-01-15|website=euronews|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2017/04/11/chechnya-concentration-camp-homosexuals/|title=Report: Chechnya Opens 'Concentration Camp for Homosexuals'|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/E-8-2017-003094_EN.pdf|title=Question to the EU Commission by Matt Carthy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Trump administration migrant detentions]] as part of [[immigration detention in the United States|immigration detention]] in the United States (2018\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hignett |first1=Katherine |title=Academics rally behind Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez over concentration camp comments: 'She is completely historically accurate' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-concentration-camps-immigrants-detention-centers-southern-border-experts-1445483 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |date=June 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a27813648/concentration-camps-southern-border-migrant-detention-facilities-trump/|title=An Expert on Concentration Camps Says That's Exactly What the U.S. Is Running at the Border|last=Holmes|first=Jack|date=2019-06-13|website=Esquire|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Beorn |first1=Waitman Wade |title=Yes, you can call the border centers 'concentration camps,' but apply the history with care |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/posteverything/wp/2018/06/20/yes-you-can-call-the-border-detention-centers-concentration-camps-but-apply-the-history-with-care |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=August 30, 2019 |date=June 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Michael Henry |title=Learning from the Germans: How We Might Atone for America's Evils |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/10/learning-from-the-germans-review-us-slavery |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |work=The Guardian |quote=Cages detaining refugees at the southern border are indeed 'concentration camps'.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Civilian internee]]\n*[[Extermination through labor]]\n*[[Extrajudicial detention]]\n*[[Gulag]]\n*[[House arrest]]\n*[[Labor camp]]\n*[[Kwalliso]] ([[North Korea]]'s [[Political prisoner|political]] [[penal labour]] [[Penal colony|colonies]])\n*[[Laogai]] (Chinese, \"reform through labor\")\n*[[Military Units to Aid Production]]\n*[[\"Polish death camp\" controversy]]\n*[[Prison overcrowding]]\n*[[Prisoner-of-war camp]]\n*[[Prisons in North Korea]]\n*[[Quasi-criminal]]\n*[[Re-education camp (Vietnam)]]\n*[[Re-education through labor]]\n*[[Remand (detention)]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Incarceration}}\n{{Segregation by type}}\n\n[[Category:Internments| ]]\n[[Category:Total institutions]]\n", "name_user": "Pinchme123", "label": "safe", "comment": "delete unnecessary break", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internment"}
{"title_page": "List of vegetarian festivals", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Update|[[American Vegan Society]], which reported on 1/20/2018 that \"Over 120 VegFests in the United States are planned for 2018\", and this article only lists a few of them<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanvegan.org/vegfests.htm|title=Vegfests|website=Americanvegan.org|accessdate=23 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122071820/http://americanvegan.org/vegfests.htm|archive-date=22 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>|date=February 2019}}  \n{{advert|date=March 2018}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=January 2018}}\n{{Update|The article requires a COUNT of the number of such vegetarian festivals in each continent, and in the USA, for which the largest list of events seems to be presented.|date=October 2019}}\n}}\n\nThis is a global '''list of vegetarian and vegan festivals''', held in numerous locations around the planet, to promote veganism and/or vegetarianism among the public and to support and link individuals and organizations that practice, promote or endorse veganism or vegetarianism. Many of these events are also [[food festivals]] and/or [[music festivals]] and can also contain [[Educational entertainment|edutainment]]. Many events scheduled for Spring 2020 have been canceled because of the coronovirus pandemic.<ref>[https://www.happycow.net/events Happy Cow Vegan Festival Calendar, accessed 4/2/2020]</ref>\n\n== Africa ==\n=== Ghana ===\nVegfest 2015 was organized by the Vegetarian Association of Ghana.<ref name=\"wnyvegfest1\">{{cite web|title = WNY VegFest|url = http://www.wnyvegfest.com//|accessdate = 26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Asia ==\n=== Hong Kong ===\nHong Kong Vegfest started in 2013 organized by the Hong Kong Vegan Association. The festival organisers stipulate only vegan products be offered at the event by vendors. Admission is free to attendees.\n\n=== Indonesia ===\nThe first Bali Vegan Festival started in 2015 at Down To Earth (Ubud).<ref>{{cite web|title=Bali Vegan Festival|url=http://www.baliveganfestival.com/|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Japan ===\nThe Vegetarian Festival in Tokyo started in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tokyo Vegefood Fiesta|url=http://tokyo-vegefest.com/english/|website=Tokyo-vegefest.com|accessdate=21 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015041509/http://tokyo-vegefest.com/english/|archive-date=15 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nThe Philippines had its first 3-leg vegan festival \u2013 VegFest Pilipinas \u2013 in November and December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=VegFest Pilipinas|url=http://vegfestpilipinas.com/|website=Vegfestpilipinas.com|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 2017 event was two 2-day VegFest Pilipinas events at two different locations: from 18\u201319 November 2017 in Eastwood City, with 'Hair,' Pilita in concert, and VegFest Pilipinas in Chinatown the following weekend, 25\u201326 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vegfestpilipinas.strikingly.com/|title=VegFest Pilipinas on Strikingly|author=|date=|website=VegFest Pilipinas|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astigvegan.com/vegfest-pilipinas-2017/|title=Enriquez RG. VegFest Pilipinas 2017, A Recap of what happened. December 8, 2017|author=|date=|website=astigvegan.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>  The 2018 event again will be two 2-day VegFest Pilipinas events at two different locations: held one weekend from 8 am to 10 pm, 18\u201319 November 2018, at the BGC Arts Center in the Eastwood Central Plaza Shopping Mall, [[Quezon City]], [[Metro Manila]], [[Philippines]]; then again, the following weekend, 25\u201326 November 2017, in Lucky Chinatown, Binondo, [[Metro Manila]], [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Community/VegFestPilipinas/posts/|title=VegFest Pilipinas|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Singapore ===\n{{see also|EarthFest (SG)}}\nThe [[EarthFest (SG)|EarthFest Singapore]] had its debut in September 2015 and was sponsored by Singapore's [[Vegetarian Society (Singapore)|Vegetarian Society]] and others.\n\n=== Thailand ===\nThe Vegetarian Festival in Bangkok takes place each fall.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Vegetarian Festival|url=http://www.bangkok.com/whats-on-events/vegetarian-festival.htm|website=Bangkok.com|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{see also|Nine Emperor Gods Festival#Celebration in Thailand}}\nThis vegetarian festival is a nine-day period in October that celebrates the abstinence from meat during the ninth lunar month of the Chinese calendar.\n\n=== Vietnam ===\nThe Vegan Festival in Ho Chi Minh City takes place under the name Plant Power Celebration. The first one was held on 30 October 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/saigonveganfestival/|title=Saigon Vegan Festival|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Europe ==\n{{see also|Veganmania|VeggieWorld}}\n\n=== Belgium ===\nVegan Summer Fest is organized by BE Vegan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vegan Summer Fest|url=http://bevegan.be/vegan-summer-fest/|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Czechia ===\n[[Fluff Fest]] is an independent [[hardcore punk]] festival held each July in [[Rokycany]]. It is fully vegan, with catering provided by local animal rights organization Svoboda zv\u00ed\u0159at.<ref name=\"idioteq2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idioteq.com/a-look-inside-fluff-fest-exclusive-interview/|title=A Look Inside Fluff Fest!|first=Karol|last=Kami\u0144ski|publisher=Idioteq|date=28 January 2013|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Greece ===\nThe Vegan Life Festival (veganlife.gr) is a celebration in several Greek cities that presents vegan lifestyles, products, and practices through speeches, workshops, brochures, stalls with companies that provide vegan products, activities for children, and vegan food and sweets.  Admission open to the general public is free.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athensculturenet.com/en/event/vegan-life-festival-athens-2018|title=The Vegan Life Festival. Athens Culture Net. Accessed 12/26/2018|author=|date=|website=athensculturenet.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.veganlife.gr/|title=Veganlife|author=|date=|website=Veganlife|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>  YouTube video documentation is available.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWEP-c1VWkxt5Hcd6WQFSJw|title=Vegan Life Festival|author=|date=|website=YouTube|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Athens ====\nThe Vegan Life Festival has been held in several cities in Greece since November 5, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/%CF%84%CE%B5%CF%87%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%80%CE%BF%CE%BB%CE%B9%CF%82-%CE%B4%CE%AE%CE%BC%CE%BF%CF%85-%CE%B1%CE%B8%CE%B7%CE%BD%CE%B1%CE%AF%CF%89%CE%BD/vegan-life-festival-2016/178401362613208/|title=Vegan Life Festival 2016|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> The 2017 Vegan Life Festival was held in Athens on July 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.veganeventhub.com/event/vegan-life-festival-athens-2017/|title=Vegan Life Festival Athens 2017|author=|date=6 June 2017|website=veganeventhub.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> Buildout plans for nine Greek cities are being implemented gradually.  Organizers claim an attendance of greater than 18,000 visitors{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} at the 2018 Athens event, held at the Technopolis of the Municipality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaboutfestivals.gr/en/festivals/vegan-life-festival-2/|title=Vegan Life Festival 2018|author=|date=|website=allaboutfestivals.gr|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/veganlifefestival/vegan-life-festival-athens-2018/2058390741104185/|title=Vegan Life Festival Athens 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/veganlifefestival/events|title=Vegan Life Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vegevents.com/events/vegan-life-festival/|title=Vegan Life Festival|author=|date=|website=Veg Events|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.happycow.net/reviews/vegan-life-festival-athens-142276 Vegan Life Festival/  HappyCow.net.  Accessed 12/26/2018]</ref>\n\n==== Thessaloniki ====\nVegan Life Festival since 2017.  The 2018 was held May 20. 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://livingcrueltyfree.gr/en/vegan-life-festival-thessaloniki-2018/|title=VEGAN LIFE FESTIVAL THESSALONIKI 2018!|last=Zoe|date=11 May 2018|website=livingcrueltyfree.gr|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Chania ====\nThe Vegan Life Festival is scheduled to begin in Chania in 2019.\n\n==== Malta ====\nFrom August 5\u20136, 2018, the Vegan Life Festival was held at The Floriana Granaries in Malta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://veganguidegreece.com/vegan-life-festival/|title=Vegan Life Festival \u2013 Vegan Guide Greece|author=|date=|website=veganguidegreece.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Ireland ===\nDublin Vegfest is the Irish capital's vegan festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dublinvegfest.com/|title=22nd & 23rd September 2018 \u2013 Dublin Vegfest|website=dublinvegfest.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\nVeganFest Bologna is a vegan event in Europe which had more than 43,000 visitors in 2014. The event took place in [[Bologna]] in September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=VeganFest Bologna|url=http://www.veganfest.it/?page_id=5188|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\nFestival The Vegetarian Chance (www.thevegetarianchance.org) was founded in 2014 by journalist Gabriel Eschenazi and chef Pietro Leemann. First Festival in the world which includes a haute cuisine vegan contest with international chefs. Out of the contest the program includes show cookings, lectures, movies and a small market. Five editions were held in Milan and the last one in Turin (11-13 October). Next edition will be held on 24-25-26 October in Milan.\n\n=== Hungary ===\n\n==== Budapest ====\nThe XIX Vegetarian Festival was organized in August 2015 in [[Budapest]]. {{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n=== Netherlands ===\n[[File:Psyfi.jpg|thumb|[[Psy-Fi]] in Leeuwarden, Netherlands]]\n* [[VeggieWorld]] in [[Utrecht]], since 2016, vegan<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nos.nl/op3/artikel/2090859-gaat-het-nieuwe-vlees-het-oude-vlees-verslaan.html |title=Gaat het nieuwe vlees het oude vlees verslaan? |work=NOS |date=5 March 2016 |accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Nederlandse Vereniging voor Veganisme|VegFest]] in Utrecht, since 2014, vegan<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.trouw.nl/home/naakte-demonstranten-op-de-bres-voor-veganisme~afe5eb72/ |title=Naakte demonstranten op de bres voor veganisme |author=Amber Dujardin |work=Trouw |date=1 November 2014 |accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Veggie Fair in [[Lisserbroek]], since 2013, vegetarian<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.veganisme.org/event/veggiefair/ |title=VeggieFair 2016 |publisher=Nederlandse Vereniging voor Veganisme |accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following music festivals have made a conscious decision not to sell any meat on the festival terrain: Digital Festival (DGTL) in [[Amsterdam]] (since 2016),<ref name=\"verbaasd\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/nederland/artikel/4208246/festival-milkshake-verbaasd-over-heftige-reacties-op-vegetarisch |title=Festival Milkshake verbaasd over heftige reacties op vegetarisch eten |work=RTL Nieuws |date=27 May 2018 |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"UITgezocht\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nu.nl/uit/5291708/uitgezocht-worden-festivals-vleesvrij.html |title=UITgezocht: Worden festivals vleesvrij? |work=NU.nl |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref> Lente Kabinet in [[Oostzaan]] (since 2018),<ref name=\"UITgezocht\"/> Festival Milkshake in Amsterdam (since 2018),<ref name=\"verbaasd\"/><ref name=\"UITgezocht\"/> and [[Psy-Fi]] in [[Leeuwarden]] (starting from 2019).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.lc.nl/friesland/article24264539.ece |title=Psy-Fi verduurzaamt verder: volgende editie volledig vegetarisch |author=Yme Gietema |work=Leeuwarder Courant |date=13 March 2019 |accessdate=28 March 2019 |language=nl}}</ref> Organisers indicated their motives were sustainability and environmental protection; aside from dropping meat sales, they also focused on reducing the use of [[disposable product]]s and electricity.<ref name=\"verbaasd\"/><ref name=\"UITgezocht\"/>\n\n=== Spain ===\n\n==== Alicante ====\nVegan Fest [[Alicante]] has been organized by Alacant Rock since 2014. It is the only vegan festival in [[Spain]]. {{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n=== Portugal ===\n\n==== Lisbon ====\nVegan\u00e1rio Fest [[Lisbon]] (www.veganario.org) has been organized since 2008 by a group of friends in punk/hardcore community with help of local HareKrishna Community. It is the oldest of its kind in Lisbon and has been growing in the last years. \nIt gathers a lot of organizations and small businesses and important people in the vegan community to talk about and spread veganism.\n\nThe music slowed down, it is more open to all the people. It is growing: Approximately 300/600px until 2014, more than 1500 in 2015, over 2000 in 2016, and more than 3500 in 2017.\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n==== ''England'' ==== \n===== Birmingham =====\nBirmingham Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\">[https://www.viva.org.uk/festivals/contact#contact Contact form for VIVA's Vegan Festivals, which supplement previously existing vegan festivals in UK]</ref>\n\n===== Bournemouth =====\nApproximately 90 stalls, talks, and food.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511025420/http://www.dorsetveganevents.co.uk/bournemouthveganfair.html|title=Bournemouth Vegan Fair \u2013 17 & 18 June 2017 \u2013 Dorset Vegan Events|author=|date=11 May 2017|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Bradford =====\nBradford Vegan Festival was held on Sunday 2 September 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Community/veganfestivaluk/posts/|title=Bradford Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> and again will be held in September 2019.\n\n===== Brighton =====\nBrighton Vegan Festival took place on Saturday 14 July 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/brightonveganfestival2018/|title=Brighton Vegan & Ethical Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> and again will occur in July 2019.\n\nBrighton Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Bristol, Brighton, London =====\n{{see also|Vegfest (UK)}}\nVegfestUK Bristol was held May 26\u201327 at Ashton Gate stadium, Ashton Road, BS3 2EJ Bristol, United Kingdom.  Standard advance day tickets are \u00a311.00 (adults), \u00a36.00 (concessions) [including booking fees] and \u00a35.50 (children)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/ashton-gate-stadium/vegfestuk-bristol-2018/713055975565881/|title=VegfestUK Bristol 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://accounts.google.com/ServiceLogin?passive=1209600&osid=1&continue=https://plus.google.com/communities/111382870961138557305&followup=https://plus.google.com/communities/111382870961138557305|title=Sign in \u2013 Google Accounts|website=accounts.google.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> but was actually held from October 27\u201328, 2018, at Olympia London. The announcement was made in September 2018, citing higher than expected costs and broad availability of good quality vegan food in Bristol, that VegFestUK organizers would not schedule another event in Bristol for 2019 or 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/ashton-gate-stadium/vegfestuk-bristol-2018/713055975565881/|title=VegfestUK Bristol 2018|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/vegfestexpress/2018/09/statement-on-the-future-of-vegfestuk-bristol|title=Statement on the future of VegfestUK Bristol|website=Statement on the future of VegfestUK Bristol|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> but that VegFestUK would continue to hold annual events elsewhere.\n\n===== Coventry =====\nCoventry Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Liverpool =====\nLiverpool Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== London =====\nJustVShow is held in July<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.justvshow.co.uk|title=Just V Show \u2013 Vegan & Vegetarian Show in London & Glasgow|website=Just V Show}}</ref> and [[Vegfest (UK)|Vegfest]] (14,500 visitors in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vegfest.co.uk/our-events/|title=Our events|website=VegfestUK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>) is held in autumn. Plant Powered Expo takes place for the first time in February 2020, just after [[Veganuary]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plantpoweredexpo.co.uk/|title=Home|website=Plant Powered Expo|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nLondon Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Kent =====\nMaidstone Vegan Festival took place for the second time on July 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maidstoneveganfestival.co.uk/|title=Maidstone Vegan Festival|website=Maidstoneveganfestival.co.uk|language=English|access-date=2017-03-19}}</ref>\n\n===== Newcastle =====\nNewcastle Vegan Festival took place on Sunday 1 July 2018 from 10:30 AM \u2013 4:30 PM UTC+01 in Newcastle upon Tyne.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/newcastleveganfest|title=Newcastle Vegan Festival|website=https://www.facebook.com/newcastleveganfest|language=English|access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/Causes/newcastle-vegan-festival-2018-vegan-awards/1645580835499105/|title=Newcastle VEGAN Festival 2018 + Vegan Awards|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Nottingham =====\nNottingham Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Sheffield =====\nSheffield Vegan Festival will be held on Saturday 15 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/sheffieldveganfestival/|title=Sheffield Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Scotland'' ====\n===== Aberdeen =====\nAberdeen Vegan Festival took place on Sunday 8 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/aberdeenveganfest/|title=Aberdeen Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Cardiff =====\nCardiff Vegan Festival occurred on Saturday 22 September 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/cardiffveganfestival/|title=Log In or Sign Up to View|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Edinburgh =====\nEdinburgh Vegan Festival took place on Sunday 19 August 2018 in Murrayfield Stadium.  This is the first annual Edinburgh Vegan Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/edinburghveganfest/|title=Edinburgh Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://veganfestival.co.uk/edinburgh-schools-vegan/|title=Edinburgh Schools Have Gone Plant Based|author=|date=25 April 2018|website=veganfestival.co.uk|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Glasgow =====\nJustVShow is held in July.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  The Glasgow JustVShow is scheduled for July 2\u20133, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justvshow.co.uk/scotland/|title=Just V Show \u2013 Vegan & Vegetarian Show in Glasgow|website=Glasgow, Scotland, Just V Show}}</ref>  In 2018 the JustVShow is co-locating with The Allergy & Free From Show Scotland 2018.\n\n== North America ==\n\n=== Canada ===\n====Alberta====\n=====Edmonton=====\nThe first Edmonton VegFest was held from 10 am to 6 pm on September 30, 2018, at the Ritchie Community League Hall and Outdoor Park, \n7727 98th Street Northwest, Edmonton, Alberta T6E 5C9. Admission was free. The nonprofit organization coordinating and hosting this annual event was Vegans and Vegetarians of Alberta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/life/food/new-vegetable-festival-launches-in-ritchie-with-fun-shopping-and-greens|title=New Edmonton vegetable festival in Ritchie offers shopping, greens \u2013 Edmonton Journal|first1=Liane|last1=Faulder|date=20 September 2018|website=edmontonjournal.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.todocanada.ca/vegfest-edmonton/|title=VegFest Edmonton \u2013 Ritchie Community League Hall & Park, 7727 98 Street Northwest, Edmonton|author=|date=|website=To Do Canada|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoedmonton.com/event/vegfest/|title=VegFest|date=22 August 2019|website=InfoEdmonton|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/vegfest-edmonton-2018/182759825765331/|title=VegFest Edmonton 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/vvoaclub/|title=Vegans and Vegetarians of Alberta|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Ontario====\n=====Guelph=====\nVegfest Guelph<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vegfestguelph.ca|title=Vegfest Guelph|website=Vegfest Guelph}}</ref> is an annual festival. The 2016 festival took place on Sunday, September 25, 2016, at Goldie Mill and the Guelph Youth Music Centre.\n\n=====Toronto=====\nThe Vegetarian Food Festival in Toronto attracted over 50,000 attendees in 2014 and featured more than 120 food and product vendors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vegetarian Food Festival Toronto|url=http://veg.ca/festival|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> It is a free public festival held at Harbourfront Centre by the [[Toronto Vegetarian Association]] in Toronto the second weekend of every September.  It was first held in 1985 and is believed to be the largest and longest continuously running vegetarian food festival in North America, and is credited with having inspired the broad vegetarian food festival movement in the United States, which was first copied by the long-running [[Boston Vegetarian Society|Boston Vegetarian Food Festival]].\n\nThe Toronto Vegan Food and Drink Festival, a fully vegan food and drink festival in the city, strives to present an all vegan experience featuring comfort food, craft brews, wine and spirits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vegan Food and Drink Festival Toronto|url=https://www.vegandrinkfest.com/toronto/}}</ref>\n\nThe Toronto Vegan Expo (formerly known as Vegan Spring Expo) was a free annual vegan festival that took place in Toronto from 2011 to 2013 and had an attendee record of 1500 in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.veganspringexpo.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222123329/http://www.veganspringexpo.com/|url-status=dead|title=502 Bad Gateway nginx openresty 185.15.56.1|archivedate=22 December 2014|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=====Niagara (St. Catharines)=====\nNiagara VegFest began in 2012 and is an annual event that takes place in downtown St. Catharines, Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|title=Niagara VegFest|url=http://niagaravegfest.com|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> The 2012 Niagara VegFest closed with a screening of [[Vegucated]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getvegucated.com/ |title=Vegucated |publisher=Getvegucated.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-17}}</ref>\n\n=====Ottawa=====\nThe first Ottawa Veg Fest was held in 2009, and was organized by the National Capital Vegetarian Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ottawa Veg Fest|url=http://vegfest.ca|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=====Kingston=====\nThe first Kingston Veg Fest was held in the fall of 2016. It is being organized by the Kingston Vegetarian Network<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingston Vegetarian Network|url=http://kingstonveg.ca |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=====Mississauga=====\nThe first Mississauga Veg Fest was held in May 2018. Mississauga Veg Fest was the city's first vegan festival! Over 60 vendors were in attendance to showcase the GTHA's finest veg-based food, drink, clothing & accessories, products, advocate groups and children's activities. It is being organized by a private volunteer committee<ref>{{cite web|title=Mississauga Veg Fest|url=https://mississaugavegfest.ca |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Muskoka=====\nMuskoka VegFest had its inaugural event on Aug 11, 2018. 68 Vendors and various speakers drew in a crowd of just under 5000 people.  The annual event is run by a private volunteer committee.  It is a not-for profit event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Muskoka Veg Fest|url=http://muskokavegfest.com|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Quebec====\n=====Montreal=====\nThe first Montreal Vegan Festival was held from September 26\u201327, 2014 and welcomed over 5,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://festivalveganedemontreal.com/2014en/|title=2014\u2013 Montreal Vegan Festival \u2013 September 26\u201327, 2014|website=2014\u2013 Montreal Vegan Festival}}</ref>\n\n====M\u00e9xico====\n\n=====Baja California=====\n\nTijuana Veggie Fest 2018 was held on July 6, 2018, in Centro Cultural Tijuana (CECUT), Paseo de los H\u00e9roes No. 9350, Zona Urbana R\u00edo, Tijuana, Baja California.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/tjveggiefest/tijuana-veggie-fest-2018/148377289195497/|title=Tijuana Veggie Fest 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>  Tijuana Veggie Fest 2019 is tentatively scheduled for June 29, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/VeggieFestTijuana/|title=Tijuana Veggie Fest 2019 Facebook page. Accessed December 26, 2018