{"title_page": "Riyadh International Book Fair", "text_new": "{{short description|Book-selling event in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n<!-- Do not remove this line! -->{{Infobox convention\n|name=Riyadh International Book Fair\n|status=Active|genre=Multi-genre\n|venue=[[Riyadh International Convention & Exhibition Center]]\n|location=[[Riyadh]]\n|country=[[Saudi Arabia]]\n|organizer=[[Ministry of Culture (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Arabian Ministry of Culture]]<ref name=fatwa />\n|frequency=Annually, in mid-March to April\n|begins = Tuesday (an opening day, not open to the general public)<ref name=alarabiya_2011 />\n|ends = Saturday (the 10th day, not counting the opening day){{efn|Always stated to end on Saturday; because Tuesday is not open to the public, it is often stated to open on Wednesday.<ref name=Sudhnoti>{{cite web |title=Visit to International Book Fair: #Riyadh |url=https://publicawaz.blogspot.com/2015/03/visit-to-international-book-fair-riyadh.html |website=Voice of Sudhnoti |date=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://accucoms.com/events/riyadh-international-book-fair/ |website=ACCUCOMS}}</ref><ref name=2006_1_jeans/>}}\n|website= [[uniform resource locator|URL]] has changed<ref name=comsci />\n*2006\u20132007: https://www.riyadhbookfair.org/<ref>The [[Internet Archive]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20051101000000*/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/ 2006 website], [https://web.archive.org/web/20060622042039/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/English/index.htm mostly unarchived English version], [https://web.archive.org/web/20070210002607/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/ February 2007 website]; after that, it's held by [[domain squatter]]s.</ref>\n*2008\u20132019: https://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/<ref name=comsci /><ref>{{cite web |title=Wayback Machine |author=[[Internet Archive]] |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org.sa/ |website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n*2020: https://engage.moc.gov.sa/book-fair<!--OK, probably don't need a citation for this yet{{cn|date=January 2020}}-->\n|logo              = Riyadh International Book Fair 2019 logo.png<!--file must be downloaded and uploaded by a logged-in user using the \"upload file\" link in the sidebar-->\n|logo_alt          = \n|logo_caption      = ''Logo of the 2019 fair''\n|logo_size         = \n|image             = Riyadh-IBF-2020-logo-300x98.png\n|image_size        = 1.5\n|alt               = \n|caption           = ''Logo of the 2020 fair''}}\n\nThe '''Riyadh International Book Fair''' is an annual [[book fair]] in [[Saudi Arabia]]. It lasts 11 days<ref name=rocket /> and regularly attracts over a half million visitors (it is not the largest fair in the [[Middle East and North Africa|MENA]] region,<ref name=size>{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Mark |title=As western publishers look the other way millions attend Arab book fairs in February |url=https://thenewpublishingstandard.com/as-western-publishers-look-the-other-way-millions-attend-arab-book-fairs-in-february/ |website=The New Publishing Standard |date=24 February 2019}}</ref> contrary to some claims<ref>{{cite news |title=Riyadh International Bookfair 2018 |url=https://www.eyeofriyadh.com/events/details/riyadh-international-bookfair-2018 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=Eye of Riyadh |date=1 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301211303/https://www.eyeofriyadh.com/events/details/riyadh-international-bookfair-2018 |archive-date=1 March 2018 }}</ref>). The fair is used to showcase Saudi government policy,<ref name=economist /><ref name=memorandum /> and it has been a locus of political power struggles with the government.<ref name=fatwa /> Hundreds of publishers sell pre-approved books,<ref name=rocket/> and some black-market books.<ref name= memorandum /> Writers take part in literary events. Invited speakers and the public discuss intellectual and social issues. Disagreements sometimes go beyond the bounds of debate, with speakers being shouted down and surrounded by protestors,<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> and arrests of speakers and protestors;{{efn|See the [[#history_2011|account in this article of the 2011 fair]] and [[#history_2018|that of the 2018 fair]] (as well as some of the linked articles on authors and public intellectuals).}} physical assaults are rare but not unknown.<ref name=CPJ />\n\nThe fair is a focus for political conflict in Saudi Arabia,<ref name=fatwa /> though some local media sources deny there is political debate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Suleiman Shoqiran |first1=Fahad |title=Debate over intellectual freedoms and rights in Saudi Arabia |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/views/news/middle-east/2018/03/25/Debate-over-intellectual-freedoms-and-rights-in-Saudi-Arabia.html |work=english.alarabiya.net |date=25 March 2018 |language=en}} (author with close ties to Saudi-government-controlled media, '''not an independent source''')</ref> The fair is organized by the [[Ministry of Culture (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Culture and Information]],<ref name=fatwa /><ref name=2008_jeans /> and has been regulated by the [[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)|religious police]]; the two have clashed at the fair,<ref name=numbers /><ref name=fatwa /><ref name=2008_jeans /> and religious police have been limited to more advisory roles.<ref name=\"SW2010\" /> Some Saudi clerics issued a [[fatwa]] criticizing the book fair during the 2012 fair.<ref name=fatwa /> Journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] said of the intellectual climate: \"It's like [[McCarthyism]] in the 1950s\".<ref name=CPJ />\n\nThe fair has been both praised and criticized domestically for providing books and cultural activities which are hard to come by in Saudi Arabia,<ref name=fatwa /> and criticized internationally for selling [[Antisemitism|anti-semitic]] and [[Misogyny|misogynistic]] books.<ref name=JerusalemPost /><ref name=US-backed /><ref name=2016_report /> Parts of the fair are gender-segregated.{{efn|See the [[#restrictions_on_visitors|discussion in this article of restrictions on visitors]].}}\n\n== Activities ==\nThe fair aims to provide freer access to literature, and a large selection is available,<ref name=protest /> including some books banned or not usually sold in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=2006_1_jeans /><ref name=memorandum /> Protests about material at the fair are common.<ref name=protest /> While authorities pre-censor the books, they have sometimes confiscated previously-approved books during the fair.<ref name=rocket>{{cite web |last1=Omran |first1=Ahmed Al |title=Edgy Saudi Bans Local Publisher |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/middleeast/2014/03/12/edgy-saudi-bans-local-publisher/ |website=Wall Street Journal |date=12 March 2014}}</ref> Publishers say that they will be banned from the Saudi market if they speak openly about books being banned.<ref name=protest /> The book fair has become a topic of political controversy, praised for providing access to useful books and supporting culture and society, and criticized for insufficient, excessive, or inappropriate censorship.<ref name=fatwa>{{cite web |title=Saudi Clerics Criticize Book Fairs, Culture Events in the Country |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/saudi-clerics-criticize-book-fairs-culture-events-country |website=MEMRI |language=en}}</ref><ref name=protest /><ref name=JerusalemPost /> The traditional rarity of public events in Saudi Arabia, and the children's activities, help make it popular with the general public.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nApart from book sales, the fair also hosts writers, poets and intellectuals, who meet with the public. They sign books, take part in public discussion panels,<ref name=memorandum /> and give public lectures.<ref name=Freitag /> Authors give public readings of their works, without public discussion of the readings.<ref name=memorandum />\n\n<!--Historically, women were only allowed to attend during two designated half-days.<ref name=\"events\"/> no date given; 2009 date given by strong implication contradicts multiple more reliable sources.--> \nThere have been some gender-based <span id=\"restrictions_on_visitors\">restrictions on admission</span>: some times have been men-only,<ref name=2009_jeans>{{cite web |last1=Al Omran |first1=Ahmed |title=Riyadh Book Fair '09 |url=https://saudijeans.org/2009/03/07/riyadh-book-fair-09/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=7 March 2009}}</ref> others \"families-only\", meaning that single men may not enter.<!--Or single-gender groups; I [HLHJ] don't think single women or groups of women are allowed at all, but have found no explicit source on this--><ref name=2006_1_jeans>{{cite web |title=Exclusive: Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://saudijeans.org/2006/02/25/exclusive-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060301055132/http://saudijeans.blogspot.com/2006/02/exclusive-riyadh-international-book.html|archive-date=1 March 2006| url-status=dead <!-- seems to redirect oddly; even some archive copies slowly redirect --> |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=25 February 2006}}</ref> From 2008 to 2011 inclusive, there were four men-only evenings; the other times were open \"for all\", meaning only mixed-gender family groups (there were no women-only times).{{efn|See the [[#history|accounts in this article of individual years; there weren't women-only times<ref name=comsci/>]]}} In 2012, there were no segregated admission times, and men and families would be allowed to attend simultaneously for the first time.<ref name=ghana /><ref name=Freitag /> In practice, most schoolgroups attend in the mornings, and most of the evening visitors are men; women and families are common all day.<ref name=Freitag />\n\nSeparately, there are gender-based restrictions on activities within the fair. Book-signings and discussion panels generally have gender-segregated spaces.<ref name=memorandum>{{cite web |last1=Aldosari |first1=Hala |title=Riyadh Book Fair 2016: A Political Memorandum from New Rulers |url=https://agsiw.org/riyadh-book-fair-2016-a-political-memorandum-from-new-rulers/ |website=Arab Gulf States Institute in Washington |date=24 March 2016}}</ref> According to local media, men have been prevented from getting their books signed by female authors.<ref name=protest /><ref name=autograph>{{cite news |title=Saudi men arrested for seeking female writer's autograph - CNN.com |url=https://www.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/03/07/saudi.arabia.autograph/ |work=www.cnn.com}}</ref> \"If the author is a woman [male] people have to have their book signed through a third party so as to prevent her direct contact with the public\", the head of the Hai\u02bea at the fair explained in 2009.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> Female panelists participate in panels by intercom, which a panelist from outside Saudi Arabia found disconcerting.<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> Women listen to lectures from a balcony, when not giving them.<ref name=Freitag /> The book fair has been criticized for supporting [[Women's rights in Saudi Arabia#Sex segregation|gender mixing]].<ref name=fatwa/> In the childrens' areas, only women and children are allowed; men are strictly excluded.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /><ref name=SW2010/>\n\nThe fair has been patrolled by the [[Commission for the Promotion of Virtue and Prevention of Vice]] (Hai\u02bea, religious police), who enforce gender segregation and advise on dress.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> Men have been prevented from entering if their hair is too long.<ref name=protest /> Some of the men who have interrupted events have claimed to be members of the religious police.<ref name=\"events\">{{cite news |last1=Ammar |first1=Hassan |title=Saudi Arabia welcoming more cultural events |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29571507/ns/world_news-mideast_n_africa/t/saudi-arabia-welcoming-more-cultural-events/ |work=msnbc.com |agency=Associated Press |date=7 March 2009 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA book competition awards prizes of 100,000 Saudi Arabian riyals (roughly US$26,000, {{as of|lc=yes|2016}}). Until 2016, winners were selected by the [[Ministry of Information (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Information]], but in 2016 a group of [[King Saud University]] professors were made responsible.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nTemporary television studios are set up within the fair, and interview authors, and there are many roaming reporters and camera teams, but personal cameras were banned, {{as of|2012|lc=yes}}.<ref name=Freitag /><!-- so that's why this article has no photos... -->\n\n==Political context==\n[[File:Hesbah.jpg|thumb|right|A member of the religious police (right) speaking with member of the public in 2006. Religious police at the fair have worn plainclothes, including the [[Bisht (clothing)|bisht]] and unbound [[Keffiyeh|ghotra]] shown here.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Caryle |title=Saudi Arabia's Shifting Islamic Landscape |url=https://pulitzercenter.org/reporting/saudi-arabias-shifting-islamic-landscape#slideshow-15 |website=Pulitzer Center |language=en |date=3 April 2014}}</ref><!--not independent, but also supports: <ref name=repub>{{cite news |last1=Hawari |first1=Walaa |last2=Al-Dosary |first2=Shiekha |title=Women's Issues in the Middle East: Saudi Arabia: Frustrating experience |url=https://womenspillar.blogspot.com/2009/03/saudi-arabia-frustrating-experience.html |work=Women's Issues in the Middle East (apparently reprinting an [[Arab News]] report) |agency=Arab News (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''') |date=11 March 2009}}</ref>{{Third-party inline|date=December 2019}}--> The bisht is associated with power and religious position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Al-Mukhtar |first1=Rima |title=Traditional and modern: The Saudi man's bisht |url=https://www.arabnews.com/fashion/traditional-modern-saudi-mans-bisht |work=Arab News |date=7 November 2012 |language=en}}</ref>]]\n\nThe Riyadh bookfair is a focus of political conflict: its events are easier to understand in their political context. Power in Saudi Arabia is held by the monarch ({{as of|lc=yes|2020||df=}}, effectively the crown prince, [[Mohammed bin Salman]]), but traditionally also by the royal family, religious clerics, and the overlapping security services and business community, who have traditionally been allied.<ref name=\"moderate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/i-will-return-saudi-arabia-moderate-islam-crown-prince|title=I will return Saudi Arabia to moderate Islam, says crown prince|last1=Chulov|first1=Martin|date=24 October 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=cost>{{cite web |first1= |title=The High Cost of Change: Repression Under Saudi Crown Prince Tarnishes Reforms |url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/11/04/high-cost-change/repression-under-saudi-crown-prince-tarnishes-reforms |website=Human Rights Watch | language=en |date=4 November 2019}}</ref> These alliances are not holding as they once did,<ref name=moderate/><ref name=cost/> because the monarchy is centralizing power and weakening other power bases.<ref name=\"rattled_royals\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-jamal-khashoggi.html|title=Uproar Over Dissident Rattles Saudi Royal Family|last1=Hubbard|first1=Ben|date=19 October 2018|work=The New York Times|last2=Kirkpatrick|first2=David D.}}</ref><ref name=cost/>\n\nThe general public and the media (including newspapers and book publishers) hold little [[Formal organization|formal power]], but their potential power has been a matter of official concern. Since the 1920s, the monarchy had repeatedly promised democratic reforms and [[constitutional monarchy]]; however, in the 2010s, it affirmed [[absolute monarchy]].<ref name=absolute>{{cite web |last1=Alaoudh |first1=Abdullah |title=Saudi Arabia's crown prince is taking the kingdom back to the Dark Ages |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/07/19/saudi-arabias-crown-prince-is-taking-the-kingdom-back-to-the-dark-ages/ |website=Washington Post |language=en |date=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Royal family===\nThere has been a power struggle between the monarchy and the royal family. Royals often hold official posts, in government or academia. Some of the authors and public intellectuals at the fair are thus members of the royal family (for instance, [[Al-Zahrani]] is the name of the third royal family, and the name of a law professor who became involved in two clashes with clergy at the book fair). The large royal family has recently lost political power.<ref name=\"royals_lose\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/11/06/562393761/what-changes-in-saudi-arabias-political-power-mean-for-u-s-saudi-relations|title=What Changes In Saudi Arabia's Political Power Mean For U.S.-Saudi Relations|website=NPR.org|language=en}}</ref> Royal officials have been replaced by officials beholden to the crown prince.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://agsiw.org/saudi-arabia-reassigns-roles-within-a-more-centralized-monarchy/|title=Saudi Arabia Reassigns Roles within a More Centralized Monarchy|last1=Smith Diwan|first1=Kristin|date=22 January 2019|website=Arab Gulf States Institute in Washington}}</ref> In 2018, members of the royal family and business community were placed under house arrest,<ref name=\"rattled_royals\" /> required to sign over assets to the government, and restricted in their movements; there are reports some were physically abused, which the government denies<ref name=\"clerics\" /><ref name=\"billions\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/11/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-corruption-mohammed-bin-salman.html|title=Saudis Said to Use Coercion and Abuse to Seize Billions|last1=Hubbard|first1=Ben|date=11 March 2018|work=The New York Times|last2=Kirkpatrick|first2=David D.|last3=Kelly|first3=Kate|last4=Mazzetti|first4=Mark}}</ref><ref name=\"fun\">{{Cite journal|title=Radical reforms in Saudi Arabia are changing the Gulf and the Arab world, Radical reforms in Saudi Arabia are changing the Gulf and the Arab world|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2018/06/21/radical-reforms-in-saudi-arabia-are-changing-the-gulf-and-the-arab-world|journal=The Economist}}</ref> (torture is illegal in Saudi Arabia<ref name=\"crush\" />).<!-- The (~35<ref name=obit>{{cite news |last1=al-Rasheed |first1=Madawi |title=King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/22/king-abdullah-of-saudi-arabia |work=The Guardian |date=22 January 2015}}</ref>) children of [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]], who died in 2015, seem to have been especial targets.<ref name=billions>{{cite news |last1=Hubbard |first1=Ben |last2=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |last3=Kelly |first3=Kate |last4=Mazzetti |first4=Mark |title=Saudis Said to Use Coercion and Abuse to Seize Billions |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/11/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-corruption-mohammed-bin-salman.html |work=The New York Times |date=11 March 2018}}</ref>--> Subsequently, the stipends paid to members of the royal family were secretly increased.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-02-01/saudis-are-said-to-raise-allowances-for-some-royals-after-purge|title=Saudis Raise Allowances for Some Royals after Purge|last1=Nereim|first1=Vivian|date=1 February 2018|work=www.bloomberg.com|agency=Bloomberg|last2=Martin|first2=Matthew}}</ref>\n\n===Clerical officials===\nThere has also been a power struggle between the monarchy and clerical officials. Clerical officials control education and the judiciary (though the monarch may issue pardons). Clerical officials traditionally censored journalists and publications, through control of the [[Ministry of Interior (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Interior]] ''(sic)''.<ref name=\"CPJ\" /> The Ministry of Interior also formerly had oversight of religious police, but lost it in the early 2010s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/13/saudi-arabia-says-religious-police-must-be-gentle-and-humane|title=Saudi Arabia says religious police must be 'gentle and humane'|first=Associated|last=Press|date=13 April 2016|via=www.theguardian.com|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> In 2017, the internal security forces and the powerful prosecution service were transferred from the control of the ministry to the direct control of the monarchy.<ref name=\"cost\" /> The powers of the clerical officials at the book fair have been increasingly restricted; for instance, the religious police have lost the power to enforce rules, retaining only the power to report violations, and government-controlled media report that members of the religious police disrupting book fair events in the 2010s were arrested.<ref name=\"SW2010\" />\n\n===Media===\n[[File:JamalKahshoggi.png|thumb|left|Journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] said of the intellectual climate: \"It's like [[McCarthyism]] in the 1950s\".<ref name=CPJ />]]\n\nEditors-in-chief in Saudi Arabia are appointed only with government approval, and work to guidelines on how stories are to be covered. Newspapers are post-censored; the government can blacklist any journalist in Saudi Arabia, preventing them from working anywhere in the country, and it can have online articles taken down.<ref name=\"CPJ\" /> Journalists have also been arrested, kept in [[solitary confinement]], and tortured, often for unclear reasons.<ref name=\"arrests\">{{cite news |last1=Yee |first1=Vivian |title=Saudi Arabia Is Stepping Up Crackdown on Dissent, Rights Groups Say |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/26/world/middleeast/saudi-arrests-journalists-activists.html |work=The New York Times |date=26 November 2019}}</ref> Journalists often attend the fair as book authors. One journalist attributed a clash with the religious police (Hai\u02bea) at the fair to her newspaper columns;<ref name=\"backfire\" /> she had criticized the Hai\u02bea,<ref name=\"backfire\" /> as Hai\u02bea-affiliated power over censorship weakened.<ref name=\"backfire\" /> Books and entire publishing houses are also censored; anyone wanting mass access to the Saudi Arabian market needs the approval of the censors.<ref name=\"algemeiner\" /><ref name=\"protest\" />\n\nThe book fair programme is set by the monarchy, which uses it to showcase its policies;<ref name= memorandum /><ref name=economist /> the monarchy also pre-censors the books to be legally sold.<ref name=rocket/> The event is regulated by the religious police, who have set admission rules, post-censored and confiscated books, and shut down events.<ref name= memorandum /><ref name=2006_1_jeans />\n\nCensorship at the book fair, as elsewhere, has become less religious and more political in its goals, as it has been transferred from clerical to monarchic control. Social liberals have at times defended the freedom of speech of social conservatives, who now face heavier censorship at the fair and elsewhere.<ref name=blame/> Informal media also face stronger restrictions; people have been jailed and tortured for blog posts and tweets.<ref name=lib_not_dem/><ref name=crush>{{cite news |last1=Mazzetti |first1=Mark |last2=Hubbard |first2=Ben |title=It Wasn't Just Khashoggi: A Saudi Prince's Brutal Drive to Crush Dissent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/world/middleeast/khashoggi-crown-prince-saudi.html |work=The New York Times |date=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=clerics>{{cite news |last1=Hubbard |first1=Ben |title=Saudi Arabia Detains Critics as New Crown Prince Consolidates Power |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/14/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-clerics.html |work=The New York Times |date=14 September 2017}}</ref> Blogs, social media, and [[satellite TV]] hinder censorship;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nolan |first1=Leigh |title=Managing reform? Saudi Arabia and the king's dilemma |url=https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/05_saudi_arabia_nolan.pdf |publisher=Brookings Doha Center |date=May 2011}}</ref>{{rp|5}} books banned from the book fair are discussed online, and available to many through illegal downloads.<ref name=downloads />\n\nThe Saudi government has spent millions on influencing foreign media coverage, especially in the wake of [[Jamal Khashoggi]]'s 2018 death. Efforts have focussed on improving its international image, attracting [[Tourism in Saudi Arabia|tourists]], and promoting tourist attractions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Massoglia |first1=Anna |title=Saudi Arabia ramped up multi-million foreign influence operation after Khashoggi's death |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/news/2019/10/saudi-arabia-ramped-up-foreign-influence-after-khashoggi/ |website=OpenSecrets News |publisher=The Center for Responsive Politics |date=2 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thebault |first1=Reis |last2=Mettler |first2=Katie |title=Instagram influencers partied at a Saudi music festival \u2014 but no one mentioned human rights | work=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/12/23/instagram-influencers-partied-saudi-arabian-music-festival-no-one-mentioned-human-rights/ |date=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Public opinion===\n[[File:Saudipop.svg|thumb|The population of Saudi Arabia is young, and youth unemployment of Saudi citizens is generally 20 to 30%, higher for women,<ref name=unshackle /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nereim |first1=Vivian |title=Saudi Unemployment Falls to 3-Year Low While Expat Exodus Slows |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-15/saudi-arabia-s-unemployment-falls-to-lowest-in-over-three-years |work=www.bloomberg.com |date=15 December 2019}}</ref> though there are doubts about the reliability of government statistics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dudley |first1=Dominic |title=Rising Unemployment Suggests Saudi Government Reforms Are Failing |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dominicdudley/2016/12/08/saudi-unemployment/ |work=Forbes |language=en}}</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Riyadh population graph RU.PNG|thumb|The population of Riyadh is growing rapidly]]\nVisitors to the fair (both the public and the writers and intellectuals) seek to evade censorship, buy and sell books, including blackmarket books,<ref name= memorandum /><ref name=2006_1_jeans /> and take part in discussions.<ref name=anas_quote /> They come into conflict with both the monarchy and the religious police, as well as one another.<ref name=SW2010 />\n\nTraditionally, the monarchy has presented itself as a progressive force, prevented from moving quickly with liberalizing reforms by the strong conservatism of the population;<ref name=\"opendem\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/5050/saudi-response-to-arab-spring-containment-and-co-option/|title=The Saudi response to the 'Arab spring': containment and co-option|website=openDemocracy}}</ref> by implication, if the country were to become democratic, then it would become much more radically conservative. This view has been challenged domestically.<ref name=moderation/> It has also been suggested that the monarchy seeks to hinder a unified Saudi political movement by playing up [[:Category:Tribes of Saudi Arabia|tribalism]] and [[sectarianism|sectarian]] religious differences, and by associating demonstrations, [[civil disobedience]] and criticism with foreign actors.<ref name=\"opendem\" /><ref name=moderation>{{cite web |title='Moderation' requires tolerance, acceptance of others, free speech and human rights |url=https://alqst.org/eng/moderation-requires-tolerance-acceptance-others-free-speech-human-rights/ |website=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0633\u0637 |language=en-US-QST |date=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2005 there were petitions for human rights and a [[constitutional monarchy]].<ref name=obit>{{cite news |last1=al-Rasheed |first1=Madawi |title=King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/22/king-abdullah-of-saudi-arabia |work=The Guardian |date=22 January 2015}}</ref> During the [[Arab Spring]], the [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests]], these were renewed, with public appeals and petitions for democracy.<ref name=absolute /><ref>{{cite web |title=The Arab Revolution Saudi Update |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2011/02/18/the-arab-revolution-saudi-update/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |author=Eman al-Nafjan |date=18 February 2011|author-link=Eman al-Nafjan }}</ref> Calls for reform were driven by corruption, official impunity, detention without trial, high unemployment, and royal excesses.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Caryle |title=Will the House of Saud adapt enough to survive ... again? {{!}} The Star |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2011/02/12/will_the_house_of_saud_adapt_enough_to_survive_again.html |website=thestar.com |language=en}}</ref> [[Foreign workers in Saudi Arabia]], who make up ~30% of the population (official census figures, {{as of|lc=yes|2014}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method%3Dhome.regcon%26contentID%3D2010112487888%26archiveissuedate%3D24%2F11%2F2010|title=Census shows Kingdom's population at more than 27 million|date=24 November 2010|publisher=Saudi Gazette|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006080326/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2010112487888&archiveissuedate=24%2F11%2F2010|archivedate=6 October 2014|accessdate=2014-11-20|df=dmy}}</ref> have [[Kafala system|limited rights]] and are disenfranchised, an additional potential source of unrest.<ref name=collapse/>\n\nThere was also significant activism on [[Saudi anti male-guardianship campaign|guardianship rules]], women's franchise, the right to drive, and the rights of political prisoners.<ref name=\"opendem\" /> A 2013 petition called for women to be permitted to drive<ref>{{cite news |title=Dozens of Saudi Arabian women drive cars on day of protest against ban |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/26/saudi-arabia-woman-driving-car-ban |work=The Guardian |date=26 October 2013}}</ref> (a position which a [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] poll found that the majority of Saudi men and women supported in 2007,<ref name=\"Gallup\">{{cite web |author=Gallup |title=Saudi Arabia: Majorities Support Women's Rights |url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/103441/saudi-arabia-majorities-support-womens-rights.aspx |website=Gallup.com |language=en-us |date=21 December 2007}}</ref> contradicting a 2006 government poll finding 89% of women opposed it<ref name=\"unshackle\">{{cite news |title=Unshackling themselves, Unshackling themselves |url=https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2014/05/17/unshackling-themselves |work=The Economist}}</ref>). Some petitions, like a 2016 one to [[Saudi anti male-guardianship campaign|abolish the male guardianship system]], were supported by clerics and social liberals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sidahmed |first1=Mazin |title=Thousands of Saudis sign petition to end male guardianship of women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/26/saudi-arabia-protest-petition-end-guardianship-law-women |work=The Guardian |date=26 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Are we or aren't we? |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2011/02/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |author=Eman al-Nafjan |language=en|author-link=Eman al-Nafjan }}</ref> \n\nThe monarchy has taken action against independent and opposition clerics, usually on the grounds that they support extremism or terrorism. It has arrested clerics of a variety of political views, including some who have supported religious tolerance and opposed travel to fight in war zones,<ref name=\"overt_support\" /> and those supporting electoral democracy.<ref name=\"Muslim_Brotherhood\">{{cite news |last1=Lacroix |first1=St\u00e9phane |title=Saudi Arabia's Muslim Brotherhood predicament |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2014/03/20/saudi-arabias-muslim-brotherhood-predicament/ |work=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> Generally, overt support of crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] is required: in some cases, this includes performing specific requested acts of support.<ref name=\"cost\" /> The clerics who are tolerated all support the crown prince, though they vary in their other views.<ref name=\"overt_support\">{{cite news |last1=Ismail |first1=Raihan |title=How is MBS's consolidation of power affecting Saudi clerics in the opposition? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/06/04/how-is-mohammads-consolidation-power-affecting-oppositional-saudi-clerics/ |work=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> This has entailed dramatic shifts in the monarchy's attitude to groups like the [[Sahwa movement]] and the [[Muslim Brotherhood]], to whom it had formerly given official positions and influence; one such shift was marked by the banning of all Muslim Brotherhood books from the book fair.<ref name=\"Muslim_Brotherhood\" /> \n\nMore such shifts have been seen on women's driving. In 2006, a politician was shouted down for raising the topic at the fair;<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> in 2014, a driving activist had an aisle at the fair named after her;<ref name=Sixth/> in 2017, the government announced that women would be allowed to drive, in 2018, the fair featured a driving simulator for women, women were allowed to drive,<ref name=economist/> non-activist women were asked to publicly thank the government so that the change would not appear to be a victory for the activists,<ref name=moderation/> and many activists who had campaigned for the right to drive were arrested (including activists honoured in 2014); in 2019, a professor was arrested after expressing support of the still-detained activists at a fair discussion panel.<ref name=viral/><ref name=anas_quote/>\n\n===Reforms: social liberalization, political restriction===\nSince these protests, the monarchy's message has begun to shift. It is now enacting socially-liberalizing reforms, against the opposition of more conservative elements of the clergy, breaking the alliance with some hardline clerics.<ref name=\"blame\" /><ref name=\"moderate\" /> There is a drive to provide leisure opportunities for young people; movie theaters and music concerts are now permitted, and fashion, art, and sport promoted.<ref name=\"fun\" /><ref name=\"lib_not_dem\" /> The heavily-promoted book fair also provides officially-sanctioned cultural activities, and some social restrictions at the fair have been relaxed (such as women's dress codes and gender segregation).<ref>See details in [[#history_2012|the section of this article about the 2012 fair]], for instance.</ref>\n\nViews on these social reforms seem to vary: young urban citizens tend to be more in favour, while conservatively religious citizens, who tend to come from specific rural areas, are more likely to oppose them.<ref name=\"lib_not_dem\">{{Cite web|url=http://afsa.org/saudi-arabia-liberalization-not-democratization|title=Saudi Arabia: Liberalization, Not Democratization|website=afsa.org}}</ref> Economic reforms, driven by falling oil prices, have varying levels of support, and a poor economy is a source of discontent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shahine |first1=Alaa |last2=Nereim |first2=Vivian |last3=Abu-Nasr |first3=Donna |title=Saudi Arabia's Great Makeover Can't Afford to Fail This Time |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-10-16/saudi-arabia-s-great-makeover-can-t-afford-to-fail-this-time |website=www.bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref name=\"collapse\">{{cite news |author=Guest Contributor |title=What If Saudi Arabia Collapses? |url=https://lobelog.com/what-if-the-state-of-saudi-arabia-collapses/ |work=LobeLog |date=10 August 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe social reforms are widely seen as a way to reduce activist pressure for reforms of political power structures (such as a greater popular voice in government).<ref name=\"lib_not_dem\" /> The monarchy is simultaneously taking harsher measures against dissent. Regardless of how liberal or conservative they are,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fahim |first1=Kareem |title=Saudi Arabia's once-powerful conservatives silenced by reforms and repression |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudi-arabias-once-powerful-conservatives-silenced-by-reforms-and-repression/2018/06/04/5332bdec-3dad-11e8-955b-7d2e19b79966_story.html |website=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> activists who call for political reforms have been jailed and tortured, even when they have advocated,<ref name=\"wrong_people\">{{cite news |last1=Khashoggi |first1=Jamal |title=Saudi Arabia's crown prince wants to 'crush extremists.' But he's punishing the wrong people. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/10/31/saudi-arabias-crown-prince-wants-to-crush-extremists-but-hes-punishing-the-wrong-people/ |work=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> or worked with the government on, reforms the government has enacted.<ref name=\"8detained\">{{cite news |last1=Batrawy |first1=Aya |title=Activists: Saudi Arabia detains eight in sustained crackdown |url=https://apnews.com/40f0c42d68a04320a05c28eca6797483 |work=AP NEWS |date=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"arrests\" /> The government has also arrested academics expressing critical views (for instance, questioning government economic projections),<ref name=\"cost\" /> including at the fair.<ref name=\"arrest\" />\n\n==History==\n\n===2004===\nThe 2004 fair (advertised as the tenth<ref name=2004_1_jeans>{{cite web |title=Not Fair! |url=https://saudijeans.org/2004/09/19/not-fair/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=19 September 2004}}</ref>) had 300 publishers from 14 (mostly Arab) countries; there was one Iraqi publisher.<ref name=2004_jeans>{{cite web |title=The Book Fair Report |url=https://saudijeans.org/2004/09/30/the-book-fair-report/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=30 September 2004}}</ref>\n\n===2006===\n[[File:\u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u0649 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0641\u0632\u064a\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0635\u0631\u064a.jpg|thumb|[[Mustafa Mahmoud]] published ''Dialogue with an Atheist'' in 1974; at the 2006 fair, it went on display in Saudi Arabia for the first time]]\nThe Saudi government (through the [[Ministry of Higher Education (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Higher Education]]) was involved with organizing the event for the first time in 2006;<ref name=2008_jeans /> the Riyadh Exhibitions Company said that they had signed a co-operation agreement.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u0639\u0631\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 Riyadh International Book Fair |url=http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/r_1.htm |publisher=Riyadh Exhibitions company |date=7 February 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060207015210/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/r_1.htm |archive-date=7 February 2006 }} (official fair website '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\nSome days were restricted to \"families-only\" attendance, meaning that single men were not allowed to enter.<!--Bizarrely, the official site just gives opening times and does not mention this segregation, though attendees do: https://web.archive.org/web/20060207015210/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/r_1.htm--> The 2006 fair was held in the Riyadh Exhibition Center.<ref name=2007_jeans /><ref>{{cite web |title=Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://www.khaled.us/riyadh-international-book-fair.html |website=Khaled rambles |date=17 February 2006}}</ref>\n\nBooths of foreign publishers, such as [[Dar Al Saqi]], [[The Arabic Cultural Center]], [[Dar Al Jamal]], the [[Arab Establishment of Research and Publishing]], and [[Dar Al Mada]], were popular.<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> Copies of the novel ''[[Banat al-Riyadh]]'' (\"Girls of Riyadh\") were unexpectedly absent; it was not clear whether it had been banned<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> or had sold out, although a representative of the publisher said it had not sold out, according to [[Asharq Al-Awsat|a Saudi government-run London newspaper]]. The same paper reported that ''[[The Dolphin's Trip]]'' and ''[[Abdullah Thabit|Terrorist Number 20]]'' were banned, while the ''[[New Testament]]'' and ''[[Mustafa Mahmoud|Dialogue with an Atheist]]'' were on display for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: Copies of ''Girls of Riyadh'' Novel Mysteriously Disappear from Book Fair |url=https://eng-archive.aawsat.com/theaawsat/news-middle-east/saudi-arabia-copies-of-girls-of-riyadh-novel-mysteriously-disappear-from-book-fair |website=eng-archive.aawsat.com |author= Asharq Al-Awsat|language=en|author-link=Asharq Al-Awsat }} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref><!--{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}}--> [[Turki Al-Hamad]]'s novel ''[[Reeh Al-Jannah]]'' was also missing.<ref name=2006_1_jeans />\n\nSome official speakers and debate topics were controversial, touching on pressing political issues, and debates were heated.<ref name=2008_jeans /> A discussion panel was disrupted by hecklers who shouted down a member of the [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia]]<ref name=globalvoices/> ([[Mohammed Al-Zulfa]]<ref name=2006_1_jeans />) speaking at the fair<ref name=globalvoices/> on women's driving.<ref name=quiet>{{cite web |last1=Arabia |first1=Crossroads |title=Riyadh Book Fair off to Quiet Start |url=http://xrdarabia.org/blog/archives/2007/02/28/riyadh-book-fair-off-to-quiet-start/ |date=21 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070321174524/http://xrdarabia.org/blog/archives/2007/02/28/riyadh-book-fair-off-to-quiet-start/ |archive-date=21 March 2007 }}</ref> A discussion on censorship, whose panelists included former Information Minister [[Muhammad Abdo Yamani]] and pro-government editor [[Turki al-Sudeiri]], was shouted down by protestors, who also surrounded the panellists and physically assaulted at least one journalist.<ref name=CPJ>{{cite news |last1=Campagna |first1=Joel |title=Saudi Arabia report: Princes, Clerics, and Censors |url=https://cpj.org/reports/2006/05/saudi-06.php |work=cpj.org |agency=Committee to Protect Journalists |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2007===\nThe 2007 fair was held in the same location as the 2006 one, and the topics selected for the cultural programme were described as less controversial.<ref name=2007_jeans />\n\nIn 2007, Abdul-Aziz al-Sabeel, deputy minister of information for cultural affairs, announced that the \"families-only\" days would be dropped: three evenings were open for men only; the rest would be open to all. The ministry and the religious police were said to have negotiated this change.<ref name=2007_jeans>{{cite web |title=Saudi Jeans: Let's Meet and Talk |url=http://saudijeans.blogspot.com/2007/02/lets-meet-and-talk.html |date=15 November 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115004540/http://saudijeans.blogspot.com/2007/02/lets-meet-and-talk.html |archive-date=15 November 2007 }}</ref><ref name=globalvoices>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: 2007 Riyadh International Book Fair, Ahmadinejad's Visit to the Kingdom, and More |url=https://globalvoices.org/2007/03/07/saudi-arabia-2007-riyadh-international-book-fair-ahmadinejads-visit-to-the-kingdom-and-more/ |website=Global Voices |language=en |date=7 March 2007}}</ref> However, it is not clear that this actually occurred; it later emerged that fair periods scheduled as \"open for all\" meant open to mixed-gender family groups only.<ref name=comsci />\n\n===2008===\nThe 2008 fair was held at the Riyadh International Exhibition Center in Morouj Dist, and featured less controversial speakers and topics than the 2006 fair.<ref name=2008_jeans>{{cite web |last1=Al Omran |first1=Ahmed |title=Riyadh International Book Fair: Could Be Better |url=https://saudijeans.org/2008/03/09/riyadh-international-book-fair-could-be-better/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=9 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Society for Human Rights]] offered a report on the state of human rights in Saudi Arabia at the fair. There were separate opening hours for men and mixed-gender family groups,<ref name=2008_jeans /> with four evenings reserved for men only.<ref name=2008_sched>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u0639\u0631\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 2008 |url=http://www.riyadhbookfair.org.sa/Sections.aspx?id=7 |date=14 March 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080314125753/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org.sa/Sections.aspx?id=7|archive-date = 14 March 2008}} (official schedule; '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\nThe US Embassy in Riydh participated, hosting a \"US Information Resource Center\" booth.<ref name=\"wikileak\">{{cite web |last1=Al-Omran |first1=Ahmed |title=Some of the 'Less Boring' Saudi Wikileaks Cables |url=https://mideastposts.com/middle-east-society/some-of-the-less-boring-saudi-wikileaks-cables/ |website=MidEastPosts.com}}</ref> The booth sold 1,829 copies of 66 pre-approved publications; Embassy officials were surprised by the positive response to their presence, and strong interest in English-language teaching materials and American literature.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Audiences Reached at Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/08RIYADH618_a.html |publisher=Wikileaks |date=2008}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\n[[File:Halema Muzaffar.jpg|thumb|There was controversy over events at journalist Halimah Matafar's book-signing]]\nIn 2009, the fair moved to the much larger<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> Riyadh International Exhibition Center on King Abdullah Road,<ref name=2009_jeans /> and ran from Thursday 3<ref name=\"events\" /> until 13 March.<ref name=2009_jeans /> Four evenings were men-only and the rest were \"for all\", according to the official conference schedule.<ref name=2009_sched>{{cite web |title=Riyadh-Book-Fair |url=http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/english/Pages/index.aspx |publisher=KSA Ministry of Culture and Information |date=16 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216090537/http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/english/Pages/index.aspx |archive-date=16 December 2009 }} ('''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\nSaudi newspapers, which are government-controlled,<ref name=CPJ /> reported that prices of books from non-Saudi publishing houses were up 20 to 25%, due to the costs of transportation, rental of space at the fair, and other factors. They said that some books that had previously been permitted were banned, and some previously banned were permitted, and that visitors were required to show the receipts for their books on the way out.<ref name=high_prices>{{cite news |title=High prices, Hai'a dampen spirits at Riyadh Book Fair |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527190648/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2009030731368 |archive-date=27 May 2009 |url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2009030731368| url-status=dead |work=Saudi Gazette |date=27 May 2009}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref> The government-controlled ''[[Saudi Gazette]]'' also reported that books by [[Abdel Rahman Badawi]] an [[Amin Maalouf]] were missing from the fair.<ref name=repub /> Dar al-Jamal, an Iraqi publisher previously popular at the fair,<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> was banned.<ref name=ghana />\n\nReligious scholars condemned the fair for inviting [[Mohammed Abed al-Jabri]]. At the fair, al-Jabri said that religious groups sought to monopolise religious authority, by restricting the ability of civic groups to defend religious beliefs.<ref name=backfire />\n\nAccording to accounts in Saudi newspapers,{{refn|name=HMciting|Aside from a blog,<ref name=tanjara /> only domestic (and thus Saudi-government-controlled) media give names of all three men;<ref name=high_prices/><ref name=repub /> Associated Press says three men but gives one name;<ref name=\"events\" /> CNN says only two were arrested, but cite the Saudi reports.<ref name=autograph /> A reprinting of a domestic media article<ref name=repub /> carries a great deal of detail on the incident, including what appear to be interviews with the participants. It contradicts another source on whether the journalist was trying to give books to her colleagues, and had to pass them via a male security guard,<ref name=repub /> or the male writers had bought books and passed them to her via a male security guard.<ref name=high_prices/> All the accounts seem to be by or based upon domestic media.}} on Thursday the 5th,<ref name=2009_jeans /> local journalist [[Halimah Matafar]]'s<!--is this romanization correct per [[Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Arabic]]?--> ([[:ar:\u062d\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0629 \u0645\u0638\u0641\u0631|ar]]) book-signing was surrounded by five security men, six policemen and two religious policemen.<ref name=\"events\" /><ref name=backfire>{{cite news |last1=Mahdi |first1=Wael |title=New-look book fair backfires on writers |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/new-look-book-fair-backfires-on-writers-1.582309 |work=The National |date=24 March 2009 |language=en}}</ref> <!--The books had to be passed between the author and men wanting autographs via a (male) fair security guard.<ref name=high_prices/><ref name=repub />{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}}--> They report that some male writers<ref name=\"events\" /> had their books signed; as they left, one waved and said \"Thank you and goodbye\" to the author,<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009>{{cite web |title=Riyadh Book Fair 2009 |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2009/03/08/riyadh-book-fair-2009/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |date=8 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"events\" /> and religious police accused him of addressing an unrelated woman.<ref name=\"events\" /> Satirical novelist and journalist<ref>{{cite web |title=Abdo Khal: International Prize for Arabic Fiction |url=https://www.arabicfiction.org/en/Abdo-Khal |website=www.arabicfiction.org}}</ref> [[Abdo Khal]] and poet [[Abdullah al-Thabet]]<ref name=booted /><ref>{{cite news |title=If You're in the KSA: The Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2010/02/20/if-youre-in-the-ksa-the-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |work=& Arablit |date=20 February 2010 |language=en}}</ref> (and law professor [[Mojab al-Zahrani]], according to some accounts<ref name=tanjara>{{cite web |title=The tanjara: Religious[sic] police and censorship cause discontent at Riyadh book fair |url=https://thetanjara.blogspot.com/2009/03/religous-police-and-censorship-cause.html |website=the tanjara |date=10 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=high_prices/>) complained that they were then verbally abused and taken to the religious police center;<ref name=\"events\" /> they were released without charge the same day. Halimah Matafar said that she was the only woman at the fair treated in this manner; she attributed it to her criticism (in her weekly column) of the religious police: \"I felt like I was wearing an explosive belt, not signing books... If any first-time female writer was surrounded by this many policemen, she would be discouraged,\" she said.<ref name=backfire />\n\nDuring the 8th, a woman visiting with her family found only one stall staffed by a woman<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> (likely Najet Mield, per state-controlled sources<ref name=repub>{{cite news |last1=Hawari |first1=Walaa |last2=Al-Dosary |first2=Shiekha |title=Women's Issues in the Middle East: Saudi Arabia: Frustrating experience |url=https://womenspillar.blogspot.com/2009/03/saudi-arabia-frustrating-experience.html |work=Women's Issues in the Middle East (apparently reprinting an [[Arab News]] report) |agency=Arab News (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''') |date=11 March 2009}}</ref>). The stallkeeper had come from France, and said staffing the stall on the first day, which was men-only, was awkward, so she had gotten a male stand-in for the men-only days.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> On Friday the 6th (the fourth day), saleswomen were banned from the hall on men's days.<ref name=2009_jeans/> Women's access to the fair was expanded from two half-days.<ref name=\"events\" />\n\nThe religious police had a large stall, which did not sell books. It exhibited items they had confiscated, and screened a video presentation on how they reverse magic spells.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 />\n\n===2010===\nThe 2010 fair advertised family-only days (no single men) and four men-only evenings.<ref name=comsci/><ref name=\"schedule\">{{cite web |title=Riyadh-Book-Fair |url=http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/English/Pages/index.aspx |publisher=Ministry of Culture, Saudi Arabia |date=11 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111004916/http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/English/Pages/index.aspx |archive-date=11 January 2010 }} Original Ministry of Culture official schedule, '''not an independent source'''</ref> It was criticized for its website changing its URL annually and being hastily thrown up just before the fair with limited information and some technical problems.<ref name=comsci>{{cite web |title=Riyadh International Book Fair 2010, let's try this again |url=https://www.khaled.us/riyadh-international-book-fair-2010-lets-try-this-again.html |website=Khaled rambles |date=3 March 2010}}</ref><!--{{better source}}--> The presence of the religious police was much more muted in 2010 than in the previous year, including a smaller stall. Some stallholders were requiring official written notice that a book was banned before removing it from sale (rather than removing books on a verbal request from the religious police).<ref name=SW2010 /> Controversially, a women did the announcements over the public address system.<ref name=SW2010>{{cite web |title=Riyadh Book Fair 2010 |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2010/03/05/riyadh-book-fair-2010/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |date=5 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe children's area (in which men are not allowed) was greatly expanded, with more children's books, a reading area, a colouring area, a stage with regular performances, and, for mothers, screenings of films on child abuse and domestic violence.<ref name=SW2010/> The [[Saudi Human Rights Organization]], the [[Riyadh Orphanage]], the disabled association, a temporary museum exhibit, and other organizations had stalls just outside the exhibition hall.<ref name=SW2010/> There was a small but varied selection of English books.<ref name=SW2010/>\n\n[[Abdo Khal]]'s prizewinning<ref>{{cite news |title=But is it fiction? |url=https://al-bab.com/blog/2010/03/it-fiction-0 |work=al-bab.com |language=en}}</ref> novel ''[[Tarmi bi-Sharar]]'' (English title: ''Spewing Sparks as Big as Castles''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calderbank |first1=Tony |title=One Arabic-English translator shares his experience |url=https://www.britishcouncil.org/voices-magazine/arabic-english-translator-shares-experience |website=www.britishcouncil.org |language=en |agency=British Council}}</ref>) was withdrawn from the fair.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi writers find voice depicting closed society |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/922385 |work=dawn.com |date=22 June 2010 |language=en}}</ref> Books by activist [[Abdullah al-Hamed]] were confiscated.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia |url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2011/saudi-arabia |website=freedomhouse.org |language=en |date=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"history_2011\"></span>2011===\n[[File:Yousef Ziedan.jpg|thumb|[[Youssef Ziedan]] at a book-signing at the fair in 2011; his books were confiscated midway through the 2017 fair]]\nOn the second day<ref name=own /> of the fair, a group of men (30 according to one Saudi journalist,<ref name=theater /> dozens according to [[Agence France-Presse]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi hardliners disrupt book fair |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContentP/2/6883/World/Saudi-hardliners-disrupt-book-fair-.aspx |work=Ahram Online |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |language=en}}</ref> and over 500 according to [[Al Arabiya]]<ref name=alarabiya_2011 /> [a domestic, and thus government-controlled, news outlet]) appeared to co-ordinate a disruption, targeting writers, publishers, journalists, and female speakers.<ref name=numbers>{{cite news |title=Book Fair Updates: Riyadh Disrupted by Ultraconservatives, Report from Casablanca |url=https://arablit.org/2011/03/03/book-fair-updates-riyadh-disrupted-by-ultraconservatives-report-from-casablanca/ |work=& Arablit |date=3 March 2011 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=ghana /> Domestic media stated that they physically assaulted some participants, issued instructions on women's dress and behaviour over a loudspeaker,<ref name=own /> and harassed women, many of whom left.<ref name=Zee /> According to [[Al Arabiya]], one challenged [[Abdul Aziz Khoja]], the Minister of Culture and Information, on the selection of speakers, complaining that they were too liberal.<ref name=theater>{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Rob L. |title=Riyadh Book Fair Debacle is Nothing More Than Theater |url=https://mideastposts.com/middle-east-politics-analysis/riyadh-book-fair-debacle-is-nothing-more-than-theater/ |work=MidEast Posts}} ('''Not an independent source'''; [[Rob L. Wagner]], the author, was an editor at Saudi-government-controlled ''[[Arab News]]'' at the time of writing, and has long been employed in posts under Saudi government control.)</ref> Saudi media reported allegations that the men were Hai\u02bea members in [[Mufti (dress)|mufti]];<ref name=own>{{cite news |last1=Royston |first1=Steve |title=Sharp Divides Emerge over Saudi Reforms |url=https://mideastposts.com/showcase/saudi-arabia-%e2%80%93-the-case-for-reform/ |work=MidEast Posts}}</ref> a Hai\u02bea spokesman said the Hai\u02bea were not involved. Some were arrested (three, according to Sabq.org<ref name=Zee>{{cite news |title=Saudi hardliners disrupt book fair: Witnesses |url=https://zeenews.india.com/news/world/saudi-hardliners-disrupt-book-fair-witnesses_691074.html |work=Zee News |date=3 March 2011 |language=en}}</ref> and Al-bab.com,<ref name=thuggery>{{cite news |last1=Whitaker |first1=Brian |title=Thuggery at Saudi book fair |url=https://al-bab.com/blog/2011/03/thuggery-saudi-book-fair |work=al-bab.com |language=en | date=3 March 2011}}</ref> or 100, according to Al Arabiya, which also said that the remaining protestors staged a sit-in calling for their release<ref name=alarabiya_2011>{{cite news |title=Saudi conservatives stir row in a Riyadh book fair |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/03/03/140027.html |work=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0646\u062a |agency=Alarabiya |date=3 March 2011 |language=en}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>). The original source of information on this event is newspapers under the control of the Saudi government; as the government is a party to this dispute, there is a lack of independent reporting.\n\nOn the last day of the fair, a hailstorm lead to extensive leaks in the roof of the [[Riyadh Expo Center]], flooding the exhibition hall. [[Squeegee]]s were used to control the water. The flood forced many publishers to evacuate their sodden books.<ref>{{cite web |title=Riyadh |work=Khaled rambles |url=https://www.khaled.us/tag/riyadh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u062f \u064a\u0632\u0648\u0631 \u0645\u0639\u0631\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 |url=http://www.alriyadh.com/612912 |work=[[Al Riyadh (newspaper)]] \u062c\u0631\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 |date=2011-03-12 |language=ar}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\n[[Dar al-Jamal]], an Iraqi publisher, was banned.<ref name=ghana />\n\n===<span id=\"history_2012\"></span>2012===\nIn the lead-up to the fair, government authorities warned that only Hai\u02bea were allowed to deal with religious issues at the fair, and non-Hai\u02bea religious activists would be held accountable. This was in response to severe disruption at previous fairs.<ref name=louts>{{cite news |last1=Arabia |first1=Crossroads |title=Saudi Authorities Crack Down on 'Book Fair Louts' |url=https://mideastposts.com/middle-east-society/saudi-authorities-crack-down-on-book-fair-louts/ |work=MidEast Posts}}</ref> There was also an announcement that women and single men would be allowed to attend simultaneously,<ref name=ghana/> for the first time.<ref name=Freitag>{{cite news |last1=Freitag |first1=Ulrike |title=International Book Fair in Riyadh: Treading the Line between Censorship and Cautious Change |url=https://en.qantara.de/content/international-book-fair-in-riyadh-treading-the-line-between-censorship-and-cautious-change |work=Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World |language=en}}</ref> The Deputy Culture Minister promised that religious police would not harass women who did not cover their faces this year.<ref name=boycott>{{cite web |title=(Don't) Boycott the Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2012/03/10/dont-boycott-the-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |website=& Arablit |language=en |date=9 March 2012}}</ref> Security was heavy, likely in response to the previous year's disruption.<ref name=fatwa />\n\nA poll found that women at the fair sought socially-critical novels, followed by studies on social and political issues and religious self-help books. Surprisingly, the fair had many books on the challenges the [[Arab Spring]] presented to Saudi Arabia, which were very popular.<ref name=Freitag />\n\nOn 11 March 2012, five days after the 11-day fair opened, 70 Saudi clerics issued a [[fatwa]] criticizing the book fair. They complained that the fair was uncensored, and thus allowed perverted literature which encourages ideological anarchy, including texts undermining the truths of Islam, and discussing deviant and [[Paganism|pagan]] religions, sex, and various abominations. They also criticized the fair for being [[Women's rights in Saudi Arabia#Sex segregation|mixed-gender]].<ref name=fatwa /> Religious conservatives did not disrupt the fair as in 2011.<ref name=Freitag />\n\nSyrian publishers were banned.<ref name=ghana>{{cite news |last1=Abdallah |first1=Mariam |title=Censorship Rife at Riyadh Book Fair |url=https://newsghana.com.gh/censorship-rife-at-riyadh-book-fair/ |work=Ghana News}}</ref><ref name=boycott />\n\n===2013===\nThe [[Arab Publishers Association]] unanimously resolved to boycott the 2013 fair, citing the exclusion of Syrian publishers from the fair, but also the price of stall space and barcode system installation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saad |first1=Mohammed |title=Arab Publishers Association boycotts Riyadh Book Fair - Arab - Books |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/18/107/63432/Books/Arab/Arab-Publishers-Association-boycotts-Riyadh-Book-F.aspx |work=Ahram Online |date=29 January 2013 |language=en}}</ref> The barcode system was abandoned the same day in a tweet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Controversy Even Months Before Opening of 2013 Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2013/01/30/controvers/ |work=& Arablit |date=30 January 2013 |language=en}}</ref> About 500 publishers, local and international, participated in the fair.<ref name=Oman/>\n\nSales-tracking devices for publishers have been described as a reaction to under-the-counter sales of banned books.<ref name= memorandum />\n\nWomen and single men were again allowed to attend simultaneously, and the Hai\u02bea announced that they would only be reporting problematic books to the Ministry, not confiscating them themselves.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi women given unprecedented permit to attend book fairs - with men |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/65786.aspx |work=Ahram Online |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\n[[File:MahmoudDarwish.jpg|thumb|Mahmoud Darwish's poetry books were confiscated during the fair, on grounds of blasphemy]]\nOver 570 publishers, local and international, participated.<ref name=Oman/>\n\n420 books were banned at the 2014 fair, and 10,000 copies of them were confiscated. The bans were described as prompting readers to download the banned books.<ref name=2014_bans>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia bans prominent Palestinian authors from Riyadh book fair |url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Saudi-Arabia-bans-prominent-Palestinian-authors-from-Riyadh-book-fair-345533 |work=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com}}</ref><ref name=downloads>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: 420 books banned at Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://freemuse.org/news/saudi-arabia-420-books-banned-at-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |website=Freemuse |date=18 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe late Palestinian poet [[Mahmoud Darwish]]'s books were confiscated during the fair, after the stall was surrounded by protesters. There were also complaints from religious police and allegations that the poems contained blasphemous passages.<ref name=protest>{{cite news |last1=Flood |first1=Alison |title=Saudi book fair bans 'blasphemous' Mahmoud Darwish works after protest |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/14/saudi-book-fair-bans-mahmoud-darwish-blasphemy |work=The Guardian |date=14 March 2014}}</ref> Similar actions were taken against works by well-known poets [[Badr Shaker al-Sayyab]], [[Abdul Wahab al-Bayati]], and [[Muin Bseiso]].<ref name=widerange /><ref name=2014_bans/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/robert-sharp/no-ambassador-its-not-med_b_7602740.html|archive-url=https://www.robertsharp.co.uk/2015/06/18/no-ambassador-its-not-meddling-to-call-for-free-speech-in-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=18 June 2015|title=No, Ambassador: It's Not 'Meddling' to Call for Free Speech in Saudi Arabia|website=HuffPost UK}}</ref>\n\nThe Arab Network for Research and Publishing, arriving at the former location of their stall on the Friday morning of the 2014 fair, found that it had been dismantled overnight, with their books confiscated, their materials scattered on the floor just outside, and the signage on their stall replaced by signage naming another publisher.<ref name=rocket /><ref name=booted>{{cite news |title=Saudi Publisher Booted From Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2014/03/12/saudi-publisher-booted-from-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |work=& Arablit |date=12 March 2014 |language=en}}</ref> The group's publishing focusses on nonfiction<ref name=booted /> about Saudi Arabia and political Islam. The books had been pre-approved, and most were sold in previous years; the reversal of the decision was attributed to the tenser political situation. The publisher was reportedly permanently banned from the fair.<ref name=rocket /><ref name=al-monitor>{{cite news |last1=Al-Rasheed |first1=Madawi |title=Saudi officials shut down display at book fair |url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/saudi-book-display-shut-down.html |work=Al-Monitor |date=13 March 2014 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=booted />\n\n[[Azmi Bishara]]'s books were also banned amid escalating tensions with Qatar.<ref name=widerange>{{cite news |title=Saudi bans books at fair in wide-ranging crackdown |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/2/8/96807/World/Region/Saudi-bans-books-at-fair-in-wideranging-crackdown.aspx |work=Ahram Online |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|date=16 March 2014 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=2014_bans /> Other banned books included ''[[Revolution 2.0]]'', by [[Wael Ghonim]], ''[[When will the Saudi Woman Drive a Car?]]'' by [[Abdullah Al Alami]],<ref name=crackdown>{{cite news |title=Saudi bans books at fair in crackdown |url=https://www.emirates247.com/news/region/saudi-bans-books-at-fair-in-crackdown-2014-03-16-1.541790 |work=www.emirates247.com |language=en}}</ref> and ''[[Al Estbdad]]'' (\"The Tyranny\"), by [[Ahmed bin Hamad al-Khalili]], the [[Grand Mufti]] of [[Oman]].<ref name=Oman>{{cite news |title=Riyadh fair bans Oman writer's book |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/oman/riyadh-fair-bans-oman-writers-book-1.1297227 |work=gulfnews.com |language=en}}</ref> The titles ''[[The History of Hijab]]'' and ''[[Feminism in Islam (book)|Feminism in Islam]]'' were also banned.<ref name=crackdown/>\n\n[[Madeha al-Ajroush]], a photographer and activist who campaigned for womens' right to drive, had an aisle at the fair named after her. The fair also featured a book on the driving protests, ''[[Sixth of November]]'', by [[Aisha al-Mana]] and [[Hissa al-Sheikh]].<ref name=Sixth>{{cite web |title=Sixth of November at the Riyadh Book Fair |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2014/03/13/sixth-of-november-at-the-riyadh-book-fair/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |date=13 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\n<!--The fair featured clowns for children and mobile ATM machines to reduce lineups.<ref name=Sudhnoti>{{cite web |title=Visit to International Book Fair: #Riyadh |url=https://publicawaz.blogspot.com/2015/03/visit-to-international-book-fair-riyadh.html |website=Voice of Sudhnoti |date=14 March 2015}}</ref>{{better source needed}} (this isn't a notable blogger) -->\nSales of the compilation book ''On the meaning of Arab Nationalism: Concepts & Challenges'' were permitted at the fair, but banned outside the fair.<ref name=memorandum /> Hai\u02bea presence was less conspicuous this year.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nA seminar entitled \"Youth and Arts... A Call for Coexistence\" was stopped by religious police after professor [[Mojab al-Zahrani]] condemned the destruction of monuments by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref name=idols>{{cite web |title=KSA: Members of the Saudi Religious Police (CPVPV \u2013 The Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice) Attacks a Seminar About Destroying Monuments |url=http://anhri.net/?p=141845&lang=en |date=9 March 2015 |agency=[[Arabic Network for Human Rights Information]]}}</ref><ref name=mixed_bag>{{cite web |title=The 2015 Riyadh International Book Fair: A Mixed Bag |url=https://arablit.org/2015/03/17/the-2015-riyadh-international-book-fair-a-mixed-bag/ |website=& Arablit |language=en |date=17 March 2015}}</ref> They accused the speaker of [[idolatry]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whitaker |first1=Brian |title=Where literary meets military |url=https://al-bab.com/blog/2016/03/where-literary-meets-military |work=al-bab.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe fair ended with a statement that anyone distributing printed materials, books or videos to visitors without prior authorization would face questioning by security authorities.<ref name=mixed_bag/>\n\n===2016===\n[[File:Villagers scour rubble for belongings scattered during the bombing of Hajar Aukaish - Yemen - in April 2015.jpg|thumb|The war in Yemen was a major theme of the 2016 fair]]\nThe 2016 fair was noted for its military themes, centered around the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]]<ref name=memorandum /> (which began in 2015). The Minister also praised the theater in his opening speech.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nThe opening day was noted for its international and rich local guests, and a temporary relaxation of gender segregation and women's dress codes, tightened again for the following days.<ref name=memorandum /> A Kuwaiti author was told not to smile, as this showed his dimples, which were considered seductive.<ref name=dimples>{{cite news |title=Liberated Saudi Youth Wonder Where All the Wahhabis Have Gone |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-14/liberated-saudi-youth-wonder-where-all-the-wahhabis-have-gone |work=Bloomberg Businessweek}}</ref><ref name=idols />\n\nThe US government was questioned about praise its diplomats gave the fair in light of anti-semitic texts on sale. The fair also included misogynistic books, such as ''[[Women Who Deserve to go to Hell]]'' by Mansour Abdel Hakim.<ref name=US-backed>{{cite news |last1=Speyer |first1=Lea |title=Human Rights Organization: Antisemitic Literature at US-Backed Riyadh Book Fair a 'Tragedy for the Jewish People' |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2016/04/05/human-rights-organization-antisemitic-literature-at-us-backed-riyadh-book-fair-a-tragedy-for-the-jewish-people/ |work=Algemeiner.com}}</ref><ref name=2016_report>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.state.gov/reports/2016-report-on-international-religious-freedom/saudi-arabia/ |website=United States Department of State}}</ref> The [[US State Department]] later condemned the anti-semitic books and other hate speech, distancing itself from the fair.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Speyer |first1=Lea |title=State Department Denies Knowledge of Antisemitic Material at Saudi Book Fair Attended by US Embassy Reps (Video) |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2016/04/06/state-department-denies-knowledge-of-antisemitic-material-at-saudi-book-fair-attended-by-us-embassy-reps-video/ |work=Algemeiner.com}}</ref>\n\nElectronic tracking of books was implemented in an attempt to prevent under-the-counter sales of unapproved books.<ref name=idols />\n\n''[[Journey to a Land Not Ruled By Allah]]'', by [[Ibrahim al-Tamimi]], was reported banned after conservatives [[Twitter|tweeted]] objections to it using the \"Campaign Against Atheist Accounts\" hashtag.<ref name=2016_report /> The fair's selection tended towards academic and technical subjects, avoiding books on sex, politics, and religion.<ref name=memorandum />\n\n===2017===\n[[Youssef Ziedan]]'s books were confiscated midway through the 2017 fair, which he attributed to his mention of the disputed Red Sea islands of [[Tiran Island|Tiran]] and [[Sanafir Island|Sanafir]].<ref name=muse />\n\n12 students of the Sekolah Seni Malaysia Johor Art School, performing a Malaysian folk dance, were interrupted by a heckler; other spectators told the heckler to leave the students alone. The religious police took prompt action and stopped the performance.<ref name=muse>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: Books banned, performance interrupted at book fair |url=https://freemuse.org/news/saudi-arabia-books-banned-performance-interrupted-book-fair/ |website=Freemuse}}</ref> A young Malaysian painted murals during the event.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alnufaie |first1=Hanan |title=Young Malaysian painter wins Saudi hearts at Riyadh Book Fair |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/art-and-culture/2017/03/17/Young-Malaysian-painter-wins-Saudi-hearts-at-Riyadh-Book-Fair-.html |work=english.alarabiya.net |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"history_2018\"></span>2018===\nHeld months after [[Women driving in Saudi Arabia|women were legally permitted to drive]], the fair featured a booth with a driving simulator for women.<ref name=economist>{{cite news |title=The red ink and the black: The unlikely rise of book fairs in the Gulf |url=https://www.economist.com/books-and-arts/2019/07/06/the-unlikely-rise-of-book-fairs-in-the-gulf |work=The Economist|date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nA publisher's stall was closed down, and the publisher banned from participating in the fair forever, for selling [[Muslim Brotherhood]] books, on grounds that these incited violence and terrorism.<ref name=algemeiner /> This was criticised; Jamal Khashoggi wrote: \"Liberals whose work was once censored or banned by [[Wahhabi]] hard-liners have turned the tables: They now ban what they see as hard-line, such as the censorship of various books at the Riyadh International Book Fair last month. One may applaud such an about-face. But shouldn't we aspire to allow the marketplace of ideas to be open?\"<ref name=blame>{{cite news |last1=Khashoggi |first1=Jamal |title=By blaming 1979 for Saudi Arabia's problems, the crown prince is peddling revisionist history |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/04/03/by-blaming-1979-for-saudi-arabias-problems-the-crown-prince-is-peddling-revisionist-history/ |work=Washington Post |date=3 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] documented the display of antisemitic conspiracy texts at the fair, and requested that texts that inflame hatred against Jews be treated in the same manner as the Muslim Brotherhood texts were.<ref name=algemeiner>{{cite web |title=Saudi Book Fair Called Out for Display of Antisemitic Titles, Including ''Mein Kampf'' |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2018/03/25/saudi-book-fair-called-out-for-display-of-antisemitic-titles-including-mein-kampf/ |website=Algemeiner.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wiesenthal Centre to Saudi Culture Minister: \"We are Distressed to Discover Vicious Antisemitic Conspiracy Texts on Display at the Riyadh Book Fair\" |url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/about/news/wiesenthal-centre-to-saudi.html |website=www.wiesenthal.com}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\n[[File:College of Law and Political Science (3) by Qrmoo3.jpg|thumb|The College of Law and Political Science at [[King Saud University]]; [[Anas al-Mazrou]], who was arrested shortly after speaking at the fair, lectured here]]\n<!--The 2019 fair took place at Riyadh International Convention and Exhibition Center, according to government-controlled media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1518681/saudi-arabia|title=Cultural minister: Riyadh book fair to kick off in April|date=2019-07-01|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-06}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>-->\n\n[[Anas al-Mazrou]], a law professor at [[King Saud University]], was arrested for speaking of the [[2018\u20132019 Saudi crackdown on feminists|detention of women's rights activists]] in Saudi Arabia during one of these panel discussions at the 2019 fair.<ref name=arrest>{{cite web |last1=Safi |first1=Michael |title=Saudi Arabia: arrests of dissidents and torture allegations continue |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/04/saudi-arabia-mass-arrests-of-dissidents-and-torture-allegations-continue |website=The Guardian |date=4 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi law professor arrested for criticising kingdom's human rights record: Report |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-law-professor-arrested-criticising-kingdoms-human-rights-record-report |work=Middle East Eye |language=en}}</ref> \"No one dares to ask, and I am not challenging anybody, including those who are sitting here on stage, to ask about the human rights activists,\" he said. He named four people as having \"contributed to spread the idea of human rights... I will give you an idea and I invite everybody to think about it; the idea of the nation being the guardian of itself, [such that the guardian] is the people, not the ruler\"<ref name=anas_quote>Translated quotation from ''The New York Times'': {{cite news |last1=Yee |first1=Vivian |last2=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |title=Saudis Escalate Crackdown on Dissent, Arresting Nine and Risking U.S. Ire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/05/world/middleeast/american-detainees-saudi-arabia.html |work=The New York Times |date=5 April 2019}}</ref> No information was given on where he was taken,<ref>{{cite web |title=Fresh wave of arrests in Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/04/saudi-arabia-new-wave-of-arrests-and-travel-bans-latest-assault-on-freedom-of-expression/ |website=www.amnesty.org |language=en}}</ref> and was described on 9 September as having had no contact with his family during this detainment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0631 Alnajjar |first1=\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0645\u0647 Omaima |title=Anas al-Mazrou |url=https://alqst.org/eng/amo-team/anas-al-mazrou/ |publisher=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0633\u0637 ALQST |language=en-US-QST | date=9 September 2019 | access-date= 21 March 2020}}</ref> The video{{efn|The video may be seen [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v&#61;WV3bbNq7Ma4 here] (Youtube).}} went [[viral video|viral]].<ref name=viral>{{cite news |last1=Qiblawi |first1=Tamara |title=Two US citizens arrested in first Saudi arrest sweep since Khashoggi killing, sources say |url=http://www.kabc.com/2019/04/05/two-us-citizens-arrested-in-first-saudi-arrest-sweep-since-khashoggi-killing-sources-say/ |work=KABC-AM |agency=CNN |date=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Simon Wiesenthal Center again complained that the fair sold anti-semitic texts, including Hitler's ''[[Mein Kampf]]''. They said that \"Of the six Arab Book Fairs we annually monitor, antisemitic texts are sadly the most numerous in Riyadh\", and asked the Saudi government to apply the same measures to \"all forms of hate, on the same level as offences to Islam\".<ref name=JerusalemPost>{{cite news |title=''Mein Kampf'' and antisemitic books found at Saudi Arabia book fair |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Jewish-rights-group-decries-sale-of-Nazi-books-at-Saudi-book-fair-585431 |work=The Jerusalem Post|date=1 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wiesenthal Centre to Saudi Media Minister: \"Ban Antisemitic Hate at the Riyadh International Book Fair\" |url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/about/news/2019_03_31_wiesenthal-centre-to-saudi.html |website=www.wiesenthal.com}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nIn July 2019, the Saudi Ministry of Culture announced that the 2020 fair would be held from 2 to 11 April<ref name=plans_2020>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abouther.com/node/20866/people/events/saudi-arabias-ministry-culture-announces-riyadh-book-fair-plans-2020|title=Saudi Arabia's Ministry of Culture Announces Riyadh Book Fair Plans for 2020|date=2019-07-16|website=About Her|language=en|access-date=2019-08-06}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref> at 'Riyadh Front'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arab.news/rpa4s|title=Saudi Culture Ministry chooses 'Riyadh Front' as book fair's new headquarters|date=2020-01-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref> However, on 5 March, the Ministry announced that the fair was postponed, as a precaution against [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the worldwide outbreak]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2165611/riyadh-intl-book-fair-postponed-over-coronavirus-fears|title=Riyadh Int'l Book Fair Postponed over Coronavirus Fears|website=Asharq Al-awsat|author-link=Asharq Al-Awsat|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\n<!--== Guest of Honour ==\n{{Third-party|section}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year \n!Guest \n|-\n|2019\n|Bahrain<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1466481/saudi-arabia|title=Riyadh book fair opens with Bahrain as guest of honor|date=2019-03-14|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|UAE<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1465866/saudi-arabia|title=Riyadh book fair starts 10-day run|date=2019-03-12|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|Malasiya<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1052131/saudi-arabia|title=Malaysia Guest-of-Honor at Riyadh International Book Fair 2017|date=2017-02-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|Greece<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/news/892966|title=Al-Toraifi opens Riyadh Book Fair 2016|date=2016-03-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Inauguration Ceremony of the 2015 Riyadh International Book Fair - News |url=https://www.mfa.gr/missionsabroad/en/saudi-arabia-en/news/inauguration-ceremony-of-the-2015-riyadh-international-book-fair.html |website=www.mfa.gr}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|South Africa\n|-\n|2014\n|Spain \n|-\n|2013\n|Morocco \n|-\n|2012\n|Sweden \n|-\n|2011\n|India \n|}\n-->\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Cairo International Book Fair]]\n*[[Jeddah International Book Fair]]\n\n\n[[Category:Book fairs in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Annual events in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Riyadh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Book-selling event in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n<!-- Do not remove this line! -->{{Infobox convention\n|name=Riyadh International Book Fair\n|status=Active|genre=Multi-genre\n|venue=[[Riyadh International Convention & Exhibition Center]]\n|location=[[Riyadh]]\n|country=[[Saudi Arabia]]\n|organizer=[[Ministry of Culture (Saudi Arabia)|Saudi Arabian Ministry of Culture]]<ref name=fatwa />\n|frequency=Annually, in mid-March to April\n|begins = Tuesday (an opening day, not open to the general public)<ref name=alarabiya_2011 />\n|ends = Saturday (the 10th day, not counting the opening day){{efn|Always stated to end on Saturday; because Tuesday is not open to the public, it is often stated to open on Wednesday.<ref name=Sudhnoti>{{cite web |title=Visit to International Book Fair: #Riyadh |url=https://publicawaz.blogspot.com/2015/03/visit-to-international-book-fair-riyadh.html |website=Voice of Sudhnoti |date=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://accucoms.com/events/riyadh-international-book-fair/ |website=ACCUCOMS}}</ref><ref name=2006_1_jeans/>}}\n|website= [[uniform resource locator|URL]] has changed<ref name=comsci />\n*2006-2007: https://www.riyadhbookfair.org/<ref>The [[Internet Archive]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20051101000000*/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/ 2006 website], [https://web.archive.org/web/20060622042039/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/English/index.htm mostly unarchived English version], [https://web.archive.org/web/20070210002607/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/ February 2007 website]; after that, it's held by [[domain squatter]]s.</ref>\n*2008-2019: https://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/<ref name=comsci /><ref>{{cite web |title=Wayback Machine |author=[[Internet Archive]] |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org.sa/ |website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n*2020: https://engage.moc.gov.sa/book-fair<!--OK, probably don't need a citation for this yet{{cn|date=January 2020}}-->\n|logo              = Riyadh International Book Fair 2019 logo.png<!--file must be downloaded and uploaded by a logged-in user using the \"upload file\" link in the sidebar-->\n|logo_alt          = \n|logo_caption      = ''Logo of the 2019 fair''\n|logo_size         = \n|image             = Riyadh-IBF-2020-logo-300x98.png\n|image_size        = 1.5\n|alt               = \n|caption           = ''Logo of the 2020 fair''}}\n\nThe '''Riyadh International Book Fair''' is an annual [[book fair]] in [[Saudi Arabia]]. It lasts 11 days<ref name=rocket /> and regularly attracts over a half million visitors (it is not the largest fair in the [[Middle East and North Africa|MENA]] region,<ref name=size>{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Mark |title=As western publishers look the other way millions attend Arab book fairs in February |url=https://thenewpublishingstandard.com/as-western-publishers-look-the-other-way-millions-attend-arab-book-fairs-in-february/ |website=The New Publishing Standard |date=24 February 2019}}</ref> contrary to some claims<ref>{{cite news |title=Riyadh International Bookfair 2018 |url=https://www.eyeofriyadh.com/events/details/riyadh-international-bookfair-2018 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=Eye of Riyadh |date=1 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301211303/https://www.eyeofriyadh.com/events/details/riyadh-international-bookfair-2018 |archive-date=1 March 2018 }}</ref>). The fair is used to showcase Saudi government policy,<ref name=economist /><ref name=memorandum /> and it has been a locus of political power struggles with the government.<ref name=fatwa /> Hundreds of publishers sell pre-approved books,<ref name=rocket/> and some black-market books.<ref name= memorandum /> Writers take part in literary events. Invited speakers and the public discuss intellectual and social issues. Disagreements sometimes go beyond the bounds of debate, with speakers being shouted down and surrounded by protestors,<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> and arrests of speakers and protestors;{{efn|See the [[#history_2011|account in this article of the 2011 fair]] and [[#history_2018|that of the 2018 fair]] (as well as some of the linked articles on authors and public intellectuals).}} physical assaults are rare but not unknown.<ref name=CPJ />\n\nThe fair is a focus for political conflict in Saudi Arabia,<ref name=fatwa /> though some local media sources deny there is political debate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Suleiman Shoqiran |first1=Fahad |title=Debate over intellectual freedoms and rights in Saudi Arabia |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/views/news/middle-east/2018/03/25/Debate-over-intellectual-freedoms-and-rights-in-Saudi-Arabia.html |work=english.alarabiya.net |date=25 March 2018 |language=en}} (author with close ties to Saudi-government-controlled media, '''not an independent source''')</ref> The fair is organized by the [[Ministry of Culture (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Culture and Information]],<ref name=fatwa /><ref name=2008_jeans /> and has been regulated by the [[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)|religious police]]; the two have clashed at the fair,<ref name=numbers /><ref name=fatwa /><ref name=2008_jeans /> and religious police have been limited to more advisory roles.<ref name=\"SW2010\" /> Some Saudi clerics issued a [[fatwa]] criticizing the book fair during the 2012 fair.<ref name=fatwa /> Journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] said of the intellectual climate: \"It's like [[McCarthyism]] in the 1950s\".<ref name=CPJ />\n\nThe fair has been both praised and criticized domestically for providing books and cultural activities which are hard to come by in Saudi Arabia,<ref name=fatwa /> and criticized internationally for selling [[Antisemitism|anti-semitic]] and [[Misogyny|misogynistic]] books.<ref name=JerusalemPost /><ref name=US-backed /><ref name=2016_report /> Parts of the fair are gender-segregated.{{efn|See the [[#restrictions_on_visitors|discussion in this article of restrictions on visitors]].}}\n\n== Activities ==\nThe fair aims to provide freer access to literature, and a large selection is available,<ref name=protest /> including some books banned or not usually sold in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=2006_1_jeans /><ref name=memorandum /> Protests about material at the fair are common.<ref name=protest /> While authorities pre-censor the books, they have sometimes confiscated previously-approved books during the fair.<ref name=rocket>{{cite web |last1=Omran |first1=Ahmed Al |title=Edgy Saudi Bans Local Publisher |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/middleeast/2014/03/12/edgy-saudi-bans-local-publisher/ |website=Wall Street Journal |date=12 March 2014}}</ref> Publishers say that they will be banned from the Saudi market if they speak openly about books being banned.<ref name=protest /> The book fair has become a topic of political controversy, praised for providing access to useful books and supporting culture and society, and criticized for insufficient, excessive, or inappropriate censorship.<ref name=fatwa>{{cite web |title=Saudi Clerics Criticize Book Fairs, Culture Events in the Country |url=https://www.memri.org/reports/saudi-clerics-criticize-book-fairs-culture-events-country |website=MEMRI |language=en}}</ref><ref name=protest /><ref name=JerusalemPost /> The traditional rarity of public events in Saudi Arabia, and the children's activities, help make it popular with the general public.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nApart from book sales, the fair also hosts writers, poets and intellectuals, who meet with the public. They sign books, take part in public discussion panels,<ref name=memorandum /> and give public lectures.<ref name=Freitag /> Authors give public readings of their works, without public discussion of the readings.<ref name=memorandum />\n\n<!--Historically, women were only allowed to attend during two designated half-days.<ref name=\"events\"/> no date given; 2009 date given by strong implication contradicts multiple more reliable sources.--> \nThere have been some gender-based <span id=\"restrictions_on_visitors\">restrictions on admission</span>: some times have been men-only,<ref name=2009_jeans>{{cite web |last1=Al Omran |first1=Ahmed |title=Riyadh Book Fair '09 |url=https://saudijeans.org/2009/03/07/riyadh-book-fair-09/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=7 March 2009}}</ref> others \"families-only\", meaning that single men may not enter.<!--Or single-gender groups; I [HLHJ] don't think single women or groups of women are allowed at all, but have found no explicit source on this--><ref name=2006_1_jeans>{{cite web |title=Exclusive: Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://saudijeans.org/2006/02/25/exclusive-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060301055132/http://saudijeans.blogspot.com/2006/02/exclusive-riyadh-international-book.html|archive-date=1 March 2006| url-status=dead <!-- seems to redirect oddly; even some archive copies slowly redirect --> |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=25 February 2006}}</ref> From 2008 to 2011 inclusive, there were four men-only evenings; the other times were open \"for all\", meaning only mixed-gender family groups (there were no women-only times).{{efn|See the [[#history|accounts in this article of individual years; there weren't women-only times<ref name=comsci/>]]}} In 2012, there were no segregated admission times, and men and families would be allowed to attend simultaneously for the first time.<ref name=ghana /><ref name=Freitag /> In practice, most schoolgroups attend in the mornings, and most of the evening visitors are men; women and families are common all day.<ref name=Freitag />\n\nSeparately, there are gender-based restrictions on activities within the fair. Book-signings and discussion panels generally have gender-segregated spaces.<ref name=memorandum>{{cite web |last1=Aldosari |first1=Hala |title=Riyadh Book Fair 2016: A Political Memorandum from New Rulers |url=https://agsiw.org/riyadh-book-fair-2016-a-political-memorandum-from-new-rulers/ |website=Arab Gulf States Institute in Washington |date=24 March 2016}}</ref> According to local media, men have been prevented from getting their books signed by female authors.<ref name=protest /><ref name=autograph>{{cite news |title=Saudi men arrested for seeking female writer's autograph - CNN.com |url=https://www.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/03/07/saudi.arabia.autograph/ |work=www.cnn.com}}</ref> \"If the author is a woman [male] people have to have their book signed through a third party so as to prevent her direct contact with the public\", the head of the Hai\u02bea at the fair explained in 2009.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> Female panelists participate in panels by intercom, which a panelist from outside Saudi Arabia found disconcerting.<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> Women listen to lectures from a balcony, when not giving them.<ref name=Freitag /> The book fair has been criticized for supporting [[Women's rights in Saudi Arabia#Sex segregation|gender mixing]].<ref name=fatwa/> In the childrens' areas, only women and children are allowed; men are strictly excluded.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /><ref name=SW2010/>\n\nThe fair has been patrolled by the [[Commission for the Promotion of Virtue and Prevention of Vice]] (Hai\u02bea, religious police), who enforce gender segregation and advise on dress.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> Men have been prevented from entering if their hair is too long.<ref name=protest /> Some of the men who have interrupted events have claimed to be members of the religious police.<ref name=\"events\">{{cite news |last1=Ammar |first1=Hassan |title=Saudi Arabia welcoming more cultural events |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29571507/ns/world_news-mideast_n_africa/t/saudi-arabia-welcoming-more-cultural-events/ |work=msnbc.com |agency=Associated Press |date=7 March 2009 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA book competition awards prizes of 100,000 Saudi Arabian riyals (roughly US$26,000, {{as of|lc=yes|2016}}). Until 2016, winners were selected by the [[Ministry of Information (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Information]], but in 2016 a group of [[King Saud University]] professors were made responsible.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nTemporary television studios are set up within the fair, and interview authors, and there are many roaming reporters and camera teams, but personal cameras were banned, {{as of|2012|lc=yes}}.<ref name=Freitag /><!-- so that's why this article has no photos... -->\n\n==Political context==\n[[File:Hesbah.jpg|thumb|right|A member of the religious police (right) speaking with member of the public in 2006. Religious police at the fair have worn plainclothes, including the [[Bisht (clothing)|bisht]] and unbound [[Keffiyeh|ghotra]] shown here.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Caryle |title=Saudi Arabia's Shifting Islamic Landscape |url=https://pulitzercenter.org/reporting/saudi-arabias-shifting-islamic-landscape#slideshow-15 |website=Pulitzer Center |language=en |date=3 April 2014}}</ref><!--not independent, but also supports: <ref name=repub>{{cite news |last1=Hawari |first1=Walaa |last2=Al-Dosary |first2=Shiekha |title=Women's Issues in the Middle East: Saudi Arabia: Frustrating experience |url=https://womenspillar.blogspot.com/2009/03/saudi-arabia-frustrating-experience.html |work=Women's Issues in the Middle East (apparently reprinting an [[Arab News]] report) |agency=Arab News (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''') |date=11 March 2009}}</ref>{{Third-party inline|date=December 2019}}--> The bisht is associated with power and religious position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Al-Mukhtar |first1=Rima |title=Traditional and modern: The Saudi man's bisht |url=https://www.arabnews.com/fashion/traditional-modern-saudi-mans-bisht |work=Arab News |date=7 November 2012 |language=en}}</ref>]]\n\nThe Riyadh bookfair is a focus of political conflict: its events are easier to understand in their political context. Power in Saudi Arabia is held by the monarch ({{as of|lc=yes|2020||df=}}, effectively the crown prince, [[Mohammed bin Salman]]), but traditionally also by the royal family, religious clerics, and the overlapping security services and business community, who have traditionally been allied.<ref name=\"moderate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/i-will-return-saudi-arabia-moderate-islam-crown-prince|title=I will return Saudi Arabia to moderate Islam, says crown prince|last1=Chulov|first1=Martin|date=24 October 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=cost>{{cite web |first1= |title=The High Cost of Change: Repression Under Saudi Crown Prince Tarnishes Reforms |url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/11/04/high-cost-change/repression-under-saudi-crown-prince-tarnishes-reforms |website=Human Rights Watch | language=en |date=4 November 2019}}</ref> These alliances are not holding as they once did,<ref name=moderate/><ref name=cost/> because the monarchy is centralizing power and weakening other power bases.<ref name=\"rattled_royals\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-jamal-khashoggi.html|title=Uproar Over Dissident Rattles Saudi Royal Family|last1=Hubbard|first1=Ben|date=19 October 2018|work=The New York Times|last2=Kirkpatrick|first2=David D.}}</ref><ref name=cost/>\n\nThe general public and the media (including newspapers and book publishers) hold little [[Formal organization|formal power]], but their potential power has been a matter of official concern. Since the 1920s, the monarchy had repeatedly promised democratic reforms and [[constitutional monarchy]]; however, in the 2010s, it affirmed [[absolute monarchy]].<ref name=absolute>{{cite web |last1=Alaoudh |first1=Abdullah |title=Saudi Arabia's crown prince is taking the kingdom back to the Dark Ages |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/07/19/saudi-arabias-crown-prince-is-taking-the-kingdom-back-to-the-dark-ages/ |website=Washington Post |language=en |date=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Royal family===\nThere has been a power struggle between the monarchy and the royal family. Royals often hold official posts, in government or academia. Some of the authors and public intellectuals at the fair are thus members of the royal family (for instance, [[Al-Zahrani]] is the name of the third royal family, and the name of a law professor who became involved in two clashes with clergy at the book fair). The large royal family has recently lost political power.<ref name=\"royals_lose\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/11/06/562393761/what-changes-in-saudi-arabias-political-power-mean-for-u-s-saudi-relations|title=What Changes In Saudi Arabia's Political Power Mean For U.S.-Saudi Relations|website=NPR.org|language=en}}</ref> Royal officials have been replaced by officials beholden to the crown prince.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://agsiw.org/saudi-arabia-reassigns-roles-within-a-more-centralized-monarchy/|title=Saudi Arabia Reassigns Roles within a More Centralized Monarchy|last1=Smith Diwan|first1=Kristin|date=22 January 2019|website=Arab Gulf States Institute in Washington}}</ref> In 2018, members of the royal family and business community were placed under house arrest,<ref name=\"rattled_royals\" /> required to sign over assets to the government, and restricted in their movements; there are reports some were physically abused, which the government denies<ref name=\"clerics\" /><ref name=\"billions\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/11/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-corruption-mohammed-bin-salman.html|title=Saudis Said to Use Coercion and Abuse to Seize Billions|last1=Hubbard|first1=Ben|date=11 March 2018|work=The New York Times|last2=Kirkpatrick|first2=David D.|last3=Kelly|first3=Kate|last4=Mazzetti|first4=Mark}}</ref><ref name=\"fun\">{{Cite journal|title=Radical reforms in Saudi Arabia are changing the Gulf and the Arab world, Radical reforms in Saudi Arabia are changing the Gulf and the Arab world|url=https://www.economist.com/special-report/2018/06/21/radical-reforms-in-saudi-arabia-are-changing-the-gulf-and-the-arab-world|journal=The Economist}}</ref> (torture is illegal in Saudi Arabia<ref name=\"crush\" />).<!-- The (~35<ref name=obit>{{cite news |last1=al-Rasheed |first1=Madawi |title=King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/22/king-abdullah-of-saudi-arabia |work=The Guardian |date=22 January 2015}}</ref>) children of [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]], who died in 2015, seem to have been especial targets.<ref name=billions>{{cite news |last1=Hubbard |first1=Ben |last2=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |last3=Kelly |first3=Kate |last4=Mazzetti |first4=Mark |title=Saudis Said to Use Coercion and Abuse to Seize Billions |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/11/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-corruption-mohammed-bin-salman.html |work=The New York Times |date=11 March 2018}}</ref>--> Subsequently, the stipends paid to members of the royal family were secretly increased.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-02-01/saudis-are-said-to-raise-allowances-for-some-royals-after-purge|title=Saudis Raise Allowances for Some Royals after Purge|last1=Nereim|first1=Vivian|date=1 February 2018|work=www.bloomberg.com|agency=Bloomberg|last2=Martin|first2=Matthew}}</ref>\n\n===Clerical officials===\nThere has also been a power struggle between the monarchy and clerical officials. Clerical officials control education and the judiciary (though the monarch may issue pardons). Clerical officials traditionally censored journalists and publications, through control of the [[Ministry of Interior (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Interior]] ''(sic)''.<ref name=\"CPJ\" /> The Ministry of Interior also formerly had oversight of religious police, but lost it in the early 2010s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/13/saudi-arabia-says-religious-police-must-be-gentle-and-humane|title=Saudi Arabia says religious police must be 'gentle and humane'|first=Associated|last=Press|date=13 April 2016|via=www.theguardian.com|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> In 2017, the internal security forces and the powerful prosecution service were transferred from the control of the ministry to the direct control of the monarchy.<ref name=\"cost\" /> The powers of the clerical officials at the book fair have been increasingly restricted; for instance, the religious police have lost the power to enforce rules, retaining only the power to report violations, and government-controlled media report that members of the religious police disrupting book fair events in the 2010s were arrested.<ref name=\"SW2010\" />\n\n===Media===\n[[File:JamalKahshoggi.png|thumb|left|Journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] said of the intellectual climate: \"It's like [[McCarthyism]] in the 1950s\".<ref name=CPJ />]]\n\nEditors-in-chief in Saudi Arabia are appointed only with government approval, and work to guidelines on how stories are to be covered. Newspapers are post-censored; the government can blacklist any journalist in Saudi Arabia, preventing them from working anywhere in the country, and it can have online articles taken down.<ref name=\"CPJ\" /> Journalists have also been arrested, kept in [[solitary confinement]], and tortured, often for unclear reasons.<ref name=\"arrests\">{{cite news |last1=Yee |first1=Vivian |title=Saudi Arabia Is Stepping Up Crackdown on Dissent, Rights Groups Say |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/26/world/middleeast/saudi-arrests-journalists-activists.html |work=The New York Times |date=26 November 2019}}</ref> Journalists often attend the fair as book authors. One journalist attributed a clash with the religious police (Hai\u02bea) at the fair to her newspaper columns;<ref name=\"backfire\" /> she had criticized the Hai\u02bea,<ref name=\"backfire\" /> as Hai\u02bea-affiliated power over censorship weakened.<ref name=\"backfire\" /> Books and entire publishing houses are also censored; anyone wanting mass access to the Saudi Arabian market needs the approval of the censors.<ref name=\"algemeiner\" /><ref name=\"protest\" />\n\nThe book fair programme is set by the monarchy, which uses it to showcase its policies;<ref name= memorandum /><ref name=economist /> the monarchy also pre-censors the books to be legally sold.<ref name=rocket/> The event is regulated by the religious police, who have set admission rules, post-censored and confiscated books, and shut down events.<ref name= memorandum /><ref name=2006_1_jeans />\n\nCensorship at the book fair, as elsewhere, has become less religious and more political in its goals, as it has been transferred from clerical to monarchic control. Social liberals have at times defended the freedom of speech of social conservatives, who now face heavier censorship at the fair and elsewhere.<ref name=blame/> Informal media also face stronger restrictions; people have been jailed and tortured for blog posts and tweets.<ref name=lib_not_dem/><ref name=crush>{{cite news |last1=Mazzetti |first1=Mark |last2=Hubbard |first2=Ben |title=It Wasn't Just Khashoggi: A Saudi Prince's Brutal Drive to Crush Dissent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/world/middleeast/khashoggi-crown-prince-saudi.html |work=The New York Times |date=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=clerics>{{cite news |last1=Hubbard |first1=Ben |title=Saudi Arabia Detains Critics as New Crown Prince Consolidates Power |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/14/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-clerics.html |work=The New York Times |date=14 September 2017}}</ref> Blogs, social media, and [[satellite TV]] hinder censorship;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nolan |first1=Leigh |title=Managing reform? Saudi Arabia and the king's dilemma |url=https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/05_saudi_arabia_nolan.pdf |publisher=Brookings Doha Center |date=May 2011}}</ref>{{rp|5}} books banned from the book fair are discussed online, and available to many through illegal downloads.<ref name=downloads />\n\nThe Saudi government has spent millions on influencing foreign media coverage, especially in the wake of [[Jamal Khashoggi]]'s 2018 death. Efforts have focussed on improving its international image, attracting [[Tourism in Saudi Arabia|tourists]], and promoting tourist attractions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Massoglia |first1=Anna |title=Saudi Arabia ramped up multi-million foreign influence operation after Khashoggi's death |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/news/2019/10/saudi-arabia-ramped-up-foreign-influence-after-khashoggi/ |website=OpenSecrets News |publisher=The Center for Responsive Politics |date=2 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thebault |first1=Reis |last2=Mettler |first2=Katie |title=Instagram influencers partied at a Saudi music festival \u2014 but no one mentioned human rights | work=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/12/23/instagram-influencers-partied-saudi-arabian-music-festival-no-one-mentioned-human-rights/ |date=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Public opinion===\n[[File:Saudipop.svg|thumb|The population of Saudi Arabia is young, and youth unemployment of Saudi citizens is generally 20 to 30%, higher for women,<ref name=unshackle /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nereim |first1=Vivian |title=Saudi Unemployment Falls to 3-Year Low While Expat Exodus Slows |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-15/saudi-arabia-s-unemployment-falls-to-lowest-in-over-three-years |work=www.bloomberg.com |date=15 December 2019}}</ref> though there are doubts about the reliability of government statistics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dudley |first1=Dominic |title=Rising Unemployment Suggests Saudi Government Reforms Are Failing |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dominicdudley/2016/12/08/saudi-unemployment/ |work=Forbes |language=en}}</ref>]]\n\n[[File:Riyadh population graph RU.PNG|thumb|The population of Riyadh is growing rapidly]]\nVisitors to the fair (both the public and the writers and intellectuals) seek to evade censorship, buy and sell books, including blackmarket books,<ref name= memorandum /><ref name=2006_1_jeans /> and take part in discussions.<ref name=anas_quote /> They come into conflict with both the monarchy and the religious police, as well as one another.<ref name=SW2010 />\n\nTraditionally, the monarchy has presented itself as a progressive force, prevented from moving quickly with liberalizing reforms by the strong conservatism of the population;<ref name=\"opendem\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/5050/saudi-response-to-arab-spring-containment-and-co-option/|title=The Saudi response to the 'Arab spring': containment and co-option|website=openDemocracy}}</ref> by implication, if the country were to become democratic, then it would become much more radically conservative. This view has been challenged domestically.<ref name=moderation/> It has also been suggested that the monarchy seeks to hinder a unified Saudi political movement by playing up [[:Category:Tribes of Saudi Arabia|tribalism]] and [[sectarianism|sectarian]] religious differences, and by associating demonstrations, [[civil disobedience]] and criticism with foreign actors.<ref name=\"opendem\" /><ref name=moderation>{{cite web |title='Moderation' requires tolerance, acceptance of others, free speech and human rights |url=https://alqst.org/eng/moderation-requires-tolerance-acceptance-others-free-speech-human-rights/ |website=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0633\u0637 |language=en-US-QST |date=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2005 there were petitions for human rights and a [[constitutional monarchy]].<ref name=obit>{{cite news |last1=al-Rasheed |first1=Madawi |title=King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jan/22/king-abdullah-of-saudi-arabia |work=The Guardian |date=22 January 2015}}</ref> During the [[Arab Spring]], the [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests]], these were renewed, with public appeals and petitions for democracy.<ref name=absolute /><ref>{{cite web |title=The Arab Revolution Saudi Update |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2011/02/18/the-arab-revolution-saudi-update/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |author=Eman al-Nafjan |date=18 February 2011|author-link=Eman al-Nafjan }}</ref> Calls for reform were driven by corruption, official impunity, detention without trial, high unemployment, and royal excesses.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Caryle |title=Will the House of Saud adapt enough to survive ... again? {{!}} The Star |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2011/02/12/will_the_house_of_saud_adapt_enough_to_survive_again.html |website=thestar.com |language=en}}</ref> [[Foreign workers in Saudi Arabia]], who make up ~30% of the population (official census figures, {{as of|lc=yes|2014}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method%3Dhome.regcon%26contentID%3D2010112487888%26archiveissuedate%3D24%2F11%2F2010|title=Census shows Kingdom's population at more than 27 million|date=24 November 2010|publisher=Saudi Gazette|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006080326/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2010112487888&archiveissuedate=24%2F11%2F2010|archivedate=6 October 2014|accessdate=2014-11-20|df=dmy}}</ref> have [[Kafala system|limited rights]] and are disenfranchised, an additional potential source of unrest.<ref name=collapse/>\n\nThere was also significant activism on [[Saudi anti male-guardianship campaign|guardianship rules]], women's franchise, the right to drive, and the rights of political prisoners.<ref name=\"opendem\" /> A 2013 petition called for women to be permitted to drive<ref>{{cite news |title=Dozens of Saudi Arabian women drive cars on day of protest against ban |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/26/saudi-arabia-woman-driving-car-ban |work=The Guardian |date=26 October 2013}}</ref> (a position which a [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] poll found that the majority of Saudi men and women supported in 2007,<ref name=\"Gallup\">{{cite web |author=Gallup |title=Saudi Arabia: Majorities Support Women's Rights |url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/103441/saudi-arabia-majorities-support-womens-rights.aspx |website=Gallup.com |language=en-us |date=21 December 2007}}</ref> contradicting a 2006 government poll finding 89% of women opposed it<ref name=\"unshackle\">{{cite news |title=Unshackling themselves, Unshackling themselves |url=https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2014/05/17/unshackling-themselves |work=The Economist}}</ref>). Some petitions, like a 2016 one to [[Saudi anti male-guardianship campaign|abolish the male guardianship system]], were supported by clerics and social liberals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sidahmed |first1=Mazin |title=Thousands of Saudis sign petition to end male guardianship of women |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/26/saudi-arabia-protest-petition-end-guardianship-law-women |work=The Guardian |date=26 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Are we or aren't we? |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2011/02/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |author=Eman al-Nafjan |language=en|author-link=Eman al-Nafjan }}</ref> \n\nThe monarchy has taken action against independent and opposition clerics, usually on the grounds that they support extremism or terrorism. It has arrested clerics of a variety of political views, including some who have supported religious tolerance and opposed travel to fight in war zones,<ref name=\"overt_support\" /> and those supporting electoral democracy.<ref name=\"Muslim_Brotherhood\">{{cite news |last1=Lacroix |first1=St\u00e9phane |title=Saudi Arabia's Muslim Brotherhood predicament |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2014/03/20/saudi-arabias-muslim-brotherhood-predicament/ |work=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> Generally, overt support of crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] is required: in some cases, this includes performing specific requested acts of support.<ref name=\"cost\" /> The clerics who are tolerated all support the crown prince, though they vary in their other views.<ref name=\"overt_support\">{{cite news |last1=Ismail |first1=Raihan |title=How is MBS's consolidation of power affecting Saudi clerics in the opposition? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/06/04/how-is-mohammads-consolidation-power-affecting-oppositional-saudi-clerics/ |work=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> This has entailed dramatic shifts in the monarchy's attitude to groups like the [[Sahwa movement]] and the [[Muslim Brotherhood]], to whom it had formerly given official positions and influence; one such shift was marked by the banning of all Muslim Brotherhood books from the book fair.<ref name=\"Muslim_Brotherhood\" /> \n\nMore such shifts have been seen on women's driving. In 2006, a politician was shouted down for raising the topic at the fair;<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> in 2014, a driving activist had an aisle at the fair named after her;<ref name=Sixth/> in 2017, the government announced that women would be allowed to drive, in 2018, the fair featured a driving simulator for women, women were allowed to drive,<ref name=economist/> non-activist women were asked to publicly thank the government so that the change would not appear to be a victory for the activists,<ref name=moderation/> and many activists who had campaigned for the right to drive were arrested (including activists honoured in 2014); in 2019, a professor was arrested after expressing support of the still-detained activists at a fair discussion panel.<ref name=viral/><ref name=anas_quote/>\n\n===Reforms: social liberalization, political restriction===\nSince these protests, the monarchy's message has begun to shift. It is now enacting socially-liberalizing reforms, against the opposition of more conservative elements of the clergy, breaking the alliance with some hardline clerics.<ref name=\"blame\" /><ref name=\"moderate\" /> There is a drive to provide leisure opportunities for young people; movie theaters and music concerts are now permitted, and fashion, art, and sport promoted.<ref name=\"fun\" /><ref name=\"lib_not_dem\" /> The heavily-promoted book fair also provides officially-sanctioned cultural activities, and some social restrictions at the fair have been relaxed (such as women's dress codes and gender segregation).<ref>See details in [[#history_2012|the section of this article about the 2012 fair]], for instance.</ref>\n\nViews on these social reforms seem to vary: young urban citizens tend to be more in favour, while conservatively religious citizens, who tend to come from specific rural areas, are more likely to oppose them.<ref name=\"lib_not_dem\">{{Cite web|url=http://afsa.org/saudi-arabia-liberalization-not-democratization|title=Saudi Arabia: Liberalization, Not Democratization|website=afsa.org}}</ref> Economic reforms, driven by falling oil prices, have varying levels of support, and a poor economy is a source of discontent.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shahine |first1=Alaa |last2=Nereim |first2=Vivian |last3=Abu-Nasr |first3=Donna |title=Saudi Arabia's Great Makeover Can't Afford to Fail This Time |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-10-16/saudi-arabia-s-great-makeover-can-t-afford-to-fail-this-time |website=www.bloomberg.com |publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref name=\"collapse\">{{cite news |author=Guest Contributor |title=What If Saudi Arabia Collapses? |url=https://lobelog.com/what-if-the-state-of-saudi-arabia-collapses/ |work=LobeLog |date=10 August 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe social reforms are widely seen as a way to reduce activist pressure for reforms of political power structures (such as a greater popular voice in government).<ref name=\"lib_not_dem\" /> The monarchy is simultaneously taking harsher measures against dissent. Regardless of how liberal or conservative they are,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fahim |first1=Kareem |title=Saudi Arabia's once-powerful conservatives silenced by reforms and repression |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/saudi-arabias-once-powerful-conservatives-silenced-by-reforms-and-repression/2018/06/04/5332bdec-3dad-11e8-955b-7d2e19b79966_story.html |website=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> activists who call for political reforms have been jailed and tortured, even when they have advocated,<ref name=\"wrong_people\">{{cite news |last1=Khashoggi |first1=Jamal |title=Saudi Arabia's crown prince wants to 'crush extremists.' But he's punishing the wrong people. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2017/10/31/saudi-arabias-crown-prince-wants-to-crush-extremists-but-hes-punishing-the-wrong-people/ |work=Washington Post |language=en}}</ref> or worked with the government on, reforms the government has enacted.<ref name=\"8detained\">{{cite news |last1=Batrawy |first1=Aya |title=Activists: Saudi Arabia detains eight in sustained crackdown |url=https://apnews.com/40f0c42d68a04320a05c28eca6797483 |work=AP NEWS |date=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"arrests\" /> The government has also arrested academics expressing critical views (for instance, questioning government economic projections),<ref name=\"cost\" /> including at the fair.<ref name=\"arrest\" />\n\n==History==\n\n===2004===\nThe 2004 fair (advertised as the tenth<ref name=2004_1_jeans>{{cite web |title=Not Fair! |url=https://saudijeans.org/2004/09/19/not-fair/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=19 September 2004}}</ref>) had 300 publishers from 14 (mostly Arab) countries; there was one Iraqi publisher.<ref name=2004_jeans>{{cite web |title=The Book Fair Report |url=https://saudijeans.org/2004/09/30/the-book-fair-report/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=30 September 2004}}</ref>\n\n===2006===\n[[File:\u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u0649 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u0648\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0644\u0641\u0632\u064a\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0635\u0631\u064a.jpg|thumb|[[Mustafa Mahmoud]] published ''Dialogue with an Atheist'' in 1974; at the 2006 fair, it went on display in Saudi Arabia for the first time]]\nThe Saudi government (through the [[Ministry of Higher Education (Saudi Arabia)|Ministry of Higher Education]]) was involved with organizing the event for the first time in 2006;<ref name=2008_jeans /> the Riyadh Exhibitions Company said that they had signed a co-operation agreement.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u0639\u0631\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 Riyadh International Book Fair |url=http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/r_1.htm |publisher=Riyadh Exhibitions company |date=7 February 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060207015210/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/r_1.htm |archive-date=7 February 2006 }} (official fair website '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\nSome days were restricted to \"families-only\" attendance, meaning that single men were not allowed to enter.<!--Bizarrely, the official site just gives opening times and does not mention this segregation, though attendees do: https://web.archive.org/web/20060207015210/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org/r_1.htm--> The 2006 fair was held in the Riyadh Exhibition Center.<ref name=2007_jeans /><ref>{{cite web |title=Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://www.khaled.us/riyadh-international-book-fair.html |website=Khaled rambles |date=17 February 2006}}</ref>\n\nBooths of foreign publishers, such as [[Dar Al Saqi]], [[The Arabic Cultural Center]], [[Dar Al Jamal]], the [[Arab Establishment of Research and Publishing]], and [[Dar Al Mada]], were popular.<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> Copies of the novel ''[[Banat al-Riyadh]]'' (\"Girls of Riyadh\") were unexpectedly absent; it was not clear whether it had been banned<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> or had sold out, although a representative of the publisher said it had not sold out, according to [[Asharq Al-Awsat|a Saudi government-run London newspaper]]. The same paper reported that ''[[The Dolphin's Trip]]'' and ''[[Abdullah Thabit|Terrorist Number 20]]'' were banned, while the ''[[New Testament]]'' and ''[[Mustafa Mahmoud|Dialogue with an Atheist]]'' were on display for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: Copies of ''Girls of Riyadh'' Novel Mysteriously Disappear from Book Fair |url=https://eng-archive.aawsat.com/theaawsat/news-middle-east/saudi-arabia-copies-of-girls-of-riyadh-novel-mysteriously-disappear-from-book-fair |website=eng-archive.aawsat.com |author= Asharq Al-Awsat|language=en|author-link=Asharq Al-Awsat }} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref><!--{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}}--> [[Turki Al-Hamad]]'s novel ''[[Reeh Al-Jannah]]'' was also missing.<ref name=2006_1_jeans />\n\nSome official speakers and debate topics were controversial, touching on pressing political issues, and debates were heated.<ref name=2008_jeans /> A discussion panel was disrupted by hecklers who shouted down a member of the [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia]]<ref name=globalvoices/> ([[Mohammed Al-Zulfa]]<ref name=2006_1_jeans />) speaking at the fair<ref name=globalvoices/> on women's driving.<ref name=quiet>{{cite web |last1=Arabia |first1=Crossroads |title=Riyadh Book Fair off to Quiet Start |url=http://xrdarabia.org/blog/archives/2007/02/28/riyadh-book-fair-off-to-quiet-start/ |date=21 March 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070321174524/http://xrdarabia.org/blog/archives/2007/02/28/riyadh-book-fair-off-to-quiet-start/ |archive-date=21 March 2007 }}</ref> A discussion on censorship, whose panelists included former Information Minister [[Muhammad Abdo Yamani]] and pro-government editor [[Turki al-Sudeiri]], was shouted down by protestors, who also surrounded the panellists and physically assaulted at least one journalist.<ref name=CPJ>{{cite news |last1=Campagna |first1=Joel |title=Saudi Arabia report: Princes, Clerics, and Censors |url=https://cpj.org/reports/2006/05/saudi-06.php |work=cpj.org |agency=Committee to Protect Journalists |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2007===\nThe 2007 fair was held in the same location as the 2006 one, and the topics selected for the cultural programme were described as less controversial.<ref name=2007_jeans />\n\nIn 2007, Abdul-Aziz al-Sabeel, deputy minister of information for cultural affairs, announced that the \"families-only\" days would be dropped: three evenings were open for men only; the rest would be open to all. The ministry and the religious police were said to have negotiated this change.<ref name=2007_jeans>{{cite web |title=Saudi Jeans: Let's Meet and Talk |url=http://saudijeans.blogspot.com/2007/02/lets-meet-and-talk.html |date=15 November 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115004540/http://saudijeans.blogspot.com/2007/02/lets-meet-and-talk.html |archive-date=15 November 2007 }}</ref><ref name=globalvoices>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: 2007 Riyadh International Book Fair, Ahmadinejad's Visit to the Kingdom, and More |url=https://globalvoices.org/2007/03/07/saudi-arabia-2007-riyadh-international-book-fair-ahmadinejads-visit-to-the-kingdom-and-more/ |website=Global Voices |language=en |date=7 March 2007}}</ref> However, it is not clear that this actually occurred; it later emerged that fair periods scheduled as \"open for all\" meant open to mixed-gender family groups only.<ref name=comsci />\n\n===2008===\nThe 2008 fair was held at the Riyadh International Exhibition Center in Morouj Dist, and featured less controversial speakers and topics than the 2006 fair.<ref name=2008_jeans>{{cite web |last1=Al Omran |first1=Ahmed |title=Riyadh International Book Fair: Could Be Better |url=https://saudijeans.org/2008/03/09/riyadh-international-book-fair-could-be-better/ |website=Saudi Jeans |language=en |date=9 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Society for Human Rights]] offered a report on the state of human rights in Saudi Arabia at the fair. There were separate opening hours for men and mixed-gender family groups,<ref name=2008_jeans /> with four evenings reserved for men only.<ref name=2008_sched>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u0639\u0631\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 2008 |url=http://www.riyadhbookfair.org.sa/Sections.aspx?id=7 |date=14 March 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080314125753/http://www.riyadhbookfair.org.sa/Sections.aspx?id=7|archive-date = 14 March 2008}} (official schedule; '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\nThe US Embassy in Riydh participated, hosting a \"US Information Resource Center\" booth.<ref name=\"wikileak\">{{cite web |last1=Al-Omran |first1=Ahmed |title=Some of the 'Less Boring' Saudi Wikileaks Cables |url=https://mideastposts.com/middle-east-society/some-of-the-less-boring-saudi-wikileaks-cables/ |website=MidEastPosts.com}}</ref> The booth sold 1,829 copies of 66 pre-approved publications; Embassy officials were surprised by the positive response to their presence, and strong interest in English-language teaching materials and American literature.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Audiences Reached at Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/08RIYADH618_a.html |publisher=Wikileaks |date=2008}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\n[[File:Halema Muzaffar.jpg|thumb|There was controversy over events at journalist Halimah Matafar's book-signing]]\nIn 2009, the fair moved to the much larger<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> Riyadh International Exhibition Center on King Abdullah Road,<ref name=2009_jeans /> and ran from Thursday 3<ref name=\"events\" /> until 13 March.<ref name=2009_jeans /> Four evenings were men-only and the rest were \"for all\", according to the official conference schedule.<ref name=2009_sched>{{cite web |title=Riyadh-Book-Fair |url=http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/english/Pages/index.aspx |publisher=KSA Ministry of Culture and Information |date=16 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216090537/http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/english/Pages/index.aspx |archive-date=16 December 2009 }} ('''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\nSaudi newspapers, which are government-controlled,<ref name=CPJ /> reported that prices of books from non-Saudi publishing houses were up 20 to 25%, due to the costs of transportation, rental of space at the fair, and other factors. They said that some books that had previously been permitted were banned, and some previously banned were permitted, and that visitors were required to show the receipts for their books on the way out.<ref name=high_prices>{{cite news |title=High prices, Hai'a dampen spirits at Riyadh Book Fair |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527190648/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2009030731368 |archive-date=27 May 2009 |url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentID=2009030731368| url-status=dead |work=Saudi Gazette |date=27 May 2009}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref> The government-controlled ''[[Saudi Gazette]]'' also reported that books by [[Abdel Rahman Badawi]] an [[Amin Maalouf]] were missing from the fair.<ref name=repub /> Dar al-Jamal, an Iraqi publisher previously popular at the fair,<ref name=2006_1_jeans /> was banned.<ref name=ghana />\n\nReligious scholars condemned the fair for inviting [[Mohammed Abed al-Jabri]]. At the fair, al-Jabri said that religious groups sought to monopolise religious authority, by restricting the ability of civic groups to defend religious beliefs.<ref name=backfire />\n\nAccording to accounts in Saudi newspapers,{{refn|name=HMciting|Aside from a blog,<ref name=tanjara /> only domestic (and thus Saudi-government-controlled) media give names of all three men;<ref name=high_prices/><ref name=repub /> Associated Press says three men but gives one name;<ref name=\"events\" /> CNN says only two were arrested, but cite the Saudi reports.<ref name=autograph /> A reprinting of a domestic media article<ref name=repub /> carries a great deal of detail on the incident, including what appear to be interviews with the participants. It contradicts another source on whether the journalist was trying to give books to her colleagues, and had to pass them via a male security guard,<ref name=repub /> or the male writers had bought books and passed them to her via a male security guard.<ref name=high_prices/> All the accounts seem to be by or based upon domestic media.}} on Thursday the 5th,<ref name=2009_jeans /> local journalist [[Halimah Matafar]]'s<!--is this romanization correct per [[Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Arabic]]?--> ([[:ar:\u062d\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0629 \u0645\u0638\u0641\u0631|ar]]) book-signing was surrounded by five security men, six policemen and two religious policemen.<ref name=\"events\" /><ref name=backfire>{{cite news |last1=Mahdi |first1=Wael |title=New-look book fair backfires on writers |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/new-look-book-fair-backfires-on-writers-1.582309 |work=The National |date=24 March 2009 |language=en}}</ref> <!--The books had to be passed between the author and men wanting autographs via a (male) fair security guard.<ref name=high_prices/><ref name=repub />{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}}--> They report that some male writers<ref name=\"events\" /> had their books signed; as they left, one waved and said \"Thank you and goodbye\" to the author,<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009>{{cite web |title=Riyadh Book Fair 2009 |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2009/03/08/riyadh-book-fair-2009/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |date=8 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"events\" /> and religious police accused him of addressing an unrelated woman.<ref name=\"events\" /> Satirical novelist and journalist<ref>{{cite web |title=Abdo Khal: International Prize for Arabic Fiction |url=https://www.arabicfiction.org/en/Abdo-Khal |website=www.arabicfiction.org}}</ref> [[Abdo Khal]] and poet [[Abdullah al-Thabet]]<ref name=booted /><ref>{{cite news |title=If You're in the KSA: The Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2010/02/20/if-youre-in-the-ksa-the-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |work=& Arablit |date=20 February 2010 |language=en}}</ref> (and law professor [[Mojab al-Zahrani]], according to some accounts<ref name=tanjara>{{cite web |title=The tanjara: Religious[sic] police and censorship cause discontent at Riyadh book fair |url=https://thetanjara.blogspot.com/2009/03/religous-police-and-censorship-cause.html |website=the tanjara |date=10 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=high_prices/>) complained that they were then verbally abused and taken to the religious police center;<ref name=\"events\" /> they were released without charge the same day. Halimah Matafar said that she was the only woman at the fair treated in this manner; she attributed it to her criticism (in her weekly column) of the religious police: \"I felt like I was wearing an explosive belt, not signing books... If any first-time female writer was surrounded by this many policemen, she would be discouraged,\" she said.<ref name=backfire />\n\nDuring the 8th, a woman visiting with her family found only one stall staffed by a woman<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> (likely Najet Mield, per state-controlled sources<ref name=repub>{{cite news |last1=Hawari |first1=Walaa |last2=Al-Dosary |first2=Shiekha |title=Women's Issues in the Middle East: Saudi Arabia: Frustrating experience |url=https://womenspillar.blogspot.com/2009/03/saudi-arabia-frustrating-experience.html |work=Women's Issues in the Middle East (apparently reprinting an [[Arab News]] report) |agency=Arab News (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''') |date=11 March 2009}}</ref>). The stallkeeper had come from France, and said staffing the stall on the first day, which was men-only, was awkward, so she had gotten a male stand-in for the men-only days.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 /> On Friday the 6th (the fourth day), saleswomen were banned from the hall on men's days.<ref name=2009_jeans/> Women's access to the fair was expanded from two half-days.<ref name=\"events\" />\n\nThe religious police had a large stall, which did not sell books. It exhibited items they had confiscated, and screened a video presentation on how they reverse magic spells.<ref name=Saudiwoman_2009 />\n\n===2010===\nThe 2010 fair advertised family-only days (no single men) and four men-only evenings.<ref name=comsci/><ref name=\"schedule\">{{cite web |title=Riyadh-Book-Fair |url=http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/English/Pages/index.aspx |publisher=Ministry of Culture, Saudi Arabia |date=11 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111004916/http://riyadhbookfair.org.sa/sites/English/Pages/index.aspx |archive-date=11 January 2010 }} Original Ministry of Culture official schedule, '''not an independent source'''</ref> It was criticized for its website changing its URL annually and being hastily thrown up just before the fair with limited information and some technical problems.<ref name=comsci>{{cite web |title=Riyadh International Book Fair 2010, let's try this again |url=https://www.khaled.us/riyadh-international-book-fair-2010-lets-try-this-again.html |website=Khaled rambles |date=3 March 2010}}</ref><!--{{better source}}--> The presence of the religious police was much more muted in 2010 than in the previous year, including a smaller stall. Some stallholders were requiring official written notice that a book was banned before removing it from sale (rather than removing books on a verbal request from the religious police).<ref name=SW2010 /> Controversially, a women did the announcements over the public address system.<ref name=SW2010>{{cite web |title=Riyadh Book Fair 2010 |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2010/03/05/riyadh-book-fair-2010/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |date=5 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe children's area (in which men are not allowed) was greatly expanded, with more children's books, a reading area, a colouring area, a stage with regular performances, and, for mothers, screenings of films on child abuse and domestic violence.<ref name=SW2010/> The [[Saudi Human Rights Organization]], the [[Riyadh Orphanage]], the disabled association, a temporary museum exhibit, and other organizations had stalls just outside the exhibition hall.<ref name=SW2010/> There was a small but varied selection of English books.<ref name=SW2010/>\n\n[[Abdo Khal]]'s prizewinning<ref>{{cite news |title=But is it fiction? |url=https://al-bab.com/blog/2010/03/it-fiction-0 |work=al-bab.com |language=en}}</ref> novel ''[[Tarmi bi-Sharar]]'' (English title: ''Spewing Sparks as Big as Castles''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calderbank |first1=Tony |title=One Arabic-English translator shares his experience |url=https://www.britishcouncil.org/voices-magazine/arabic-english-translator-shares-experience |website=www.britishcouncil.org |language=en |agency=British Council}}</ref>) was withdrawn from the fair.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi writers find voice depicting closed society |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/922385 |work=dawn.com |date=22 June 2010 |language=en}}</ref> Books by activist [[Abdullah al-Hamed]] were confiscated.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia |url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2011/saudi-arabia |website=freedomhouse.org |language=en |date=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"history_2011\"></span>2011===\n[[File:Yousef Ziedan.jpg|thumb|[[Youssef Ziedan]] at a book-signing at the fair in 2011; his books were confiscated midway through the 2017 fair]]\nOn the second day<ref name=own /> of the fair, a group of men (30 according to one Saudi journalist,<ref name=theater /> dozens according to [[Agence France-Presse]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi hardliners disrupt book fair |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContentP/2/6883/World/Saudi-hardliners-disrupt-book-fair-.aspx |work=Ahram Online |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |language=en}}</ref> and over 500 according to [[Al Arabiya]]<ref name=alarabiya_2011 /> [a domestic, and thus government-controlled, news outlet]) appeared to co-ordinate a disruption, targeting writers, publishers, journalists, and female speakers.<ref name=numbers>{{cite news |title=Book Fair Updates: Riyadh Disrupted by Ultraconservatives, Report from Casablanca |url=https://arablit.org/2011/03/03/book-fair-updates-riyadh-disrupted-by-ultraconservatives-report-from-casablanca/ |work=& Arablit |date=3 March 2011 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=ghana /> Domestic media stated that they physically assaulted some participants, issued instructions on women's dress and behaviour over a loudspeaker,<ref name=own /> and harassed women, many of whom left.<ref name=Zee /> According to [[Al Arabiya]], one challenged [[Abdul Aziz Khoja]], the Minister of Culture and Information, on the selection of speakers, complaining that they were too liberal.<ref name=theater>{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Rob L. |title=Riyadh Book Fair Debacle is Nothing More Than Theater |url=https://mideastposts.com/middle-east-politics-analysis/riyadh-book-fair-debacle-is-nothing-more-than-theater/ |work=MidEast Posts}} ('''Not an independent source'''; [[Rob L. Wagner]], the author, was an editor at Saudi-government-controlled ''[[Arab News]]'' at the time of writing, and has long been employed in posts under Saudi government control.)</ref> Saudi media reported allegations that the men were Hai\u02bea members in [[Mufti (dress)|mufti]];<ref name=own>{{cite news |last1=Royston |first1=Steve |title=Sharp Divides Emerge over Saudi Reforms |url=https://mideastposts.com/showcase/saudi-arabia-%e2%80%93-the-case-for-reform/ |work=MidEast Posts}}</ref> a Hai\u02bea spokesman said the Hai\u02bea were not involved. Some were arrested (three, according to Sabq.org<ref name=Zee>{{cite news |title=Saudi hardliners disrupt book fair: Witnesses |url=https://zeenews.india.com/news/world/saudi-hardliners-disrupt-book-fair-witnesses_691074.html |work=Zee News |date=3 March 2011 |language=en}}</ref> and Al-bab.com,<ref name=thuggery>{{cite news |last1=Whitaker |first1=Brian |title=Thuggery at Saudi book fair |url=https://al-bab.com/blog/2011/03/thuggery-saudi-book-fair |work=al-bab.com |language=en | date=3 March 2011}}</ref> or 100, according to Al Arabiya, which also said that the remaining protestors staged a sit-in calling for their release<ref name=alarabiya_2011>{{cite news |title=Saudi conservatives stir row in a Riyadh book fair |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/03/03/140027.html |work=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0646\u062a |agency=Alarabiya |date=3 March 2011 |language=en}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>). The original source of information on this event is newspapers under the control of the Saudi government; as the government is a party to this dispute, there is a lack of independent reporting.\n\nOn the last day of the fair, a hailstorm lead to extensive leaks in the roof of the [[Riyadh Expo Center]], flooding the exhibition hall. [[Squeegee]]s were used to control the water. The flood forced many publishers to evacuate their sodden books.<ref>{{cite web |title=Riyadh |work=Khaled rambles |url=https://www.khaled.us/tag/riyadh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u062f \u064a\u0632\u0648\u0631 \u0645\u0639\u0631\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 |url=http://www.alriyadh.com/612912 |work=[[Al Riyadh (newspaper)]] \u062c\u0631\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 |date=2011-03-12 |language=ar}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\n[[Dar al-Jamal]], an Iraqi publisher, was banned.<ref name=ghana />\n\n===<span id=\"history_2012\"></span>2012===\nIn the lead-up to the fair, government authorities warned that only Hai\u02bea were allowed to deal with religious issues at the fair, and non-Hai\u02bea religious activists would be held accountable. This was in response to severe disruption at previous fairs.<ref name=louts>{{cite news |last1=Arabia |first1=Crossroads |title=Saudi Authorities Crack Down on 'Book Fair Louts' |url=https://mideastposts.com/middle-east-society/saudi-authorities-crack-down-on-book-fair-louts/ |work=MidEast Posts}}</ref> There was also an announcement that women and single men would be allowed to attend simultaneously,<ref name=ghana/> for the first time.<ref name=Freitag>{{cite news |last1=Freitag |first1=Ulrike |title=International Book Fair in Riyadh: Treading the Line between Censorship and Cautious Change |url=https://en.qantara.de/content/international-book-fair-in-riyadh-treading-the-line-between-censorship-and-cautious-change |work=Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World |language=en}}</ref> The Deputy Culture Minister promised that religious police would not harass women who did not cover their faces this year.<ref name=boycott>{{cite web |title=(Don't) Boycott the Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2012/03/10/dont-boycott-the-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |website=& Arablit |language=en |date=9 March 2012}}</ref> Security was heavy, likely in response to the previous year's disruption.<ref name=fatwa />\n\nA poll found that women at the fair sought socially-critical novels, followed by studies on social and political issues and religious self-help books. Surprisingly, the fair had many books on the challenges the [[Arab Spring]] presented to Saudi Arabia, which were very popular.<ref name=Freitag />\n\nOn 11 March 2012, five days after the 11-day fair opened, 70 Saudi clerics issued a [[fatwa]] criticizing the book fair. They complained that the fair was uncensored, and thus allowed perverted literature which encourages ideological anarchy, including texts undermining the truths of Islam, and discussing deviant and [[Paganism|pagan]] religions, sex, and various abominations. They also criticized the fair for being [[Women's rights in Saudi Arabia#Sex segregation|mixed-gender]].<ref name=fatwa /> Religious conservatives did not disrupt the fair as in 2011.<ref name=Freitag />\n\nSyrian publishers were banned.<ref name=ghana>{{cite news |last1=Abdallah |first1=Mariam |title=Censorship Rife at Riyadh Book Fair |url=https://newsghana.com.gh/censorship-rife-at-riyadh-book-fair/ |work=Ghana News}}</ref><ref name=boycott />\n\n===2013===\nThe [[Arab Publishers Association]] unanimously resolved to boycott the 2013 fair, citing the exclusion of Syrian publishers from the fair, but also the price of stall space and barcode system installation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saad |first1=Mohammed |title=Arab Publishers Association boycotts Riyadh Book Fair - Arab - Books |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/18/107/63432/Books/Arab/Arab-Publishers-Association-boycotts-Riyadh-Book-F.aspx |work=Ahram Online |date=29 January 2013 |language=en}}</ref> The barcode system was abandoned the same day in a tweet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Controversy Even Months Before Opening of 2013 Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2013/01/30/controvers/ |work=& Arablit |date=30 January 2013 |language=en}}</ref> About 500 publishers, local and international, participated in the fair.<ref name=Oman/>\n\nSales-tracking devices for publishers have been described as a reaction to under-the-counter sales of banned books.<ref name= memorandum />\n\nWomen and single men were again allowed to attend simultaneously, and the Hai\u02bea announced that they would only be reporting problematic books to the Ministry, not confiscating them themselves.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi women given unprecedented permit to attend book fairs - with men |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/News/65786.aspx |work=Ahram Online |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\n[[File:MahmoudDarwish.jpg|thumb|Mahmoud Darwish's poetry books were confiscated during the fair, on grounds of blasphemy]]\nOver 570 publishers, local and international, participated.<ref name=Oman/>\n\n420 books were banned at the 2014 fair, and 10,000 copies of them were confiscated. The bans were described as prompting readers to download the banned books.<ref name=2014_bans>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia bans prominent Palestinian authors from Riyadh book fair |url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Saudi-Arabia-bans-prominent-Palestinian-authors-from-Riyadh-book-fair-345533 |work=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com}}</ref><ref name=downloads>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: 420 books banned at Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://freemuse.org/news/saudi-arabia-420-books-banned-at-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |website=Freemuse |date=18 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe late Palestinian poet [[Mahmoud Darwish]]'s books were confiscated during the fair, after the stall was surrounded by protesters. There were also complaints from religious police and allegations that the poems contained blasphemous passages.<ref name=protest>{{cite news |last1=Flood |first1=Alison |title=Saudi book fair bans 'blasphemous' Mahmoud Darwish works after protest |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/14/saudi-book-fair-bans-mahmoud-darwish-blasphemy |work=The Guardian |date=14 March 2014}}</ref> Similar actions were taken against works by well-known poets [[Badr Shaker al-Sayyab]], [[Abdul Wahab al-Bayati]], and [[Muin Bseiso]].<ref name=widerange /><ref name=2014_bans/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/robert-sharp/no-ambassador-its-not-med_b_7602740.html|archive-url=https://www.robertsharp.co.uk/2015/06/18/no-ambassador-its-not-meddling-to-call-for-free-speech-in-saudi-arabia/|archive-date=18 June 2015|title=No, Ambassador: It's Not 'Meddling' to Call for Free Speech in Saudi Arabia|website=HuffPost UK}}</ref>\n\nThe Arab Network for Research and Publishing, arriving at the former location of their stall on the Friday morning of the 2014 fair, found that it had been dismantled overnight, with their books confiscated, their materials scattered on the floor just outside, and the signage on their stall replaced by signage naming another publisher.<ref name=rocket /><ref name=booted>{{cite news |title=Saudi Publisher Booted From Riyadh International Book Fair |url=https://arablit.org/2014/03/12/saudi-publisher-booted-from-riyadh-international-book-fair/ |work=& Arablit |date=12 March 2014 |language=en}}</ref> The group's publishing focusses on nonfiction<ref name=booted /> about Saudi Arabia and political Islam. The books had been pre-approved, and most were sold in previous years; the reversal of the decision was attributed to the tenser political situation. The publisher was reportedly permanently banned from the fair.<ref name=rocket /><ref name=al-monitor>{{cite news |last1=Al-Rasheed |first1=Madawi |title=Saudi officials shut down display at book fair |url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/saudi-book-display-shut-down.html |work=Al-Monitor |date=13 March 2014 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=booted />\n\n[[Azmi Bishara]]'s books were also banned amid escalating tensions with Qatar.<ref name=widerange>{{cite news |title=Saudi bans books at fair in wide-ranging crackdown |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/2/8/96807/World/Region/Saudi-bans-books-at-fair-in-wideranging-crackdown.aspx |work=Ahram Online |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|date=16 March 2014 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=2014_bans /> Other banned books included ''[[Revolution 2.0]]'', by [[Wael Ghonim]], ''[[When will the Saudi Woman Drive a Car?]]'' by [[Abdullah Al Alami]],<ref name=crackdown>{{cite news |title=Saudi bans books at fair in crackdown |url=https://www.emirates247.com/news/region/saudi-bans-books-at-fair-in-crackdown-2014-03-16-1.541790 |work=www.emirates247.com |language=en}}</ref> and ''[[Al Estbdad]]'' (\"The Tyranny\"), by [[Ahmed bin Hamad al-Khalili]], the [[Grand Mufti]] of [[Oman]].<ref name=Oman>{{cite news |title=Riyadh fair bans Oman writer's book |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/oman/riyadh-fair-bans-oman-writers-book-1.1297227 |work=gulfnews.com |language=en}}</ref> The titles ''[[The History of Hijab]]'' and ''[[Feminism in Islam (book)|Feminism in Islam]]'' were also banned.<ref name=crackdown/>\n\n[[Madeha al-Ajroush]], a photographer and activist who campaigned for womens' right to drive, had an aisle at the fair named after her. The fair also featured a book on the driving protests, ''[[Sixth of November]]'', by [[Aisha al-Mana]] and [[Hissa al-Sheikh]].<ref name=Sixth>{{cite web |title=Sixth of November at the Riyadh Book Fair |url=https://saudiwoman.me/2014/03/13/sixth-of-november-at-the-riyadh-book-fair/ |website=Saudiwoman's Weblog |language=en |date=13 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\n<!--The fair featured clowns for children and mobile ATM machines to reduce lineups.<ref name=Sudhnoti>{{cite web |title=Visit to International Book Fair: #Riyadh |url=https://publicawaz.blogspot.com/2015/03/visit-to-international-book-fair-riyadh.html |website=Voice of Sudhnoti |date=14 March 2015}}</ref>{{better source needed}} (this isn't a notable blogger) -->\nSales of the compilation book ''On the meaning of Arab Nationalism: Concepts & Challenges'' were permitted at the fair, but banned outside the fair.<ref name=memorandum /> Hai\u02bea presence was less conspicuous this year.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nA seminar entitled \"Youth and Arts... A Call for Coexistence\" was stopped by religious police after professor [[Mojab al-Zahrani]] condemned the destruction of monuments by the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref name=idols>{{cite web |title=KSA: Members of the Saudi Religious Police (CPVPV \u2013 The Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice) Attacks a Seminar About Destroying Monuments |url=http://anhri.net/?p=141845&lang=en |date=9 March 2015 |agency=[[Arabic Network for Human Rights Information]]}}</ref><ref name=mixed_bag>{{cite web |title=The 2015 Riyadh International Book Fair: A Mixed Bag |url=https://arablit.org/2015/03/17/the-2015-riyadh-international-book-fair-a-mixed-bag/ |website=& Arablit |language=en |date=17 March 2015}}</ref> They accused the speaker of [[idolatry]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whitaker |first1=Brian |title=Where literary meets military |url=https://al-bab.com/blog/2016/03/where-literary-meets-military |work=al-bab.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe fair ended with a statement that anyone distributing printed materials, books or videos to visitors without prior authorization would face questioning by security authorities.<ref name=mixed_bag/>\n\n===2016===\n[[File:Villagers scour rubble for belongings scattered during the bombing of Hajar Aukaish - Yemen - in April 2015.jpg|thumb|The war in Yemen was a major theme of the 2016 fair]]\nThe 2016 fair was noted for its military themes, centered around the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]]<ref name=memorandum /> (which began in 2015). The Minister also praised the theater in his opening speech.<ref name=memorandum />\n\nThe opening day was noted for its international and rich local guests, and a temporary relaxation of gender segregation and women's dress codes, tightened again for the following days.<ref name=memorandum /> A Kuwaiti author was told not to smile, as this showed his dimples, which were considered seductive.<ref name=dimples>{{cite news |title=Liberated Saudi Youth Wonder Where All the Wahhabis Have Gone |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-14/liberated-saudi-youth-wonder-where-all-the-wahhabis-have-gone |work=Bloomberg Businessweek}}</ref><ref name=idols />\n\nThe US government was questioned about praise its diplomats gave the fair in light of anti-semitic texts on sale. The fair also included misogynistic books, such as ''[[Women Who Deserve to go to Hell]]'' by Mansour Abdel Hakim.<ref name=US-backed>{{cite news |last1=Speyer |first1=Lea |title=Human Rights Organization: Antisemitic Literature at US-Backed Riyadh Book Fair a 'Tragedy for the Jewish People' |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2016/04/05/human-rights-organization-antisemitic-literature-at-us-backed-riyadh-book-fair-a-tragedy-for-the-jewish-people/ |work=Algemeiner.com}}</ref><ref name=2016_report>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.state.gov/reports/2016-report-on-international-religious-freedom/saudi-arabia/ |website=United States Department of State}}</ref> The [[US State Department]] later condemned the anti-semitic books and other hate speech, distancing itself from the fair.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Speyer |first1=Lea |title=State Department Denies Knowledge of Antisemitic Material at Saudi Book Fair Attended by US Embassy Reps (Video) |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2016/04/06/state-department-denies-knowledge-of-antisemitic-material-at-saudi-book-fair-attended-by-us-embassy-reps-video/ |work=Algemeiner.com}}</ref>\n\nElectronic tracking of books was implemented in an attempt to prevent under-the-counter sales of unapproved books.<ref name=idols />\n\n''[[Journey to a Land Not Ruled By Allah]]'', by [[Ibrahim al-Tamimi]], was reported banned after conservatives [[Twitter|tweeted]] objections to it using the \"Campaign Against Atheist Accounts\" hashtag.<ref name=2016_report /> The fair's selection tended towards academic and technical subjects, avoiding books on sex, politics, and religion.<ref name=memorandum />\n\n===2017===\n[[Youssef Ziedan]]'s books were confiscated midway through the 2017 fair, which he attributed to his mention of the disputed Red Sea islands of [[Tiran Island|Tiran]] and [[Sanafir Island|Sanafir]].<ref name=muse />\n\n12 students of the Sekolah Seni Malaysia Johor Art School, performing a Malaysian folk dance, were interrupted by a heckler; other spectators told the heckler to leave the students alone. The religious police took prompt action and stopped the performance.<ref name=muse>{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: Books banned, performance interrupted at book fair |url=https://freemuse.org/news/saudi-arabia-books-banned-performance-interrupted-book-fair/ |website=Freemuse}}</ref> A young Malaysian painted murals during the event.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alnufaie |first1=Hanan |title=Young Malaysian painter wins Saudi hearts at Riyadh Book Fair |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/art-and-culture/2017/03/17/Young-Malaysian-painter-wins-Saudi-hearts-at-Riyadh-Book-Fair-.html |work=english.alarabiya.net |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"history_2018\"></span>2018===\nHeld months after [[Women driving in Saudi Arabia|women were legally permitted to drive]], the fair featured a booth with a driving simulator for women.<ref name=economist>{{cite news |title=The red ink and the black: The unlikely rise of book fairs in the Gulf |url=https://www.economist.com/books-and-arts/2019/07/06/the-unlikely-rise-of-book-fairs-in-the-gulf |work=The Economist|date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nA publisher's stall was closed down, and the publisher banned from participating in the fair forever, for selling [[Muslim Brotherhood]] books, on grounds that these incited violence and terrorism.<ref name=algemeiner /> This was criticised; Jamal Khashoggi wrote: \"Liberals whose work was once censored or banned by [[Wahhabi]] hard-liners have turned the tables: They now ban what they see as hard-line, such as the censorship of various books at the Riyadh International Book Fair last month. One may applaud such an about-face. But shouldn't we aspire to allow the marketplace of ideas to be open?\"<ref name=blame>{{cite news |last1=Khashoggi |first1=Jamal |title=By blaming 1979 for Saudi Arabia's problems, the crown prince is peddling revisionist history |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/04/03/by-blaming-1979-for-saudi-arabias-problems-the-crown-prince-is-peddling-revisionist-history/ |work=Washington Post |date=3 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] documented the display of antisemitic conspiracy texts at the fair, and requested that texts that inflame hatred against Jews be treated in the same manner as the Muslim Brotherhood texts were.<ref name=algemeiner>{{cite web |title=Saudi Book Fair Called Out for Display of Antisemitic Titles, Including ''Mein Kampf'' |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2018/03/25/saudi-book-fair-called-out-for-display-of-antisemitic-titles-including-mein-kampf/ |website=Algemeiner.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wiesenthal Centre to Saudi Culture Minister: \"We are Distressed to Discover Vicious Antisemitic Conspiracy Texts on Display at the Riyadh Book Fair\" |url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/about/news/wiesenthal-centre-to-saudi.html |website=www.wiesenthal.com}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\n[[File:College of Law and Political Science (3) by Qrmoo3.jpg|thumb|The College of Law and Political Science at [[King Saud University]]; [[Anas al-Mazrou]], who was arrested shortly after speaking at the fair, lectured here]]\n<!--The 2019 fair took place at Riyadh International Convention and Exhibition Center, according to government-controlled media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1518681/saudi-arabia|title=Cultural minister: Riyadh book fair to kick off in April|date=2019-07-01|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-06}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>-->\n\n[[Anas al-Mazrou]], a law professor at [[King Saud University]], was arrested for speaking of the [[2018\u20132019 Saudi crackdown on feminists|detention of women's rights activists]] in Saudi Arabia during one of these panel discussions at the 2019 fair.<ref name=arrest>{{cite web |last1=Safi |first1=Michael |title=Saudi Arabia: arrests of dissidents and torture allegations continue |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/04/saudi-arabia-mass-arrests-of-dissidents-and-torture-allegations-continue |website=The Guardian |date=4 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi law professor arrested for criticising kingdom's human rights record: Report |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-law-professor-arrested-criticising-kingdoms-human-rights-record-report |work=Middle East Eye |language=en}}</ref> \"No one dares to ask, and I am not challenging anybody, including those who are sitting here on stage, to ask about the human rights activists,\" he said. He named four people as having \"contributed to spread the idea of human rights... I will give you an idea and I invite everybody to think about it; the idea of the nation being the guardian of itself, [such that the guardian] is the people, not the ruler\"<ref name=anas_quote>Translated quotation from ''The New York Times'': {{cite news |last1=Yee |first1=Vivian |last2=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |title=Saudis Escalate Crackdown on Dissent, Arresting Nine and Risking U.S. Ire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/05/world/middleeast/american-detainees-saudi-arabia.html |work=The New York Times |date=5 April 2019}}</ref> No information was given on where he was taken,<ref>{{cite web |title=Fresh wave of arrests in Saudi Arabia |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/04/saudi-arabia-new-wave-of-arrests-and-travel-bans-latest-assault-on-freedom-of-expression/ |website=www.amnesty.org |language=en}}</ref> and was described on 9 September as having had no contact with his family during this detainment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0631 Alnajjar |first1=\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0645\u0647 Omaima |title=Anas al-Mazrou |url=https://alqst.org/eng/amo-team/anas-al-mazrou/ |publisher=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0633\u0637 ALQST |language=en-US-QST | date=9 September 2019 | access-date= 21 March 2020}}</ref> The video{{efn|The video may be seen [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v&#61;WV3bbNq7Ma4 here] (Youtube).}} went [[viral video|viral]].<ref name=viral>{{cite news |last1=Qiblawi |first1=Tamara |title=Two US citizens arrested in first Saudi arrest sweep since Khashoggi killing, sources say |url=http://www.kabc.com/2019/04/05/two-us-citizens-arrested-in-first-saudi-arrest-sweep-since-khashoggi-killing-sources-say/ |work=KABC-AM |agency=CNN |date=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Simon Wiesenthal Center again complained that the fair sold anti-semitic texts, including Hitler's ''[[Mein Kampf]]''. They said that \"Of the six Arab Book Fairs we annually monitor, antisemitic texts are sadly the most numerous in Riyadh\", and asked the Saudi government to apply the same measures to \"all forms of hate, on the same level as offences to Islam\".<ref name=JerusalemPost>{{cite news |title=''Mein Kampf'' and antisemitic books found at Saudi Arabia book fair |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Jewish-rights-group-decries-sale-of-Nazi-books-at-Saudi-book-fair-585431 |work=The Jerusalem Post|date=1 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wiesenthal Centre to Saudi Media Minister: \"Ban Antisemitic Hate at the Riyadh International Book Fair\" |url=http://www.wiesenthal.com/about/news/2019_03_31_wiesenthal-centre-to-saudi.html |website=www.wiesenthal.com}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nIn July 2019, the Saudi Ministry of Culture announced that the 2020 fair would be held from 2 to 11 April<ref name=plans_2020>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abouther.com/node/20866/people/events/saudi-arabias-ministry-culture-announces-riyadh-book-fair-plans-2020|title=Saudi Arabia's Ministry of Culture Announces Riyadh Book Fair Plans for 2020|date=2019-07-16|website=About Her|language=en|access-date=2019-08-06}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref> at 'Riyadh Front'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arab.news/rpa4s|title=Saudi Culture Ministry chooses 'Riyadh Front' as book fair's new headquarters|date=2020-01-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-11}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref> However, on 5 March, the Ministry announced that the fair was postponed, as a precaution against [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the worldwide outbreak]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2165611/riyadh-intl-book-fair-postponed-over-coronavirus-fears|title=Riyadh Int'l Book Fair Postponed over Coronavirus Fears|website=Asharq Al-awsat|author-link=Asharq Al-Awsat|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}} (Saudi-government-controlled media, and thus '''not an independent source''')</ref>\n\n<!--== Guest of Honour ==\n{{Third-party|section}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year \n!Guest \n|-\n|2019\n|Bahrain<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1466481/saudi-arabia|title=Riyadh book fair opens with Bahrain as guest of honor|date=2019-03-14|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|UAE<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1465866/saudi-arabia|title=Riyadh book fair starts 10-day run|date=2019-03-12|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|Malasiya<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1052131/saudi-arabia|title=Malaysia Guest-of-Honor at Riyadh International Book Fair 2017|date=2017-02-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|Greece<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/news/892966|title=Al-Toraifi opens Riyadh Book Fair 2016|date=2016-03-10|website=Arab News|language=en|access-date=2019-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Inauguration Ceremony of the 2015 Riyadh International Book Fair - News |url=htt